{"title_page": "2007 Christmas violence in Kandhamal", "text_new": "{{short description|Anti- Christian violence in Orissa}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title            = 2007 Christmas violence in Kandhamal\n| subtitle         = \n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| date             =December 24, 2007 - December 27, 2007 (4 days) \n| place            = [[Kandhamal District]], [[Orissa]]\n| coordinates      = \n| causes           =[[Hate Speech]], [[Religious Nationalism]], [[Ethnic nationalism]], [[Ethnic hatred|Ethnic tensions]] \n| goals            = \n| methods          =[[Arson]], [[murder]], [[looting]] \n| status           = \n| result           = \n| side1            = \n| side2            = \n| side3            = \n| side4            = \n| leadfigures1     = \n| leadfigures2     = \n| leadfigures3     = \n| leadfigures4     = \n| howmany1         = \n| howmany2         = \n| howmany3         = \n| howmany4         = \n| casualties1      = \n| casualties2      = \n| casualties3      = \n| casualties4      = \n| fatalities       =3-50\n| injuries         =\n| arrests          =\n| detentions       =\n| charged          =\n| fined            =\n| effect           =*100+ Churches burnt down, demolished or vandalized\n*100+ Christian institutions burnt down or vandalized\n*837+ familes left homeless\n*700-730 houses (120 belonging to Hindus) were burnt or damaged\n| effect_label     =Damages\n| casualties_label =Casualties and Damages \n| notes            = \n| sidebox          = \n}}\nThe '''2007 Christmas violence in Kandhamal violence''' refers to the violence that occurred during the Christmas of 2007 between the groups led by [[Sangh Parivar]] together with the Sangh-affiliated Kui Samaj and the Christians in the Kandhamal district of Orissa.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Das|first=Sib Kumar|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/kandhamal-rises-above-violent-past-on-christmas/article30398875.ece|title=Kandhamal rises above violent past on Christmas|date=2019-12-26|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrang.com/cc/archive/2008/jan08/cover2.html|title=Kandhamal: Hindutva\u2019s terror {{!}} Charting the history of sangh parivar violence in Orissa|last=CHATTERJI|first=ANGANA|date=January 2008|website=[[Communalism Combat]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2007/12/29/india-stop-hindu-christian-violence-orissa|title=India: Stop Hindu-Christian Violence in Orissa|last=Human Rights Watch|first=|date=2007-12-29|website=Human Rights Watch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Violence started on December 24th and ended on December 27th of 2007, Violence first broke out on December 24 during an altercation between Hindus and Christians over Christmas celebrations where a mob of 500-3000 members led by various Sangh Parivar organizations desecrated several Christmas decorations and injured many Christians. On the same day an alleged attack on Lakshmanananda Saraswati and his driver by some Christians after some of his body-guards allegedly vandalized church equipment.\n\nClashes between the Kui samaj which protested the tribal status to the Christians together with groups led by [[Vishva Hindu Parishad|Vishwa Hindu Parishad]], [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|Rashtriya Swayamswvak Sangh]], [[Bajrang Dal]] and the [[Vanavasi Kalyan Ashram]] against the Christians erupted after these incidents, where more than 100 churches and Church institutions, 700 houses were burnt down, vandalized or damaged. During the final days of the riots there was also a Christian retaliation in which Christian mobs burnt down about 120 houses of Hindus at different places in the district.\n\nThe official death toll suggested 3 Christians were killed but other reports put the death toll to nearly 50. \n== Background ==\n\n=== Kandha\u2013Pana tensions ===\nThe [[kandhamal district]] is home more than 100,000 Christians where 60% of them converted from the [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Castes]] (SC) and are locally called as the Pana Christians (Pana). They were dalits and they speak [[Kui language (India)|Kui language]] like tribal Kandhas. The district has been ethnically divided for decades between the tribal Kui-speaking Kandha tribals, and lower caste Kui-speaking Christian Panas, who occupy a dominant position in their society. The \"Kui Samaj\" which is a Sangh-affiliated tribal organization, claimed to represent all the Kandha tribals, who were nearly 52% of the population in the district.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=29}} According to the Constitution, the reservation benefits are removed from the SCs after conversion but the Pana Christians demanded the [[Scheduled Tribe|Scheduled tribe]] (ST) status after the Presidential Order of 2002 which mentioned the Kui tribes in the ST category since they also speak the kui language. This was opposed by the [[Vishva Hindu Parishad|Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] (VHP) and the Kui Association and other political leaders who depend on Hindu tribals to support their vote bank in the area. These tensions soon transformed into communal.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-18808|title=Ethnic Violence and Communal Polarisation in Orissa's Kandhamal District|date=2008-01-12|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/quota-fuel-to-communal-fire/story-EbGKLcCsHYwcGIVVSpNaZL.html|title=Quota fuel to communal fire|date=2008-12-31|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/671529854|title=Margins of faith : Dalit and tribal Christianity in India|date=2010|publisher=Sage Publications|others=Robinson, Rowena, 1967-, Kuj\u016bra, Josepha Mariy\u0101nusa., Kuj\u03b3\u0310\u01b0ura, Josepha Mariy\u03b3\u0310\u01b0anusa.|year=|isbn=978-81-321-0604-3|location=New Delhi, India|pages=271-274|oclc=671529854}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/tribals-hold-key-to-peace/story-mqHbpz5mquA5dHGQZfiAcM.html|title=Tribals hold key to peace|date=2008-12-19|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Communalism Combat|Communalism combat]] blamed the sangh parivar in orchestrating rivalries between Kandhas and the Christian Panas in Kandhamal through Hinduization and polarising the Kandhas ties with the panas and instigating the Kandhas against the latter's campaign for a scheduled status as a tribe.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Christmas tensions ===\nDuring the last days of the 2007 Christmas, the Dalit Pana Christians were constructing a cloth-draped [[pandal]]{{angle bracket|a temporary decorative scaffolding}} for the Christiams clebrations, over-topping a main-street in the town of Brahmanigaon after receiving permission for the construction from the authorities. The pandal which had been constructed on the same spot for number of years was warned to be removed this year by some local Hindus because it was located in the same area where a recent Durga Puja clebrations took place. On, December 23rd, [[Narendra Modi]] was celebrating his re-election as chief minister in Gujarat. The activists of the Sangh-affiliated Kui Samaj who had a strained relationship with the Pana Christians called for a Statewide [[bandh]]{{angle bracket|shutdown}} on December 24th and December 25th of 2007 to protest against granting of  the ST caste status to the SC Pana Christians allegly with the support of the.<ref name=\":4\" /> Christians were also warned not to put-up Christmas decorations due to the fact that some Hindus also celebrated Christmas along with them. Due to these tensions several Christian groups asked for extra police protection for their Christmas celebrations.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=265}}\n\nDespite the Kui Samaj's call for the Statewide bandh, the police opened the local market on December 24th at about 7 a.m in Brahmanigaon after recommendation by some christian groups for their Christmas preparations. About two hours late a large group allegedly led by a local RSS leader, Bikram Rout, arrived in the market and attempted to forcefully shut it down but the police kept it open. Later scuffles started between the Hindu and the Christian merchants after the group led by the RSS leader allegedly roughed up with some Christians in the market and the market was eventually closed down.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=265}}\n\n=== Lakshmanananda Saraswati ===\nOn December 24th, at about 10.45 am, Lakshmanananda Saraswati, while travelling to the town of Brahmanigaon for a yagna ritual in his car was forced to stop after a bus broke down in front of his vehicle. Hearing Christmas music coming from a nearby church, he sent his bodyguards to ask it to be turned down. His body guards allegedly roughed up on some Christians and vandalized the Church equipments. Saraswati claimed that a group of Christians injured him and his driver and damaged his car, while eye-witnesses and doctor's statements said that he did not appear seriously hurt.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=25}} Yet, pictures of him, lying in a hospital bed were circulated widely in the internet and in the news reports. The RSS, Bajrang Dal, Vishwa Hindu Parishad and the Bhartiya Janata Party called for a 4-hour bandh on the Christmas day following the incident.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=266}} This led to the communal tensions in the area.{{Sfn|Bauman|2015|p=53}}<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/892641/in-photos-damaged-churches-broken-homes-are-the-lingering-scars-of-the-2008-kandhamal-riots|title=In photos: Damaged churches, broken homes are the lingering scars of the 2008 Kandhamal riots|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ncds.nic.in/sites/default/files/WorkingandOccasionalPapers/WP64NCDS.pdf|title=Dialogue, Sacrifice and Reconciliation:A Study of Kandhamal Violence, Odisha|last=Patnaik|first=Arun K|last2=Bag|first2=Rajesh|date=January 2016|website=Nabakrushna Choudhury Centre for Development Studies,Bhubaneswar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Other incidents leading up to the riots ===\nOn December 23, Hindutva-associated tribal organisations reportedly organized a rally with slogans of 'Stop Christianity, Kill Christians' with the support of Sangh Parivar groups.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=23}}\n\nOn December 23, Hindutva activists organized a ritual to convert Pastor Digal from the Kutikia gram panchayat along with 12 members of the Christian community. He was beaten, brutally tortured and paraded naked as he refused to renounce Christianity.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=24-25}}\n\n== Riots ==\nViolent clashes occurred from 24th to 27th of December 2007 between people led by the Sangh Parivar groups, the Sangh- affiliated Kui Samaj and the Christians.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAround 10 a.m on December 24th, a mob of around 500 people led again by the RSS leader, Bikram Rout ransacked the pandal and set it on fire in-front of the onlooking police. The mob then went on to destroy Christian shops and attack Christians. Gun-shots were fired, a boy was severely wounded, many Christians fled to the near-by jungles out of fear.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=266}} While other reports suggest more than 3000 people belonging to Vishwa Hindu Parishad, RSS, Bajrang Dal and the [[Vanavasi Kalyan Ashram]] started to vandalize Christian symbols and two young boys suffered gun injuries. The Church of the lady of Lourdes was decimated.This occurred before Laksmananda was attacked.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=25}}\n\nOn 25th December, Six Churches were set ablaze after the Christians were chased out. The Violence continued as the members of each community clashed with each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/in-india-churches-torched-on-christmas/|title=In India, Churches Torched On Christmas|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 26th December, clashes continued all over the district, multiple houses were attacked and many were left injured, a Police Station in Phiringia was set on fire. Police was found it difficult to reach the violence hit areas in the villages as protesters obstructed roads by blocking it with trees. Chief Minister [[Naveen Patnaik]] held two rounds of meetings with senior officials to review the situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2007/dec/26orissa.htm|title=Orissa: Fresh violence in curfew-bound areas|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/AdvisoryCom/PostDisaster/OdishaForumForActionReport.pdf#page=2|title=An Assessment of Damage and Loss of Private Property during the Anti-Christian Violence in Kandhamal, India|last=|first=|date=|website=Centre for the Sustainable Use of Natural and Social Resources|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nOn 27th December, Dozens of Churches were ransacked and razed in the areas of  Nuagaon, G Udaygiri  Phulbani Sadar and Brahmanigaon. A a Congress parliamentarian's house was also attacked by the Saffron activists and the Kui tribals, opposing tribal status to the Pana Christians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2007/dec/27church.htm|title=Twelve more churches razed in Orissa|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> A Christian retaliation also took place as a Christian mob entered the Hindu quarter of Brahmanigaon and set fire to about hundred homes. Similarly a Christian mob set fire to an additional twenty homes near Gadapur. On the Same day the rioting had stopped.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=267}}\n\n== Total casualties and damages ==\nInitial governmental reports suggested that more than 100 churches and church institutions, including hostels, convents and about 700 houses and other structures were burnt in the riots and three persons killed(all Christians).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orissapost.com/3706-acquitted-in-kandhamal-riots/|title=3,706 acquitted in Kandhamal riots - OrissaPOST|date=2020-01-24|website=Odisha News, Odisha Latest news, Odisha Daily - OrissaPOST|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> More than 837 familes were left homless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrangindia.in/article/flashback-kandhamal-targeted-violence-against-christians-9-years-later|title=A Flashback to Kandhamal Targeted Violence against Christians, 9 Years Later|date=2017-08-24|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nA report by the [[National Commission for Minorities]], suggested more than 730 houses were destroyed and 95 churches were burnt.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=267}}\n\nThe Communalism combat reported 85-95 Christian institutions were burnt down, vandalized or damaged additionally to the reported damages.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAll India Christian Council (AICC) study team stated that in December 2007, Hindu nationalists murdered a total of 50 Christians, destroyed 730 housing units and 95 churches.\u00a0In the numerous relief camps set up by State government, hundreds of displaced Christians were made to stay.<ref name=\"worldwatchmonitor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldwatchmonitor.org/2008/02-February/newsarticle_5210.html/|title=Maoists Said to Recruit Victims of Violence|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124132712/https://www.worldwatchmonitor.org/2008/02-February/newsarticle_5210.html/|archive-date=24 November 2015|accessdate=2015-08-27|newspaper=www.worldwatchmonitor.org|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe general secretary of the Kandhamal district's Christian Endeavour Union, suggested that 100 houses belonging to Christians were burnt in Godapur, Brahmanigaon, Barakhama, and some other villages on 26 and 27 December 2007. He also visited Godapur and Brahmanigaon  villages to take a look of the situation, and suspected that these houses were burnt sown by sections of \"Hinditva Activists\" who may have been incited by the Maoists.<ref>[http://www.compassdirect.org/en/display.php?page=news&lang=en&length=long&idelement=5210 INDIA: MAOISTS SAID TO RECRUIT VICTIMS OF VIOLENCE] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222000553/http://www.compassdirect.org/en/display.php?page=news&lang=en&length=long&idelement=5210|date=22 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Ndtv.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/news/ngo-maoist-link-in-kandhamal/21988|title=NGO-Maoist link in Kandhamal|last=|date=|accessdate=2015-08-27|newspaper=Ndtv.com}}</ref>\n\n== Investigations ==\nMany members of the Hindu community have claimed that Christian show of religiosity, and the financial privilege that enabled such an exhibition, contributed to the rioting.<ref name=\":1\" /> While some Hindu organisations suggested that disturbances were the result of ethnic tensions in the area, mainly between the Dalit Pana community and the Adivasi Kandhas.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIndependent experts also found, in terms of violence and planning across mountainous areas, that that violence was orchestrated and the police had prior information about the Hindutva organisations planning to riot. It should also be remembered that the celebration of his party's 10th anniversary by Chief Minister [[Naveen Patnaik]] coincided with the turmoil. The celebration demanded that a significant number of the state police forces be relocated from districts to Bhubaneswar, the state capital. The police found it challenging to react to the developing situation in Kandhamal between 24 and 25 December.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nHindutva Organizations accused that the violent uprising of Hindus stemmed from Christian conversions and actions of Maoist organizations, resulting in the Kandhamal riots of 2007 even though the Maoist parties are not present in the places in which violence has arisen, even though sangh parivar organisations have seen a increase in these same places in recent years.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{Cite book|last=Robinson|first=Rowena|url=https://searchworks.stanford.edu/view/8794295|title=Margins of faith : Dalit and tribal Christianity in India|date=2010|publisher=Sage Publications|others=Joseph Marianus Kujur|year=2010|isbn=978-81-321-0604-3|location=New Delhi, India|pages=|oclc=671529854|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=JPDC|first=Justice, Peace and Development Commission (JPDC)(Bhubaneswar, India)|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/294883231|title=Faith under fire|date=2008|publisher=Media House|others=|year=2008|isbn=81-7495-320-5|location=Delhi|pages=|oclc=294883231|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Bauman|first=Chad M.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/888554934|title=Pentecostals, proselytization, and anti-Christian violence in contemporary India|publisher=Oxford University Press, 2015|year=2015|isbn=978-0-19-020210-1|location=New York, NY|pages=|oclc=888554934|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Violence against Christians in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Christian sentiment in Asia]]\n[[Category:Hate crimes]]\n[[Category:Attacks on churches in Asia]]\n[[Category:Hindu nationalism]]\n[[Category:Persecution by Hindus]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Christians]]\n[[Category:Sectarian violence]]\n[[Category:Hinduism-motivated violence in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Anti- Christian violence in Orissa}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title            = 2007 Christmas violence in Kandhamal\n| subtitle         = \n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| date             =December 24, 2007 - December 27, 2007 (4 days) \n| place            = [[Kandhamal District]], [[Orissa]]\n| coordinates      = \n| causes           =[[Hate Speech]], [[Religious Nationalism]], [[Ethnic nationalism]], [[Ethnic hatred|Ethnic tensions]] \n| goals            = \n| methods          =[[Arson]], [[murder]], [[looting]] \n| status           = \n| result           = \n| side1            = \n| side2            = \n| side3            = \n| side4            = \n| leadfigures1     = \n| leadfigures2     = \n| leadfigures3     = \n| leadfigures4     = \n| howmany1         = \n| howmany2         = \n| howmany3         = \n| howmany4         = \n| casualties1      = \n| casualties2      = \n| casualties3      = \n| casualties4      = \n| fatalities       =3-50\n| injuries         =\n| arrests          =\n| detentions       =\n| charged          =\n| fined            =\n| effect           =*100+ Churches burnt down, demolished or vandalized\n*100+ Christian institutions burnt down or vandalized\n*837+ familes left homeless\n*700-730 houses (120 belonging to Hindus) were burnt or damaged\n| effect_label     =Damages\n| casualties_label =Casualties and Damages \n| notes            = \n| sidebox          = \n}}\nThe '''2007 Christmas violence in Kandhamal violence''' refers to the violence that occurred during the Christmas of 2007 between the the groups led by [[Sangh Parivar]] together with the Sangh-affiliated Kui Samaj and the Christians in the Kandhamal district of Orissa.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Das|first=Sib Kumar|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/kandhamal-rises-above-violent-past-on-christmas/article30398875.ece|title=Kandhamal rises above violent past on Christmas|date=2019-12-26|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrang.com/cc/archive/2008/jan08/cover2.html|title=Kandhamal: Hindutva\u2019s terror {{!}} Charting the history of sangh parivar violence in Orissa|last=CHATTERJI|first=ANGANA|date=January 2008|website=[[Communalism Combat]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2007/12/29/india-stop-hindu-christian-violence-orissa|title=India: Stop Hindu-Christian Violence in Orissa|last=Human Rights Watch|first=|date=2007-12-29|website=Human Rights Watch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Violence started on December 24th and ended on December 27th of 2007, Violence first broke out on December 24 during an altercation between Hindus and Christians over Christmas celebrations where a mob of 500-3000 members led by various Sangh Parivar organizations desecrated several Christmas decorations and injured many Christians. On the same day an alleged attack on Lakshmanananda Saraswati and his driver by some Christians after some of his body-guards allegedly vandalized church equipment.\n\nClashes between the Kui samaj which protested the tribal status to the Christians together with groups led by [[Vishva Hindu Parishad|Vishwa Hindu Parishad]], [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|Rashtriya Swayamswvak Sangh]], [[Bajrang Dal]] and the [[Vanavasi Kalyan Ashram]] against the Christians erupted after these incidents, where more than 100 churches and Church institutions, 700 houses were burnt down, vandalized or damaged. During the final days of the riots there was also a Christian retaliation in which Christian mobs burnt down about 120 houses of Hindus at different places in the district.\n\nThe official death toll suggested 3 Christians were killed but other reports put the death toll to nearly 50. \n== Background ==\n\n=== Kandha\u2013Pana tensions ===\nThe [[kandhamal district]] is home more than 100,000 Christians where 60% of them converted from the [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Castes]] (SC) and are locally called as the Pana Christians (Pana). They were dalits and they speak [[Kui language (India)|Kui language]] like tribal Kandhas. The district has been ethnically divided for decades between the tribal Kui-speaking Kandha tribals, and lower caste Kui-speaking Christian Panas, who occupy a dominant position in their society. The \"Kui Samaj\" which is a Sangh-affiliated tribal organization, claimed to represent all the Kandha tribals, who were nearly 52% of the population in the district.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=29}} According to the Constitution, the reservation benefits are removed from the SCs after conversion but the Pana Christians demanded the [[Scheduled Tribe|Scheduled tribe]] (ST) status after the Presidential Order of 2002 which mentioned the Kui tribes in the ST category since they also speak the kui language. This was opposed by the [[Vishva Hindu Parishad|Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] (VHP) and the Kui Association and other political leaders who depend on Hindu tribals to support their vote bank in the area. These tensions soon transformed into communal.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-18808|title=Ethnic Violence and Communal Polarisation in Orissa's Kandhamal District|date=2008-01-12|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/quota-fuel-to-communal-fire/story-EbGKLcCsHYwcGIVVSpNaZL.html|title=Quota fuel to communal fire|date=2008-12-31|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/671529854|title=Margins of faith : Dalit and tribal Christianity in India|date=2010|publisher=Sage Publications|others=Robinson, Rowena, 1967-, Kuj\u016bra, Josepha Mariy\u0101nusa., Kuj\u03b3\u0310\u01b0ura, Josepha Mariy\u03b3\u0310\u01b0anusa.|year=|isbn=978-81-321-0604-3|location=New Delhi, India|pages=271-274|oclc=671529854}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/tribals-hold-key-to-peace/story-mqHbpz5mquA5dHGQZfiAcM.html|title=Tribals hold key to peace|date=2008-12-19|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Communalism Combat|Communalism combat]] blamed the sangh parivar in orchestrating rivalries between Kandhas and the Christian Panas in Kandhamal through Hinduization and polarising the Kandhas ties with the panas and instigating the Kandhas against the latter's campaign for a scheduled status as a tribe.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Christmas tensions ===\nDuring the last days of the 2007 Christmas, the Dalit Pana Christians were constructing a cloth-draped [[pandal]]{{angle bracket|a temporary decorative scaffolding}} for the Christiams clebrations, over-topping a main-street in the town of Brahmanigaon after receiving permission for the construction from the authorities. The pandal which had been constructed on the same spot for number of years was warned to be removed this year by some local Hindus because it was located in the same area where a recent Durga Puja clebrations took place. On, December 23rd, [[Narendra Modi]] was celebrating his re-election as chief minister in Gujarat. The activists of the Sangh-affiliated Kui Samaj who had a strained relationship with the Pana Christians called for a Statewide [[bandh]]{{angle bracket|shutdown}} on December 24th and December 25th of 2007 to protest against granting of  the ST caste status to the SC Pana Christians allegly with the support of the.<ref name=\":4\" /> Christians were also warned not to put-up Christmas decorations due to the fact that some Hindus also celebrated Christmas along with them. Due to these tensions several Christian groups asked for extra police protection for their Christmas celebrations.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=265}}\n\nDespite the Kui Samaj's call for the Statewide bandh, the police opened the local market on December 24th at about 7 a.m in Brahmanigaon after recommendation by some christian groups for their Christmas preparations. About two hours late a large group allegedly led by a local RSS leader, Bikram Rout, arrived in the market and attempted to forcefully shut it down but the police kept it open. Later scuffles started between the Hindu and the Christian merchants after the group led by the RSS leader allegedly roughed up with some Christians in the market and the market was eventually closed down.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=265}}\n\n=== Lakshmanananda Saraswati ===\nOn December 24th, at about 10.45 am, Lakshmanananda Saraswati, while travelling to the town of Brahmanigaon for a yagna ritual in his car was forced to stop after a bus broke down in front of his vehicle. Hearing Christmas music coming from a nearby church, he sent his bodyguards to ask it to be turned down. His body guards allegedly roughed up on some Christians and vandalized the Church equipments. Saraswati claimed that a group of Christians injured him and his driver and damaged his car, while eye-witnesses and doctor's statements said that he did not appear seriously hurt.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=25}} Yet, pictures of him, lying in a hospital bed were circulated widely in the internet and in the news reports. The RSS, Bajrang Dal, Vishwa Hindu Parishad and the Bhartiya Janata Party called for a 4-hour bandh on the Christmas day following the incident.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=266}} This led to the communal tensions in the area.{{Sfn|Bauman|2015|p=53}}<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/892641/in-photos-damaged-churches-broken-homes-are-the-lingering-scars-of-the-2008-kandhamal-riots|title=In photos: Damaged churches, broken homes are the lingering scars of the 2008 Kandhamal riots|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ncds.nic.in/sites/default/files/WorkingandOccasionalPapers/WP64NCDS.pdf|title=Dialogue, Sacrifice and Reconciliation:A Study of Kandhamal Violence, Odisha|last=Patnaik|first=Arun K|last2=Bag|first2=Rajesh|date=January 2016|website=Nabakrushna Choudhury Centre for Development Studies,Bhubaneswar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Other incidents leading up to the riots ===\nOn December 23, Hindutva-associated tribal organisations reportedly organized a rally with slogans of 'Stop Christianity, Kill Christians' with the support of Sangh Parivar groups.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=23}}\n\nOn December 23, Hindutva activists organized a ritual to convert Pastor Digal from the Kutikia gram panchayat along with 12 members of the Christian community. He was beaten, brutally tortured and paraded naked as he refused to renounce Christianity.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=24-25}}\n\n== Riots ==\nViolent clashes occurred from 24th to 27th of December 2007 between people led by the Sangh Parivar groups, the Sangh- affiliated Kui Samaj and the Christians.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAround 10 a.m on December 24th, a mob of around 500 people led again by the RSS leader, Bikram Rout ransacked the pandal and set it on fire in-front of the onlooking police. The mob then went on to destroy Christian shops and attack Christians. Gun-shots were fired, a boy was severely wounded, many Christians fled to the near-by jungles out of fear.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=266}} While other reports suggest more than 3000 people belonging to Vishwa Hindu Parishad, RSS, Bajrang Dal and the [[Vanavasi Kalyan Ashram]] started to vandalize Christian symbols and two young boys suffered gun injuries. The Church of the lady of Lourdes was decimated.This occurred before Laksmananda was attacked.{{Sfn|JPDC|2008|p=25}}\n\nOn 25th December, Six Churches were set ablaze after the Christians were chased out. The Violence continued as the members of each community clashed with each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/in-india-churches-torched-on-christmas/|title=In India, Churches Torched On Christmas|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 26th December, clashes continued all over the district, multiple houses were attacked and many were left injured, a Police Station in Phiringia was set on fire. Police was found it difficult to reach the violence hit areas in the villages as protesters obstructed roads by blocking it with trees. Chief Minister [[Naveen Patnaik]] held two rounds of meetings with senior officials to review the situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2007/dec/26orissa.htm|title=Orissa: Fresh violence in curfew-bound areas|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/AdvisoryCom/PostDisaster/OdishaForumForActionReport.pdf#page=2|title=An Assessment of Damage and Loss of Private Property during the Anti-Christian Violence in Kandhamal, India|last=|first=|date=|website=Centre for the Sustainable Use of Natural and Social Resources|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nOn 27th December, Dozens of Churches were ransacked and razed in the areas of  Nuagaon, G Udaygiri  Phulbani Sadar and Brahmanigaon. A a Congress parliamentarian's house was also attacked by the Saffron activists and the Kui tribals, opposing tribal status to the Pana Christians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2007/dec/27church.htm|title=Twelve more churches razed in Orissa|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> A Christian retaliation also took place as a Christian mob entered the Hindu quarter of Brahmanigaon and set fire to about hundred homes. Similarly a Christian mob set fire to an additional twenty homes near Gadapur. On the Same day the rioting had stopped.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=267}}\n\n== Total casualties and damages ==\nInitial governmental reports suggested that more than 100 churches and church institutions, including hostels, convents and about 700 houses and other structures were burnt in the riots and three persons killed(all Christians).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orissapost.com/3706-acquitted-in-kandhamal-riots/|title=3,706 acquitted in Kandhamal riots - OrissaPOST|date=2020-01-24|website=Odisha News, Odisha Latest news, Odisha Daily - OrissaPOST|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> More than 837 familes were left homless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sabrangindia.in/article/flashback-kandhamal-targeted-violence-against-christians-9-years-later|title=A Flashback to Kandhamal Targeted Violence against Christians, 9 Years Later|date=2017-08-24|website=SabrangIndia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nA report by the [[National Commission for Minorities]], suggested more than 730 houses were destroyed and 95 churches were burnt.{{Sfn|Robinson|2010|p=267}}\n\nThe Communalism combat reported 85-95 Christian institutions were burnt down, vandalized or damaged additionally to the reported damages.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAll India Christian Council (AICC) study team stated that in December 2007, Hindu nationalists murdered a total of 50 Christians, destroyed 730 housing units and 95 churches.\u00a0In the numerous relief camps set up by State government, hundreds of displaced Christians were made to stay.<ref name=\"worldwatchmonitor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldwatchmonitor.org/2008/02-February/newsarticle_5210.html/|title=Maoists Said to Recruit Victims of Violence|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124132712/https://www.worldwatchmonitor.org/2008/02-February/newsarticle_5210.html/|archive-date=24 November 2015|accessdate=2015-08-27|newspaper=www.worldwatchmonitor.org|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe general secretary of the Kandhamal district's Christian Endeavour Union, suggested that 100 houses belonging to Christians were burnt in Godapur, Brahmanigaon, Barakhama, and some other villages on 26 and 27 December 2007. He also visited Godapur and Brahmanigaon  villages to take a look of the situation, and suspected that these houses were burnt sown by sections of \"Hinditva Activists\" who may have been incited by the Maoists.<ref>[http://www.compassdirect.org/en/display.php?page=news&lang=en&length=long&idelement=5210 INDIA: MAOISTS SAID TO RECRUIT VICTIMS OF VIOLENCE] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222000553/http://www.compassdirect.org/en/display.php?page=news&lang=en&length=long&idelement=5210|date=22 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Ndtv.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/news/ngo-maoist-link-in-kandhamal/21988|title=NGO-Maoist link in Kandhamal|last=|date=|accessdate=2015-08-27|newspaper=Ndtv.com}}</ref>\n\n== Investigations ==\nMany members of the Hindu community have claimed that Christian show of religiosity, and the financial privilege that enabled such an exhibition, contributed to the rioting.<ref name=\":1\" /> While some Hindu organisations suggested that disturbances were the result of ethnic tensions in the area, mainly between the Dalit Pana community and the Adivasi Kandhas.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIndependent experts also found, in terms of violence and planning across mountainous areas, that that violence was orchestrated and the police had prior information about the Hindutva organisations planning to riot. It should also be remembered that the celebration of his party's 10th anniversary by Chief Minister [[Naveen Patnaik]] coincided with the turmoil. The celebration demanded that a significant number of the state police forces be relocated from districts to Bhubaneswar, the state capital. The police found it challenging to react to the developing situation in Kandhamal between 24 and 25 December.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nHindutva Organizations accused that the violent uprising of Hindus stemmed from Christian conversions and actions of Maoist organizations, resulting in the Kandhamal riots of 2007 even though the Maoist parties are not present in the places in which violence has arisen, even though sangh parivar organisations have seen a increase in these same places in recent years.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{Cite book|last=Robinson|first=Rowena|url=https://searchworks.stanford.edu/view/8794295|title=Margins of faith : Dalit and tribal Christianity in India|date=2010|publisher=Sage Publications|others=Joseph Marianus Kujur|year=2010|isbn=978-81-321-0604-3|location=New Delhi, India|pages=|oclc=671529854|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=JPDC|first=Justice, Peace and Development Commission (JPDC)(Bhubaneswar, India)|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/294883231|title=Faith under fire|date=2008|publisher=Media House|others=|year=2008|isbn=81-7495-320-5|location=Delhi|pages=|oclc=294883231|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Bauman|first=Chad M.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/888554934|title=Pentecostals, proselytization, and anti-Christian violence in contemporary India|publisher=Oxford University Press, 2015|year=2015|isbn=978-0-19-020210-1|location=New York, NY|pages=|oclc=888554934|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Violence against Christians in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against Christians]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Christian sentiment in Asia]]\n[[Category:Hate crimes]]\n[[Category:Attacks on churches in Asia]]\n[[Category:Hindu nationalism]]\n[[Category:Persecution by Hindus]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Christians]]\n[[Category:Sectarian violence]]\n[[Category:Hinduism-motivated violence in India]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Christmas_violence_in_Kandhamal"}
{"title_page": "Gogmagog (band)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{distinguish|Gog and Magog|Gog Magog Hills}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Gogmagog\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[London]], England\n| genre = [[Hard rock]]\n| years_active = 1985\n| label = Food for Thought\n| associated_acts = \n| website = \n| current_members = \n| past_members = [[Paul Di'Anno]]<br>[[Pete Willis]]<br>[[Janick Gers]]<br>[[Neil Murray (British musician)|Neil Murray]]<br>[[Clive Burr]]\n}}\n\n'''Gogmagog''' were a short-lived British [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]], assembled in 1985 by the record producer [[Jonathan King]].<ref name=\"LarkinHM\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Guinness Who\u2019s Who of Heavy Metal]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|date=1995|edition=Second|isbn=0-85112-656-1|page=150}}</ref> The band's lineup featured former [[Iron Maiden]] vocalist [[Paul Di'Anno]] and drummer [[Clive Burr]], future Iron Maiden guitarist [[Janick Gers]], former [[Def Leppard]] guitarist [[Pete Willis]], and former [[Whitesnake]] bassist [[Neil Murray (British musician)|Neil Murray]].<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/>\n\nTogether for only a short time, Gogmagog released a three song E.P. on the independent Food For Thought label in 1985 entitled ''I Will Be There''.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> Two of the songs recorded were written by producer King (\"Living in a Fucking Time Warp\" and \"It\u2019s Illegal, It\u2019s Immoral, It\u2019s Unhealthy, But It\u2019s Fun\"), with the title track being composed by longtime [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] collaborator [[Russ Ballard]], and originally released on his 1981 solo album ''Into the Fire''. The band members were not permitted to write any original material.<ref name=\"metal-rules1\"/> \n\nOriginally, King attempted to put together a supergroup revolving around Whitesnake vocalist [[David Coverdale]], bassist [[John Entwistle]] of [[The Who]], and veteran drummer [[Cozy Powell]], but this early line-up \"wasn't working out\" according to Di'Anno.<ref name=\"metal-rules1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metal-rules.com/interviews/dianno.htm |title=Interview with Paul Di'Anno in Stockholm, Sweden |website=Metal-rules.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Being little more than a contrivance concocted by producer Jonathan King, the band quickly fell apart once he lost interest.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> Vocalist Di'Anno was completely dismissive of both the group and producer, referring to the failed project as \"...nothing. That was some fucking idiot who got us doing that shit.\"<ref name=\"metal-rules1\"/>\n\nThe two King-penned songs appeared in the soundtrack to the 2011 film ''Me Me Me'', also written by King.  All the members of the band appear in the cast.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1819597/</ref>\n\n==Former band members==\n*[[Paul Di'Anno]] \u2013 lead vocals\n*[[Pete Willis]] \u2013 guitars\n*[[Janick Gers]] \u2013 guitars \n*[[Neil Murray (British musician)|Neil Murray]] \u2013 bass\n*[[Clive Burr]] \u2013 drums, percussion\n\n==Discography==\n*''I Will Be There'' EP (1985)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Iron Maiden}}\n{{Def Leppard}}\n\n[[Category:English hard rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:Iron Maiden (band)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1985]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Rock music supergroups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{distinguish|Gog and Magog|Gog Magog Hills}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Gogmagog\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[London]], England\n| genre = [[Hard rock]]\n| years_active = 1985\n| label = Food for Thought\n| associated_acts = \n| website = \n| current_members = \n| past_members = [[Paul Di'Anno]]<br>[[Pete Willis]]<br>[[Janick Gers]]<br>[[Neil Murray (British musician)|Neil Murray]]<br>[[Clive Burr]]\n}}\n\n'''Gogmagog''' were a short-lived British [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]], assembled in 1985 by the record producer [[Jonathan King]].<ref name=\"LarkinHM\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Guinness Who\u2019s Who of Heavy Metal]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|date=1995|edition=Second|isbn=0-85112-656-1|page=150}}</ref> The band's lineup featured former [[Iron Maiden]] vocalist [[Paul Di'Anno]] and drummer [[Clive Burr]], future Iron Maiden guitarist [[Janick Gers]], former [[Def Leppard]] guitarist [[Pete Willis]], and former [[Whitesnake]] bassist [[Neil Murray (British musician)|Neil Murray]].<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/>\n\nTogether for only a short time, Gogmagog released a three song E.P. on the independent Food For Thought label in 1985 entitled ''I Will Be There''.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> Two of the songs recorded were written by producer King (\"Living in a Fucking Time Warp\" and \"It\u2019s Illegal, It\u2019s Immoral, It\u2019s Unhealthy, But It\u2019s Fun\"), with the title track being composed by longtime [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] collaborator [[Russ Ballard]], and originally released on his 1981 solo album ''Into the Fire''. The band members were not permitted to write any original material.<ref name=\"metal-rules1\"/> \n\nOriginally, King attempted to put together a supergroup revolving around Whitesnake vocalist [[David Coverdale]], bassist [[John Entwistle]] of [[The Who]], and veteran drummer [[Cozy Powell]], but this early line-up \"wasn't working out\" according to Di'Anno.<ref name=\"metal-rules1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metal-rules.com/interviews/dianno.htm |title=Interview with Paul Di'Anno in Stockholm, Sweden |website=Metal-rules.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Being little more than a contrivance concocted by producer Jonathan King, the band quickly fell apart once he lost interest.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\"/> Vocalist Di'Anno was completely dismissive of both the group and producer, referring to the failed project as \"...nothing. That was some fucking idiot who got us doing that shit.\"<ref name=\"metal-rules1\"/>\n\nThe two King-penned songs appeared in the sountrack to the 2011 film ''Me Me Me'', also written by King.  All the members of the band appear in the cast.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1819597/</ref>\n\n==Former band members==\n*[[Paul Di'Anno]] \u2013 lead vocals\n*[[Pete Willis]] \u2013 guitars\n*[[Janick Gers]] \u2013 guitars \n*[[Neil Murray (British musician)|Neil Murray]] \u2013 bass\n*[[Clive Burr]] \u2013 drums, percussion\n\n==Discography==\n*''I Will Be There'' EP (1985)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Iron Maiden}}\n{{Def Leppard}}\n\n[[Category:English hard rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:Iron Maiden (band)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1985]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Rock music supergroups]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: sountrack->soundtrack", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gogmagog_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Milan Bandi\u0107", "text_new": "{{Infobox Mayor\n| name         = Milan Bandi\u0107\n| image        = Dan OSRH Milan Bandic 28052011 2.jpg| width        = 220px\n| caption      = Bandi\u0107 on 28 May 2011\n| order        = 50th and 52nd\n| office       = Mayor of Zagreb\n| term_start1  = 15 May 2005\n| predecessor1 = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| successor1   = \n| term_start2  = 5 May 2000\n| term_end2    = 21 January 2002\n| predecessor2 = [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]]\n| successor2   = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| office3           = Leader of the [[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party|Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 -<br />Labour and Solidarity Party]] \n| term_start3    = 28 March 2015 \n| term_end3     =\n| predecessor3 = ''Position established'' \n| successor3     = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Grude]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]] {{small|(now [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]])}}\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Croatian\n| party        = {{plainlist|\n*[[League of Communists of Croatia]] {{small|(1980s)}}\n*[[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] {{small|(1990\u20132009)}}\n*[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] {{small|(2009\u20132015)}}\n*[[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n}}\n| other_party = \n| relations   =\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|1981|1996}}<br />{{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|2003}}<ref name=spouse_children />\n| children    = 1<ref name=spouse_children />\n| residence   = [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]]\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Zagreb]]\n| occupation  = [[Politician]]\n| profession  = \n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{About|the Croatian politician|the Croatian filmmaker who legally changed his name to Milan Bandi\u0107|Dario Juri\u010dan}}\n\n'''Milan Bandi\u0107''' ({{IPA-hr|m\u01d0lan b\u00e2\u02d0ndit\u0361\u0255:|hr}} {{small|({{Audio-nohelp|Milanbandicname.ogg|listen}})}}; born 22 November 1955) is a Croatian politician currently serving his sixth term as [[List of mayors of Zagreb|mayor]] of the Croatian capital, [[Zagreb]], since 2005. Between 2000 and 2009, he was a prominent member of the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP). In 2007, he unsuccessfully ran for party president. However, he remained one of the main rivals of the former party president [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]]. On 5 November 2009, he announced his intention to run for a president, in violation of the party's bylaws which led to his expulsion from the party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/video--bandic-krenuo-u-utrku-milan-ce-igrati-lopte-u-svakom-selu/458485.aspx |title=Video - Bandi\u0107 krenuo u utrku: \"Milan \u0107e igrati lopte u svakom selu\" |author= |date=5 November 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Index.hr]] |accessdate=16 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> On 10 January 2010, he lost the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|Croatian presidential election]] to the official SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] in the runoff elections.\n\nAlthough described in 2002 as the SDP's most popular politician for the \"famous 24 hours he devotes to the service of citizens of Zagreb\",<ref name=nin_omiljeni>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.nin.co.rs/2002-01/31/21760.html\n| title = Metropola bez gradona\u010delnika\n| date = 2002-01-31\n| last = Stanivukovi\u0107\n| first = Zoran\n| accessdate = 2008-09-19\n| work = [[\u041d\u0418\u041d]]\n| language = Serbian\n}}</ref> he has also gained notoriety for a number of actions and statements he has made as mayor.<ref name=javno_biografija/>\nBandi\u0107 is viewed as a hands-on mayor because of his ambition and the number of projects related to Zagreb that he has undertaken. He is widely credited{{fact|date=January 2020}} for the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]] (now [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]), for his work on the [[Arena Zagreb]] and the [[Homeland Bridge]] (which opened during his third term).\n\nBandi\u0107 was arrested in the evening hours of 19 October 2014, along with 18 other officials, under the suspicion of malfeasance related to [[Zagreb Holding]]. In his absence, his deputy [[Sandra \u0160valjek]] took the duties of mayor from 19 October 2014 until 26 March 2015.<ref>http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Novosti/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/279857/Bandi-opunomoio-Kusin-za-voenje-Zagreba.aspx</ref> Bandi\u0107 canceled the authorization that he granted to her because some disagreements between them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/jutarnji-doznaje-uhicen-milan-bandic-/1229175/ |title=Uhi\u0107eni Milan Bandi\u0107! |last1=De\u0161kovi\u0107 |first1=Marin |date=2014-10-19 |website=Jutarnji list |publisher=Jutarnji list |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtl.hr/vijesti/novosti/1367502/uhicen-milan-bandic-u-tijeku-pretraga-njegovog-stana/ |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107, u tijeku pretraga njegovog stana! |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014-10-19 |website=RTL Televizija |publisher=RTL Televizija |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref> Consequently, \u0160valjek has resigned all of her duties in city. Bandi\u0107's second deputy Vesna Kusin took the duties of mayor on 26 March 2015. On 10 April 2015, Zagreb County Court ruled that Milan Bandi\u0107 has to be released from prison while pending trial. Consequently, he returned to the position of Mayor.<ref>http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandic-ostaje-na-slobodi-i-vraca-se-na-mjesto-gradonacelnika/812562.aspx</ref>\n\n==Private life==\nMilan Bandi\u0107 was born to Jozo and Blagica Bandi\u0107 ([[n\u00e9e]] Tomi\u0107) in the small [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of Bandi\u0107a Brig, a part of Cerov Dolac in the municipality of [[Grude]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (then [[PR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[FPR Yugoslavia]]).<ref name=Bandic>Bandi\u0107, Milan. [http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 Biografija] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424082908/http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 |date=2008-04-24}}. Bandi\u0107's official web site. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He was the middle child in the family, with an older brother Drago and a younger sister Tonka.<ref name=Barilar>{{cite news |title=Bandi\u0107: Od doseljenika s koferom do neprikosnovenog vladara Zagreba |author=Barilar, Suzana |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/bandic--od-doseljenika-s-koferom-do-neprikosnovenog-vladara-zagreba/333515/ |newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]] |date=4 November 2009 |accessdate=20 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> His family's main source of income was a [[tobacco plantation]]. As a child, Bandi\u0107 was altar servant in local church.<ref name=Bandic/> He attended [[Antun Branko \u0160imi\u0107]] High School in Grude and he was excellent student.<ref name=Barilar/> In 1974, he moved to Zagreb to study at the Department of Political Science at the [[University of Zagreb]]<ref name=Bandic/>, program of National defense and social self-protection (today non-existent). To pay off his [[student loan]]s he unloaded sugar and coal<ref name=Bandic/> and he was also a [[masonry|mason]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-put-na-celo-zagreba-poceo-je-istovarom-secera-i-zbukanjem-fasada/778501.aspx | title=Bandi\u0107ev put na \u010delo Zagreba po\u010deo je istovarom \u0161e\u0107era i \u017ebukanjem fasada | date=19 October 2014 | work=[[Index.hr]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Bandi\u0107 was conscripted to the [[Yugoslav People's Army]], and after that he was employed in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo]], producer of ice creams.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring his student days he met his wife Vesna.<ref name=Bandic/> He was married to her until their divorce in 1996, although they still live together in their [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]] apartment. They have a daughter, Ana-Marija.<ref name=spouse_children>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=248861\n | title = Bandi\u0107 se 1996. razveo zbog otkupa stana?\n | date = 2005-02-10\n | accessdate = 2008-08-01\n | work = Vijesti.net\n | language = Croatian}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has stated that his divorce was the result of a seven-year separation.<ref name=spouse_children /> Bandi\u0107 owns two [[golden retriever]]s, Bil and Rudi, which he often walks during his work hours.<ref name=24sata_bil_operacija>{{cite web\n| url = http://damp.nsk.hr/arhiva/vol1/880/14301/www.24sata.hr/articles/view/48239/index.html\n| title = Bandi\u0107ev Bil ide na kemoterapiju?\n| date = 2007-03-22\n| last = Vukadin\n| first = Romana\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = [[24 sata (Croatia)|24 sata]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=bil_rudi>{{cite journal |date=2008-08-04 |title=Bandi\u0107u u dom sti\u017ee retriver Rudi |trans-title=Retriever Rudi arrives in Bandi\u0107 home |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=664 |language=Croatian |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47766/8/ |accessdate=2008-08-06 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oppVAzh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47766/bandicu-u-dom-stize-retriver-rudi |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 is an avid distance runner, describing himself as \"addicted to running\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Ne bojim se, imam jo\u0161 mnogo kilometara za pretr\u010dati| work=[[Jutarnji list]] | date=July 28, 2009 | language=Croatian | quote=Mogu re\u0107i da sam ovisan o tr\u010danju i da je to moja droga.}}</ref> He is reported to run 10 kilometers every weekday morning,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | title=PHOTO: Zagreb Mayor Turns Pilgrimage Into Marathon | work=javno.com | first=Ivan | last=Kova\u010d | date=September 15, 2008 | accessdate=2009-08-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520043315/http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | archivedate=May 20, 2009}}</ref> and in March 2008 completed the 61&nbsp;km [[Zagreb]]\u2013[[\u010cazma]] [[ultramarathon]].\n\n==Political career==\n{{POV section|date=April 2020}}\n==={{anchor|Before becoming a mayor}}Before becoming mayor===\nAfter serving the army and short work in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo company]] Bandi\u0107 was employed in Municipal Committee of [[League of Communists of Croatia]] in [[Pe\u0161\u010denica \u2013 \u017ditnjak|Pe\u0161\u0107enica]] where he worked as professional political worker.<ref name=Bandic/><ref name=Barilar/>\n\nAfter collapse of [[Socialist Federative Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]] and [[League of Communists of Croatia]] Bandi\u0107 did not want to leave the party because he worked for years in Pe\u0161\u010denica and thus it was matter of pride.<ref name=Bandic/> He expressed his hopes that he and his colleagues will return to political stage as Croatian social democrats.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring the [[Croatian War of Independence]] Bandi\u0107 helped with logistics.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nBandi\u0107 was one of the few [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Herzegovinian Croats]] to remain with the party after the [[1990 Croatian parliamentary election|first democratic elections in 1990]] in which the Communist Party, led by [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]], reformed and re-branded itself as the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (SDP). He demonstrated organizational ability and populist political instincts. These abilities allowed the SDP to gain in Zagreb blue-collar neighborhoods and attract votes which the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] (HDZ) and its then-president [[Franjo Tu\u0111man]] had considered theirs by default. As such, he proved to be a valuable asset for the Social Democratic Party. In 1993 he became party secretary.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\nConflict between HDZ and SDP manifested in the [[1995 Croatian parliamentary election|1995 parliamentary]] and City of [[Zagreb]] elections, leading to the [[Zagreb Crisis]]: an electoral alliance (in which the SDP was a major partner) won a majority in the Zagreb elections and chose [[Goran Grani\u0107]] as the new mayor, but Franjo Tu\u0111man used a legal loophole to stop Grani\u0107 from taking office. Several subsequent elections were held, with the SDP winning each time and Tu\u0111man promptly removing every candidate. For a time Zagreb was a city without a mayor, which led to public unrest and protests in [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]]. With the final 1997 election of the HDZ candidate [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]] as the mayor of Zagreb, the crisis faded. Bandi\u0107 played a role in the crisis by becoming a city councilman in 1995 and the leader of the Zagreb SDP in 1997.<ref name=javno_biografija>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/hrvatska/clanak.php?id=49365\n |title       = Biografija: Milan Bandi\u0107\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-01\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68EJ2pyfI?url=http://dalje.com/hr-hrvatska/biografija--milan-bandic/49365\n |archivedate = 2012-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first campaign his [[Herzegovina|Herzegovinian]] background became an issue, as the [[Croatian Peasant Party]] (HSS) suggested that only a native citizen of Zagreb could become the city's mayor. HSS also launched a propaganda campaign against [[Herzegovinians]] in an effort to undermine Bandi\u0107's campaign. The party hoped that the majority of Zagreb voters would turn away from Bandi\u0107. Those expectations were not fulfilled and Bandi\u0107 later used his Herzegovinian background as an advantage, broadening his support among the ordinary citizens of Zagreb.\n\nThe HDZ under Bandi\u0107 eventually lost power in the Croatian capital in 2000.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\n==={{anchor|First and second term (2000\u20132002)}}First and second terms (2000\u20132002)===\n{{see also|2000 Zagreb local elections|2001 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nBandi\u0107 was elected [[mayor]] of Zagreb in 2000<ref name=izbori>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | title = Izbori odr\u017eani 7. svibnja 2000.\n | work = Gradski zavod za automatsku obradu podataka\n | accessdate = 2008-07-27\n | language = Croatian\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100129103926/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | archive-date = 2010-01-29\n | url-status = dead\n}}</ref> and re-elected in the city election in 2001.<ref name=izbori_2001>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| title = Izbori odr\u017eani 20. svibnja 2001.\n| work = City Bureau for Automatic Data Processing\n| accessdate = 2008-08-04\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080316190322/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| archive-date = 2008-03-16\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref> His rise in influence among SDP politicians and on the Zagreb political scene created a backlash by the [[Croatian People's Party]] (HNS), the other left-of-center party led by [[Vesna Pusi\u0107]], who did not trust his nationalist populism and his occasional run-ins with the courts. The HNS campaigned against the SDP in the 2000 elections. However, the HNS entered into a coalition with the SDP in 2001. It governed Zagreb with the SDP until 2005 when it withdrew, again because of Bandi\u0107.\n\nIn 2002, Bandi\u0107 fled from the scene of a motor vehicle accident while under the influence of alcohol. He tried to bribe the officer who stopped him and threatened the officer with his alleged connections in the [[Ministry of the Interior (Croatia)|Ministry of the Interior]]. The incident was heavily covered by the media that asked for his resignation. The SDP was at first reluctant to sanction Bandi\u0107. Under public pressure, the SDP leadership compelled Bandi\u0107 to resign.<ref name=resignation>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti2/020121jl.htm| title = Bandi\u0107eva ostavka - pobjeda javnosti| accessdate = 2008-07-27| last = Lovri\u0107| first = Jelena| date = 2002-01-21| work = [[Novi list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti7/060118vm.htm| title = Esdepeovci zgro\u017eeni pona\u0161anjem Bandi\u0107a| accessdate = 2007-09-29| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2006-01-18| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=index_policemen>{{cite web| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=391401| title = Kako se rije\u0161iti policajca koji radi svoj posao| accessdate = 2008-09-21| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2008-06-17| work = Vijesti.net| language = Croatian}}</ref> After his resignation there was uncertainty concerning his successor; while the Zagreb SDP had the right to nominate the mayor, it was so dominated by Bandi\u0107 that it was questionable who could replace him.<ref name=resignation /> Eventually [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] took over as mayor, while Bandi\u0107 retained a place in the Zagreb chain of command as deputy mayor. He was eager to become a mayor again, and blocked Pavi\u0107's development plans (advancing his own) while working toward an early election.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=\"savez_desni\u010dari\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10596/\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 s desni\u010darima ru\u0161i Vlastu Pavi\u0107\n |date        = 2003-05-27\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-02\n |last        = Babi\u0107\n |first       = Jelena\n |issue       = 393\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |trans-title = Bandi\u0107 and right-wingers brings down Vlasta Pavi\u0107\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68oWiX4IA?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10596/bandic-s-desnicarima-rusi-vlastu-pavic\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10895/ |title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 u zamjenu za primirje ustupa mjesto Bandi\u0107u |last=Jelini\u0107 |first=Berislav |language=Croatian |trans-title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 steps down for Bandi\u0107 in exchange for a truce |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |date=24 February 2004 |accessdate=30 June 2012 |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oY6G8Cg?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10895/vlasta-pavic-u-zamjenu-za-primirje-ustupa-mjesto-bandicu |url-status=dead}}</ref> In response [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] (head of the SDP) tried to restrain Bandi\u0107's activities.<ref name=\"ra\u010dan_upozorenje\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10240/ |title=Ra\u010dan poti\u010de Vlastu Pavi\u0107 da vlada bez Bandi\u0107a |date=15 May 2002 |last=Ple\u0161e |first=Mladen |accessdate=30 June 2012 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |trans-title=Ra\u010dan urges Vlasta Pavi\u0107 to govern without Bandi\u0107 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oWJlgkS?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10240/racan-potice-vlastu-pavic-da-vlada-bez-bandica |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe rules then in force would not allow Bandi\u0107 to have a second term as mayor during the current term of the assembly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom |publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)]] |title=Ra\u010dan ustuknuo pred Bandi\u0107evim divlja\u0161tvom |trans-title=Ra\u010dan taken aback by Bandi\u0107's savage remark |language=Croatian |author=Berislav Jelini\u0107 |date=4 May 2004 |accessdate=1 July 2012 |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68pZwx7NY?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom}}</ref> Vlasta Pavi\u0107 attempted to strike a deal ending the ongoing feud, but Bandi\u0107 eventually succeeded in undermining her. Although no early elections were held, he was re-elected mayor in [[2005 Zagreb mayoral elections|the May 15, 2005 elections]].<ref name=izbori_2005>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| title = Rezultati glasovanja za izbor \u010dlanova Gradske skup\u0161tine Grada Zagreba (\"Voting results for the election of Municipal Councillors to the City of Zagreb\")\n| date = 2005-05-16\n| accessdate = 2008-08-01\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721102953/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| archive-date = 2011-07-21\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\" />\n\nIn April 2004 then-mayor [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] criticized Bandi\u0107 for having spent 15 million [[kuna (currency)|kunas]] (about [[USD|US$]]3.26 million) of city money to buy a lot on [[Vjekoslav Heinzel Avenue|Heinzelova Avenue]] which was formerly owned by the [[meat packing industry|meat packing plant]] Zagrep\u010danka. The controversy was dubbed \"the Zagrep\u010danka case\" by the newspapers.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> The city government could not use the lot, because its ownership was divided among 43 individuals. When (responding to a question from a city counselor) Mayor Pavi\u0107 distanced herself from Bandi\u0107, Bandi\u0107 was accused of cursing her mother in a vulgar way during the talks.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/clanak.aspx?id=199287\n| title = Milan Bandi\u0107 opsovao majku zagreba\u010dkoj gradona\u010delnici\n| accessdate = 2007-09-29\n| date = 2004-04-28\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> He also published a newspaper advertisement on behalf of the city government, entitled ''Istina je!'' (\"It's true!\"). The advertisement was supported by all SDP members of the city council except [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]], the mayor at that time. [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] later condemned the advertisement as a political mistake, telling the Zagreb SDP that they would face consequences for their action.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment/>\n\nA court case ensued, with charges being brought against Bandi\u0107 and others involved.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |title       = Kaznena prijava protiv Bandi\u0107a, Buluma i nekih \u010dlanova poglavarstva zbog oglasa ''Istina je!''\n |date        = 2004-05-10\n |publisher   = [[Croatian Radio Television]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |accessdate  = 2008-04-30\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170804/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-03\n}}</ref> Three years later, Bandi\u0107 was acquitted and the City of Zagreb was awarded ownership of the Zagrep\u010danka lot in a [[judgment (law)|court judgment]]. Bandi\u0107 promised a new [[business district]] in the Zagrep\u010danka location.<ref name=city_centar_zagrepcanka>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |title       = Zagreb To Get A City Centre\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612235956/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |archivedate = 2007-06-12\n}}</ref>\n\nNot all legal troubles have been solved, however, as the city still has to deal with unsolved cases and complaints entered against the lot.<ref name=plomba>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130126200636/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-01-26\n |title      = Bandi\u0107 isplatio ovrhu za Zagrep\u010danku - 3 mil kuna\n |date       = 2008-09-26\n |accessdate = 2008-09-28\n |work       = Javno.hr\n |language   = Croatian\n}}</ref> In 2008 the sale of the Zagrep\u010danka lot to [[Institut IGH]] was announced, but the deal fell through in 2009; this has potential to incur a cost of \u20ac4.5&nbsp;million to the Zagreb [[holding company]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.poslovni.hr/133686.aspx | title = Ivo \u010covi\u0107 ipak potpisao \u0161tetan ugovor s Radi\u0107em? | language = Croatian | work = [[Poslovni dnevnik]] | date = December 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Third term (2005\u20132009)===\n{{see also|2005 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nFollowing the illness and death of Ra\u010dan Bandi\u0107 announced his candidacy for SDP leadership,<ref name=nacional_kandidatura>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34638/\n |title       = Obra\u010dun Bandi\u0107a i Milanovi\u0107a odlu\u010duje o \u0161efu SDP-a\n |trans-title = Conflict of Bandi\u0107 and Milanovi\u0107 to decide leader of the SDP\n |date        = 2007-05-21\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-04\n |issue       = 601\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68ohfBem2?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34638/obracun-bandica-i-milanovica-odlucuje-o-sefu-sdp-a\n |url-status  = dead\n}}</ref> planning to resign as mayor afterwards. He competed against [[\u017deljka Antunovi\u0107]], [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] and [[Tonino Picula]]. [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] was elected on 2 June 2007 as the new SDP leader, while Bandi\u0107 remained mayor of Zagreb.<ref name=milanovic>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/35122/\n |title       = Milanovi\u0107 widens his base\n |accessdate  = 2007-09-30\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-06-06\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLPJQhh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/35122/milanovic-widens-his-base\n |issue       = 603\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref> He did not give up the fight, however, organizing opposition within the party and campaigning to defeat Milanovi\u0107 in the next party election.<ref name=\"revolt_milanovi\u0107\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/40824/\n |title       = Revolt against Milanovi\u0107\n |accessdate  = 2008-07-28\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLV04ei?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/40824/revolt-against-milanovic\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-12-12\n |issue       = 630\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref><ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_obra\u010dun\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/11033/Default.aspx\n| title = Milanovi\u0107 krenuo u obra\u010dun s Bandi\u0107em\n| accessdate = 2008-07-28\n| last = Karlovi\u0107-Saboti\u0107\n| first = Marina\n| date = 2008-06-12\n| work = [[Slobodna Dalmacija]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz />\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist />\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2008 the Main Committee of SDP received a letter entitled ''Za \u0161to se, uop\u0107e, danas zala\u017ee SDP?'' (\"What, overall, does the SDP stand for today?\") by [[Dra\u017een Lali\u0107]] (a Croatian [[sociologist]]) which attacked Bandi\u0107 by pointing out his misdeeds and errors and questioning Bandi\u0107's loyalty to the SDP's principles. The letter was sparked partially by the [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] of anti-corruption Zagreb road-authorities director Igor Ra\u0111enovi\u0107, which had not been properly investigated. Another reason was a concert held on [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]] by [[Marko Perkovi\u0107 Thompson]], a singer known to attract an [[Usta\u0161e|usta\u0161a]] audience. Bandi\u0107 supported the concert instead of condemning it, inaccordance with SDP anti-nationalistic principles. Although the letter attacked the SDP as a whole, Bandi\u0107 was considered a key participant in all events described. Bandi\u0107 responded to the letter indirectly by encouraging the police to do their job, while failing to appropriately defend his position.<ref name=lalic_letter>{{cite journal\n| last = Cigoj\n| first = Mark\n|author2=Galovi\u0107, Alen\n| title = Pismo koje potresa SDP\n| journal = [[Globus (weekly)|Globus]]\n| issue = 918\n| pages =18\u201322\n| url = http://www.globus.com.hr\n| date = 2008-07-11\n| accessdate = 2008-07-12\n}}</ref><ref name=\"lali\u0107_ve\u010dernji\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |title=Javne osobe pisale Milanovi\u0107u da zaustavi Bandi\u0107a \n |last=Popovi\u0107 \n |first=Jasmina \n |date=2008-07-09 \n |accessdate=2008-08-02 \n |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] \n |language=Croatian \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731053802/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |archivedate=2008-07-31 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> Zoran Milanovi\u0107 responded instead, accusing Lali\u0107 of trying to buy himself a return to the Croatian political scene. Bandi\u0107 thus received the SDP's support, ensuring his candidacy in the upcoming 2009 mayoral election.<ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_fights_back\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47300/ |title=Pismo koje je u\u010dvrstilo Bandi\u0107a |author1=Bajru\u0161i, Robert |trans-title=A letter that strengthened Bandi\u0107 |author2=Gaura, Orhidea |date=2008-07-14 |accessdate=2008-08-02 |issue=661 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oon0FPx?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47300/pismo-koje-je-ucvrstilo-bandica}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox /> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov /> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing /> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-kum-izgradio-najskuplji-wc-u-hrvatskoj-20090318|title=Bandi\u0107ev kum izgradio najskuplji WC u Hrvatskoj|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|accessdate=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Fourth term (2009\u20132013)===\n{{see also|2009 Zagreb local elections}}\nUntil 2009, the mayor of Zagreb was elected by the city assembly ([[city council]]). In [[2009 Zagreb local elections|elections held in the spring of 2009]], the mayor was directly elected for the first time. Bandi\u0107 was forced into a second round not by HDZ candidate ([[Jasen Mesi\u0107]]) but by outsider [[Josip Kregar]] (dean of the Faculty of Law at the [[University of Zagreb]]), who ran on an independent platform. Bandi\u0107 won the second round, with 62 percent of the vote to Kregar's 37 percent. In October 2009, Bandi\u0107 visited the site of a World War II [[Yugoslav Partisans|partisan]] massacre on the island of [[Daksa (Dubrovnik)|Daksa]] with the [[Croatian Bishops' Conference]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Dubrovnik/tabid/75/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/75337/Default.aspx | title=Daksa kod Dubrovnika: biskupi molili za \u017ertve komunisti\u010dkog terora - do\u0161ao i Milan Bandi\u0107 | work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]] | date=October 21, 2009 | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> On 29 October 2009 Bandi\u0107's proposed exceptional budget, with a proposal to hold a referendum on the building of a new football stadium, was rejected. Among those voting against the budget was his own party, the SDP.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=51872&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=38&cHash=8a5414470f | title=I SDP protiv Bandi\u0107a | date=October 29, 2009 | work=hrt.hr | publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302221451/http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48 | archivedate=March 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential campaign===\n[[File:Milan bandi\u0107 poster.JPG|thumb|240px|Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard during second round of 2009\u20132010 presidential [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|elections]]|alt=Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard in parking lot, with blue and red letters on white background]]\nOn 5 November 2009 Bandi\u0107 announced his presidential candidacy in the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|2009\u20132010 presidential election]] after media speculation. Bandi\u0107's move resulted in his automatic expulsion from the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] and the loss of his positions as party president and leader of the Zagreb branch. He was replaced as leader of the Zagreb SDP by [[Davor Bernardi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=75175&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=34&cHash=098abf8794\n| title = HRT: Bernardi\u0107 na \u010delu zagreba\u010dkog SDP-a\n| year = 2010\n| accessdate = 2010-06-29\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the 27 December 2009 first round of the election Bandi\u0107 received 14.83 percent of the vote, placing him in second place after SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] (with 32.7 percent). On 10 January he lost the second round with 39.74 percent of the vote.\nIn Zagreb Bandi\u0107 lost both rounds of the election, receiving support in only a handful of city neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite web | work = Zagrebancija.com | url = http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | language = Croatian | title = Detaljna analiza kraha - Kako je Milan Bandi\u0107 izgubio povjerenje Zagreba | date = December 30, 2009 | accessdate = January 16, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100120181034/http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | archivedate = January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Ve\u010dernji list]] | url = http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/josipovic-potukao-bandica-gotovo-svim-zagrebackim-cetvrtima-clanak-77273 | language = Croatian | title = Donja Dubrava i Brezovica jedine Bandi\u0107eve \u010detvrti - Josipovi\u0107 potukao Bandi\u0107a u gotovo svim zagreba\u010dkim \u010detvrtima | date = January 10, 2010 | accessdate = January 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary election of 2011===\nOn 8 October 2011 Bandi\u0107 announced that he will compete in [[2011 Croatian parliamentary election|Croatian parliamentary election of 2011]] with independent list named \"Stijena\" ({{lang-en|Rock}}).<ref name=VL>[http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/bandic-izbore-ide-neovisnom-listom-koju-je-nazvao-stijena-clanak-334146 Bandi\u0107 na izbore ide s neovisnom listom koju je nazvao Stijena]. [[Ve\u010dernji list]], 2011-10-08. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref>\n\n===Fifth term (2013\u20132017)===\n{{See also|2013 Zagreb local elections}}\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Sixth term (2017\u2013present)===\n{{See also|2017 Zagreb local elections}}\n\n==Mayoral achievements==\n[[File:Milan Bandi\u0107 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bandi\u0107 at the [[Snow Queen Trophy]], January 2009|alt=Bandi\u0107 smiling and looking to his right, wearing blue-and-white skiing jersey over brown long-sleeved shirt]]\n[[File:Zagrebacka Avenija, Zagreb.JPG|thumb|right|Renovated [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]|alt=Aerial view of eight-lane highway]]\nOne of Bandi\u0107's best-known projects is the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]], whose eastern stretch beginning at Svilkovi\u0107i Street (later Savska Opatovina Rotary) was later renamed to [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]].<ref name=komunalni_lj-zg>{{cite journal\n |url=http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |title=Zastupnici skratili Ljubljansku \n |last=Kos Bu\u010dar \n |first=Dajana \n |language=Croatian \n |date=2006-10-11 \n |accessdate=2008-07-24 \n |journal=Zagreba\u010dki komunalni vjesnik \n |issue=338 \n |format=PDF, 108 KB \n |page=4 \n |issn=1845-4968 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529140837/http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |archivedate=2011-05-29 \n}}</ref> He is also credited with the Zagreb model apartment building ({{lang-hr|Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje}}), also locally known as ''Bandi\u0107evi stanovi'' (\"Bandi\u0107's apartments\").<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\" /> [[Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107]], another investor in the Zagreb apartment market, accused Bandi\u0107 of trying to undermine the statewide POS housing projects. POS ({{lang-hr|POticana Stanogradnja}}, \"subsidized apartments\") is cheap housing instituted by Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107 during the coalition of SDP, Bandi\u0107's party, and several other parties (such as \u010ca\u010di\u0107's HNS, which ruled the Croatian government from 2000 to 2003).<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| title = Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n| date = 2004-05-18\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = \u0160pansko.net\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629150931/http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| archive-date = 2011-06-29\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=hrt_zms>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |title       = Milan Bandi\u0107 najavio zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n |date        = 2002-02-22\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-03\n |work        = [[Croatian Radiotelevision]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091952/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-04\n}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 has heavily criticized the state of [[Transport in Zagreb|Zagreb's transportation system]] which he encountered at the beginning of his mayoral career.<ref name=jeza>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |title       = Bandi\u0107: Hvata me jeza zbog Remetine\u010dkog rotora\n |date        = 2008-04-10\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-29\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080412093330/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |archivedate = 2008-04-12\n}}</ref> With the guidance of Zagreb traffic engineers Bandi\u0107 has approved ambitious transportation projects in Zagreb, such as the Ljubljanska/Zagreba\u010dka Avenue widening, [[Homeland Bridge]] construction, renovation of the [[green wave]] system in the city center with the addition of [[bicycle path]]s and multi-level underground [[parking garages]] at [[Tu\u0161kanac]], [[Kvaternik Square]] and other locations. An important project begun during Bandi\u0107's term in office is the Zagreb [[light rail|metro]], which is planned to become the main suburban transportation mode to the city.<ref name=metro>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |format      = PDF\n |title       = Design concept and financing of the light rail Zagreb project\n |date        = 2006-09-22\n |last1       = Koli\u0107\n |first1      = Davorin\n |last2       = Marenjak\n |first2      = Sa\u0161a\n |last3       = Skendrovi\u0107\n |first3      = Vladimir\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-26\n |work        = Neuron Consulting Engineers\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711211147/http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |archivedate = 2007-07-11\n}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has arranged the construction of the [[Arena Zagreb]], a [[team handball|handball]] arena located in [[Lani\u0161te, Croatia|Lani\u0161te]], which was constructed to prepare the city for the [[2009 World Men's Handball Championship]].<ref name=arena_sanader>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=344911\n| title = Bandi\u0107 i Sanader dogovorili izgradnju dvorane Arena Zagreb, Ingra i TriGr\u00e1nit dobili posao\n| date = 2007-04-24\n| accessdate = 2008-08-07\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=\"arena_\u0161pricer\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34754/ |title=Bandi\u0107: \"Hladan sam k'o \u0161pricer\" |trans-title=Bandi\u0107: I'm as cool as can be |date=2007-05-25 |last=Zrinjski |first=Marijana |accessdate=2008-08-07 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=602 |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oiDfnqv?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34754/bandic-hladan-sam-ko-spricer |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nOn July 10, 2009, Bandi\u0107 was made an honorary citizen of [[Srebrenica]], Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914132454/http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2011 |title=Povelja op\u0161tine: Milan Bandi\u0107 po\u010dasni gra\u0111anin Srebrenice |author=A. B. |date=10 July 2009 |publisher=BiH Vijesti |accessdate=16 November 2011 |language=bs}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2018, [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] honored Bandi\u0107 with an [[Order of Friendship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Putin odlikovao Milana Bandi\u0107a Ordenom prijateljstva |url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/putin-odlikovao-milana-bandica-ordenom-prijateljstva-1264868 |website=vecernji.hr |accessdate=29 November 2018|language=hr}}</ref>\n\n==Health problems==\n\nOn 3 July 2003 after a session of the Zagreb City Council Bandi\u0107 requested medical assistance, stating that he had begun to feel ill during the session. The media reported that he had suffered a minor [[stroke]]; the official explanation was that exhaustion and overwork had caused a [[blood vessel]] in his [[endocranium]] to [[spasm]]. He was hospitalized for a few weeks, then went to [[Krapinske Toplice]] to recover, and returned to his duties in September.<ref name=\"ostojic bandic\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.vecernji.hr/lokalni-izbori/bitka-za-zagreb-kako-je-ostojic-bandicu-spasio-zivot-491484\n| title = Bitka za Zagreb: Kako je Ostoji\u0107 Bandi\u0107u spasio \u017eivot\n| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]\n| date = 28 December 2012\n| language = Croatian\n| accessdate = 3 March 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n{{Criticism section|date=October 2014}}\n\n==={{anchor|Land exchange case}}Land-exchange case===\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\n===''Cvjetni prolaz'' case===\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox>{{cite web |url=http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm \n |title=Eparhijski arhijerej |accessdate=2008-09-27 |work=Serbian orthodox church |language=Serbian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531230841/http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm |archivedate=2008-05-31 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov>{{cite web |url = http://www.glasistre.hr/?5bb51035b592e5bf7ec3a43bb6bb7e44,TS,1885,,11666,15206,150393, | title = Ne vjeruj Bandi\u0107u ni kad te triput ljubi | accessdate = 2008-02-17 | date = 2007-01-13 | work = Glas Istre | last = Vesi\u0107 | first = Vanja |language = Croatian}}</ref> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-psovkama-protiv-protivnika-projekta.html | title = Bandi\u0107 psovkama protiv protivnika projekta | accessdate = 2008-05-15 | date = 2007-01-27 | work = Dnevnik.hr | language = Croatian}}</ref> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\n=== ''Golden Toilets'' case ===\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\" /> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|accessdate=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===2014 arrest===\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged use of cocaine===\nAccording to some Croatian media, Bandi\u0107 is long time cocaine addict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dnevno.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/nas-je-gradonacelnik-zesci-ovisnik-o-kokainu-918248/ |title=Na\u0161 je gradona\u010delnik \u017ee\u0161\u0107i ovisnik o kokainu! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://100posto.jutarnji.hr/news/cak-se-ni-i-hdz-ovci-vise-se-skrivaju-s-travom-a-europarlamentarka-tvrdi-da-nam-je-sabor-pun-kokaina-bacilo-me-na-paranoju-u-strah-i-bilo-je-to-prvi-i-zadnji-put-da-sam/ |title=Kad se zabijeli Markov trg! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n===Minor controversies===\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz>{{cite web | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=277097 | title = Zuroff: Neka Bandi\u0107 sebi i suradnicima plati put u Auschwitz | date = 2005-08-02 | accessdate = 2008-09-28 | work = Vijesti.net | language = Croatian}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist>{{cite web |url = http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |title=Bandi\u0107 javno prijetio novinaru |date= 2006-01-17 |work= Bolji \u017eivot |language= Croatian |url-status= dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020755/http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |archivedate = 2007-09-28 |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May 2007 Bandi\u0107 fell asleep shortly before noon during a session of the Zagreb City Assembly; TV cameras captured the moment.<ref name=city_assembly_sleep>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-zaspao-na-sjednici-skupstine.html | title = Bandi\u0107 zaspao na sjednici Skup\u0161tine | accessdate = 2008-06-15 | date = 2007-06-01 | work = [[Dnevnik Nove TV]] | language = Croatian}}</ref> This was apparently not the first time he suffered from sleep problems; he fell asleep on 16 June 2006 at the [[Croatian National Theatre in Zagreb|Croatian National Theater]], where he presented an award to Marija Musta\u0107, secretary of the [[Croatian Association of the Blind]].\n\nIn May 2008 Bandi\u0107 left his car illegally parked at the center of [[\u0160ubi\u0107eva Street]], creating a road hazard and causing traffic problems; he held a public presentation of a camera system designed to issue [[traffic ticket|tickets]] to red-light runners, improperly-parked cars and the like. He then shopped in the [[Dolac Market|Dolac]] open-air market while his driver waited in the car, obstructing traffic. When questioned about this incident, Bandi\u0107 blamed it on his driver.<ref name=subiceva_road_obstruction>{{cite web |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |title=Bandi\u0107 najavio prometno redarstvo koje bi, kad bi ga bilo, ju\u010der najprije ulovilo njega |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2008-05-16 |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] |last=\u0160poljar |first=Marko |author2=Li\u0161anin, Mi\u0161o |language=Croatian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517135056/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |archivedate=2008-05-17 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n* [[List of mayors of Zagreb]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Josip Kregar]]\n(governor appointed by Croatian government)|\n years=2000\u20132002|\n after=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]|\n years=2005\u2013present |\n after=Incumbent\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandic, Milan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Political Sciences, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Grude]]\n[[Category:League of Communists of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Mayor\n| name         = Milan Bandi\u0107\n| image        = Dan OSRH Milan Bandic 28052011 2.jpg| width        = 220px\n| caption      = Bandi\u0107 on 28 May 2011\n| order        = 50th and 52nd\n| office       = Mayor of Zagreb\n| term_start1  = 15 May 2005\n| predecessor1 = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| successor1   = \n| term_start2  = 5 May 2000\n| term_end2    = 21 January 2002\n| predecessor2 = [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]]\n| successor2   = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| office3           = Leader of the [[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party|Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 -<br />Labour and Solidarity Party]] \n| term_start3    = 28 March 2015 \n| term_end3     =\n| predecessor3 = ''Position established'' \n| successor3     = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Grude]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]] {{small|(now [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]])}}\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Croatian\n| party        = {{plainlist|\n*[[League of Communists of Croatia]] {{small|(1980s)}}\n*[[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] {{small|(1990\u20132009)}}\n*[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] {{small|(2009\u20132015)}}\n*[[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n}}\n| other_party = \n| relations   =\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|1981|1996}}<br />{{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|2003}}<ref name=spouse_children />\n| children    = 1<ref name=spouse_children />\n| residence   = [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]]\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Zagreb]]\n| occupation  = [[Politician]]\n| profession  = \n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{About|the Croatian politician|the Croatian filmmaker who legally changed his name to Milan Bandi\u0107|Dario Juri\u010dan}}\n\n'''Milan Bandi\u0107''' ({{IPA-hr|m\u01d0lan b\u00e2\u02d0ndit\u0361\u0255:|hr}} {{small|({{Audio-nohelp|Milanbandicname.ogg|listen}})}}; born 22 November 1955) is a Croatian politician currently serving his sixth term as [[List of mayors of Zagreb|mayor]] of the Croatian capital, [[Zagreb]], since 2005. Between 2000 and 2009, he was a prominent member of the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP). In 2007, he unsuccessfully ran for party president. However, he remained one of the main rivals of the former party president [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]]. On 5 November 2009, he announced his intention to run for a president, in violation of the party's bylaws which led to his expulsion from the party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/video--bandic-krenuo-u-utrku-milan-ce-igrati-lopte-u-svakom-selu/458485.aspx |title=Video - Bandi\u0107 krenuo u utrku: \"Milan \u0107e igrati lopte u svakom selu\" |author= |date=5 November 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Index.hr]] |accessdate=16 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> On 10 January 2010, he lost the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|Croatian presidential election]] to the official SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] in the runoff elections.\n\nAlthough described in 2002 as the SDP's most popular politician for the \"famous 24 hours he devotes to the service of citizens of Zagreb\",<ref name=nin_omiljeni>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.nin.co.rs/2002-01/31/21760.html\n| title = Metropola bez gradona\u010delnika\n| date = 2002-01-31\n| last = Stanivukovi\u0107\n| first = Zoran\n| accessdate = 2008-09-19\n| work = [[\u041d\u0418\u041d]]\n| language = Serbian\n}}</ref> he has also gained notoriety for a number of actions and statements he has made as mayor.<ref name=javno_biografija/>\nBandi\u0107 is viewed as a hands-on mayor because of his ambition and the number of projects related to Zagreb that he has undertaken. He is widely credited{{fact|date=January 2020}} for the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]] (now [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]), for his work on the [[Arena Zagreb]] and the [[Homeland Bridge]] (which opened during his third term).\n\nBandi\u0107 was arrested in the evening hours of 19 October 2014, along with 18 other officials, under the suspicion of malfeasance related to [[Zagreb Holding]]. In his absence, his deputy [[Sandra \u0160valjek]] took the duties of mayor from 19 October 2014 until 26 March 2015.<ref>http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Novosti/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/279857/Bandi-opunomoio-Kusin-za-voenje-Zagreba.aspx</ref> Bandi\u0107 canceled the authorization that he granted to her because some disagreements between them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/jutarnji-doznaje-uhicen-milan-bandic-/1229175/ |title=Uhi\u0107eni Milan Bandi\u0107! |last1=De\u0161kovi\u0107 |first1=Marin |date=2014-10-19 |website=Jutarnji list |publisher=Jutarnji list |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtl.hr/vijesti/novosti/1367502/uhicen-milan-bandic-u-tijeku-pretraga-njegovog-stana/ |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107, u tijeku pretraga njegovog stana! |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014-10-19 |website=RTL Televizija |publisher=RTL Televizija |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref> Consequently, \u0160valjek has resigned all of her duties in city. Bandi\u0107's second deputy Vesna Kusin took the duties of mayor on 26 March 2015. On 10 April 2015, Zagreb County Court ruled that Milan Bandi\u0107 has to be released from prison while pending trial. Consequently, he returned to the position of Mayor.<ref>http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandic-ostaje-na-slobodi-i-vraca-se-na-mjesto-gradonacelnika/812562.aspx</ref>\n\n==Private life==\nMilan Bandi\u0107 was born to Jozo and Blagica Bandi\u0107 ([[n\u00e9e]] Tomi\u0107) in the small [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of Bandi\u0107a Brig, a part of Cerov Dolac in the municipality of [[Grude]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (then [[PR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[FPR Yugoslavia]]).<ref name=Bandic>Bandi\u0107, Milan. [http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 Biografija] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424082908/http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 |date=2008-04-24}}. Bandi\u0107's official web site. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He was the middle child in the family, with an older brother Drago and a younger sister Tonka.<ref name=Barilar>{{cite news |title=Bandi\u0107: Od doseljenika s koferom do neprikosnovenog vladara Zagreba |author=Barilar, Suzana |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/bandic--od-doseljenika-s-koferom-do-neprikosnovenog-vladara-zagreba/333515/ |newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]] |date=4 November 2009 |accessdate=20 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> His family's main source of income was a [[tobacco plantation]]. As a child, Bandi\u0107 was altar servant in local church.<ref name=Bandic/> He attended [[Antun Branko \u0160imi\u0107]] High School in Grude and he was excellent student.<ref name=Barilar/> In 1974, he moved to Zagreb to study at the Department of Political Science at the [[University of Zagreb]]<ref name=Bandic/>, program of National defense and social self-protection (today non-existent). To pay off his [[student loan]]s he unloaded sugar and coal<ref name=Bandic/> and he was also a [[masonry|mason]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-put-na-celo-zagreba-poceo-je-istovarom-secera-i-zbukanjem-fasada/778501.aspx | title=Bandi\u0107ev put na \u010delo Zagreba po\u010deo je istovarom \u0161e\u0107era i \u017ebukanjem fasada | date=19 October 2014 | work=[[Index.hr]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Bandi\u0107 was conscripted to the [[Yugoslav People's Army]], and after that he was employed in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo]], producer of ice creams.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring his student days he met his wife Vesna.<ref name=Bandic/> He was married to her until their divorce in 1996, although they still live together in their [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]] apartment. They have a daughter, Ana-Marija.<ref name=spouse_children>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=248861\n | title = Bandi\u0107 se 1996. razveo zbog otkupa stana?\n | date = 2005-02-10\n | accessdate = 2008-08-01\n | work = Vijesti.net\n | language = Croatian}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has stated that his divorce was the result of a seven-year separation.<ref name=spouse_children /> Bandi\u0107 owns two [[golden retriever]]s, Bil and Rudi, which he often walks during his work hours.<ref name=24sata_bil_operacija>{{cite web\n| url = http://damp.nsk.hr/arhiva/vol1/880/14301/www.24sata.hr/articles/view/48239/index.html\n| title = Bandi\u0107ev Bil ide na kemoterapiju?\n| date = 2007-03-22\n| last = Vukadin\n| first = Romana\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = [[24 sata (Croatia)|24 sata]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=bil_rudi>{{cite journal |date=2008-08-04 |title=Bandi\u0107u u dom sti\u017ee retriver Rudi |trans-title=Retriever Rudi arrives in Bandi\u0107 home |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=664 |language=Croatian |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47766/8/ |accessdate=2008-08-06 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oppVAzh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47766/bandicu-u-dom-stize-retriver-rudi |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 is an avid distance runner, describing himself as \"addicted to running\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Ne bojim se, imam jo\u0161 mnogo kilometara za pretr\u010dati| work=[[Jutarnji list]] | date=July 28, 2009 | language=Croatian | quote=Mogu re\u0107i da sam ovisan o tr\u010danju i da je to moja droga.}}</ref> He is reported to run 10 kilometers every weekday morning,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | title=PHOTO: Zagreb Mayor Turns Pilgrimage Into Marathon | work=javno.com | first=Ivan | last=Kova\u010d | date=September 15, 2008 | accessdate=2009-08-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520043315/http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | archivedate=May 20, 2009}}</ref> and in March 2008 completed the 61&nbsp;km [[Zagreb]]\u2013[[\u010cazma]] [[ultramarathon]].\n\n==Political career==\n{{POV section|date=April 2020}}\n==={{anchor|Before becoming a mayor}}Before becoming mayor===\nAfter serving the army and short work in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo company]] Bandi\u0107 was employed in Municipal Committee of [[League of Communists of Croatia]] in [[Pe\u0161\u010denica \u2013 \u017ditnjak|Pe\u0161\u0107enica]] where he worked as professional political worker.<ref name=Bandic/><ref name=Barilar/>\n\nAfter collapse of [[Socialist Federative Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]] and [[League of Communists of Croatia]] Bandi\u0107 did not want to leave the party because he worked for years in Pe\u0161\u010denica and thus it was matter of pride.<ref name=Bandic/> He expressed his hopes that he and his colleagues will return to political stage as Croatian social democrats.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring the [[Croatian War of Independence]] Bandi\u0107 helped with logistics.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nBandi\u0107 was one of the few [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Herzegovinian Croats]] to remain with the party after the [[1990 Croatian parliamentary election|first democratic elections in 1990]] in which the Communist Party, led by [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]], reformed and re-branded itself as the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (SDP). He demonstrated organizational ability and populist political instincts. These abilities allowed the SDP to gain in Zagreb blue-collar neighborhoods and attract votes which the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] (HDZ) and its then-president [[Franjo Tu\u0111man]] had considered theirs by default. As such, he proved to be a valuable asset for the Social Democratic Party. In 1993 he became party secretary.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\nConflict between HDZ and SDP manifested in the [[1995 Croatian parliamentary election|1995 parliamentary]] and City of [[Zagreb]] elections, leading to the [[Zagreb Crisis]]: an electoral alliance (in which the SDP was a major partner) won a majority in the Zagreb elections and chose [[Goran Grani\u0107]] as the new mayor, but Franjo Tu\u0111man used a legal loophole to stop Grani\u0107 from taking office. Several subsequent elections were held, with the SDP winning each time and Tu\u0111man promptly removing every candidate. For a time Zagreb was a city without a mayor, which led to public unrest and protests in [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]]. With the final 1997 election of the HDZ candidate [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]] as the mayor of Zagreb, the crisis faded. Bandi\u0107 played a role in the crisis by becoming a city councilman in 1995 and the leader of the Zagreb SDP in 1997.<ref name=javno_biografija>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/hrvatska/clanak.php?id=49365\n |title       = Biografija: Milan Bandi\u0107\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-01\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68EJ2pyfI?url=http://dalje.com/hr-hrvatska/biografija--milan-bandic/49365\n |archivedate = 2012-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first campaign his [[Herzegovina|Herzegovinian]] background became an issue, as the [[Croatian Peasant Party]] (HSS) suggested that only a native citizen of Zagreb could become the city's mayor. HSS also launched a propaganda campaign against [[Herzegovinians]] in an effort to undermine Bandi\u0107's campaign. The party hoped that the majority of Zagreb voters would turn away from Bandi\u0107. Those expectations were not fulfilled and Bandi\u0107 later used his Herzegovinian background as an advantage, broadening his support among the ordinary citizens of Zagreb.\n\nThe HDZ under Bandi\u0107 eventually lost power in the Croatian capital in 2000.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\n==={{anchor|First and second term (2000\u20132002)}}First and second terms (2000\u20132002)===\n{{see also|2000 Zagreb local elections|2001 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nBandi\u0107 was elected [[mayor]] of Zagreb in 2000<ref name=izbori>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | title = Izbori odr\u017eani 7. svibnja 2000.\n | work = Gradski zavod za automatsku obradu podataka\n | accessdate = 2008-07-27\n | language = Croatian\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100129103926/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | archive-date = 2010-01-29\n | url-status = dead\n}}</ref> and re-elected in the city election in 2001.<ref name=izbori_2001>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| title = Izbori odr\u017eani 20. svibnja 2001.\n| work = City Bureau for Automatic Data Processing\n| accessdate = 2008-08-04\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080316190322/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| archive-date = 2008-03-16\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref> His rise in influence among SDP politicians and on the Zagreb political scene created a backlash by the [[Croatian People's Party]] (HNS), the other left-of-center party led by [[Vesna Pusi\u0107]], who did not trust his nationalist populism and his occasional run-ins with the courts. The HNS campaigned against the SDP in the 2000 elections. However, the HNS entered into a coalition with the SDP in 2001. It governed Zagreb with the SDP until 2005 when it withdrew, again because of Bandi\u0107.\n\nIn 2002, Bandi\u0107 fled from the scene of a motor vehicle accident while under the influence of alcohol. He tried to bribe the officer who stopped him and threatened the officer with his alleged connections in the [[Ministry of the Interior (Croatia)|Ministry of the Interior]]. The incident was heavily covered by the media that asked for his resignation. The SDP was at first reluctant to sanction Bandi\u0107. Under public pressure, the SDP leadership compelled Bandi\u0107 to resign.<ref name=resignation>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti2/020121jl.htm| title = Bandi\u0107eva ostavka - pobjeda javnosti| accessdate = 2008-07-27| last = Lovri\u0107| first = Jelena| date = 2002-01-21| work = [[Novi list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti7/060118vm.htm| title = Esdepeovci zgro\u017eeni pona\u0161anjem Bandi\u0107a| accessdate = 2007-09-29| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2006-01-18| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=index_policemen>{{cite web| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=391401| title = Kako se rije\u0161iti policajca koji radi svoj posao| accessdate = 2008-09-21| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2008-06-17| work = Vijesti.net| language = Croatian}}</ref> After his resignation there was uncertainty concerning his successor; while the Zagreb SDP had the right to nominate the mayor, it was so dominated by Bandi\u0107 that it was questionable who could replace him.<ref name=resignation /> Eventually [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] took over as mayor, while Bandi\u0107 retained a place in the Zagreb chain of command as deputy mayor. He was eager to become a mayor again, and blocked Pavi\u0107's development plans (advancing his own) while working toward an early election.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=\"savez_desni\u010dari\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10596/\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 s desni\u010darima ru\u0161i Vlastu Pavi\u0107\n |date        = 2003-05-27\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-02\n |last        = Babi\u0107\n |first       = Jelena\n |issue       = 393\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |trans-title = Bandi\u0107 and right-wingers brings down Vlasta Pavi\u0107\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68oWiX4IA?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10596/bandic-s-desnicarima-rusi-vlastu-pavic\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10895/ |title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 u zamjenu za primirje ustupa mjesto Bandi\u0107u |last=Jelini\u0107 |first=Berislav |language=Croatian |trans-title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 steps down for Bandi\u0107 in exchange for a truce |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |date=24 February 2004 |accessdate=30 June 2012 |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oY6G8Cg?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10895/vlasta-pavic-u-zamjenu-za-primirje-ustupa-mjesto-bandicu |url-status=dead}}</ref> In response [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] (head of the SDP) tried to restrain Bandi\u0107's activities.<ref name=\"ra\u010dan_upozorenje\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10240/ |title=Ra\u010dan poti\u010de Vlastu Pavi\u0107 da vlada bez Bandi\u0107a |date=15 May 2002 |last=Ple\u0161e |first=Mladen |accessdate=30 June 2012 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |trans-title=Ra\u010dan urges Vlasta Pavi\u0107 to govern without Bandi\u0107 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oWJlgkS?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10240/racan-potice-vlastu-pavic-da-vlada-bez-bandica |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe rules then in force would not allow Bandi\u0107 to have a second term as mayor during the current term of the assembly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom |publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)]] |title=Ra\u010dan ustuknuo pred Bandi\u0107evim divlja\u0161tvom |trans-title=Ra\u010dan taken aback by Bandi\u0107's savage remark |language=Croatian |author=Berislav Jelini\u0107 |date=4 May 2004 |accessdate=1 July 2012 |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68pZwx7NY?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom}}</ref> Vlasta Pavi\u0107 attempted to strike a deal ending the ongoing feud, but Bandi\u0107 eventually succeeded in undermining her. Although no early elections were held, he was re-elected mayor in [[2005 Zagreb mayoral elections|the May 15, 2005 elections]].<ref name=izbori_2005>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| title = Rezultati glasovanja za izbor \u010dlanova Gradske skup\u0161tine Grada Zagreba (\"Voting results for the election of Municipal Councillors to the City of Zagreb\")\n| date = 2005-05-16\n| accessdate = 2008-08-01\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721102953/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| archive-date = 2011-07-21\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\" />\n\nIn April 2004 then-mayor [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] criticized Bandi\u0107 for having spent 15 million [[kuna (currency)|kunas]] (about [[USD|US$]]3.26 million) of city money to buy a lot on [[Vjekoslav Heinzel Avenue|Heinzelova Avenue]] which was formerly owned by the [[meat packing industry|meat packing plant]] Zagrep\u010danka. The controversy was dubbed \"the Zagrep\u010danka case\" by the newspapers.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> The city government could not use the lot, because its ownership was divided among 43 individuals. When (responding to a question from a city counselor) Mayor Pavi\u0107 distanced herself from Bandi\u0107, Bandi\u0107 was accused of cursing her mother in a vulgar way during the talks.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/clanak.aspx?id=199287\n| title = Milan Bandi\u0107 opsovao majku zagreba\u010dkoj gradona\u010delnici\n| accessdate = 2007-09-29\n| date = 2004-04-28\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> He also published a newspaper advertisement on behalf of the city government, entitled ''Istina je!'' (\"It's true!\"). The advertisement was supported by all SDP members of the city council except [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]], the mayor at that time. [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] later condemned the advertisement as a political mistake, telling the Zagreb SDP that they would face consequences for their action.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment/>\n\nA court case ensued, with charges being brought against Bandi\u0107 and others involved.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |title       = Kaznena prijava protiv Bandi\u0107a, Buluma i nekih \u010dlanova poglavarstva zbog oglasa ''Istina je!''\n |date        = 2004-05-10\n |publisher   = [[Croatian Radio Television]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |accessdate  = 2008-04-30\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170804/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-03\n}}</ref> Three years later, Bandi\u0107 was acquitted and the City of Zagreb was awarded ownership of the Zagrep\u010danka lot in a [[judgment (law)|court judgment]]. Bandi\u0107 promised a new [[business district]] in the Zagrep\u010danka location.<ref name=city_centar_zagrepcanka>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |title       = Zagreb To Get A City Centre\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612235956/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |archivedate = 2007-06-12\n}}</ref>\n\nNot all legal troubles have been solved, however, as the city still has to deal with unsolved cases and complaints entered against the lot.<ref name=plomba>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130126200636/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-01-26\n |title      = Bandi\u0107 isplatio ovrhu za Zagrep\u010danku - 3 mil kuna\n |date       = 2008-09-26\n |accessdate = 2008-09-28\n |work       = Javno.hr\n |language   = Croatian\n}}</ref> In 2008 the sale of the Zagrep\u010danka lot to [[Institut IGH]] was announced, but the deal fell through in 2009; this has potential to incur a cost of \u20ac4.5&nbsp;million to the Zagreb [[holding company]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.poslovni.hr/133686.aspx | title = Ivo \u010covi\u0107 ipak potpisao \u0161tetan ugovor s Radi\u0107em? | language = Croatian | work = [[Poslovni dnevnik]] | date = December 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Third term (2005\u20132009)===\n{{see also|2005 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nFollowing the illness and death of Ra\u010dan Bandi\u0107 announced his candidacy for SDP leadership,<ref name=nacional_kandidatura>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34638/\n |title       = Obra\u010dun Bandi\u0107a i Milanovi\u0107a odlu\u010duje o \u0161efu SDP-a\n |trans-title = Conflict of Bandi\u0107 and Milanovi\u0107 to decide leader of the SDP\n |date        = 2007-05-21\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-04\n |issue       = 601\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68ohfBem2?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34638/obracun-bandica-i-milanovica-odlucuje-o-sefu-sdp-a\n |url-status  = dead\n}}</ref> planning to resign as mayor afterwards. He competed against [[\u017deljka Antunovi\u0107]], [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] and [[Tonino Picula]]. [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] was elected on 2 June 2007 as the new SDP leader, while Bandi\u0107 remained mayor of Zagreb.<ref name=milanovic>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/35122/\n |title       = Milanovi\u0107 widens his base\n |accessdate  = 2007-09-30\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-06-06\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLPJQhh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/35122/milanovic-widens-his-base\n |issue       = 603\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref> He did not give up the fight, however, organizing opposition within the party and campaigning to defeat Milanovi\u0107 in the next party election.<ref name=\"revolt_milanovi\u0107\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/40824/\n |title       = Revolt against Milanovi\u0107\n |accessdate  = 2008-07-28\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLV04ei?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/40824/revolt-against-milanovic\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-12-12\n |issue       = 630\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref><ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_obra\u010dun\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/11033/Default.aspx\n| title = Milanovi\u0107 krenuo u obra\u010dun s Bandi\u0107em\n| accessdate = 2008-07-28\n| last = Karlovi\u0107-Saboti\u0107\n| first = Marina\n| date = 2008-06-12\n| work = [[Slobodna Dalmacija]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz />\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist />\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2008 the Main Committee of SDP received a letter entitled ''Za \u0161to se, uop\u0107e, danas zala\u017ee SDP?'' (\"What, overall, does the SDP stand for today?\") by [[Dra\u017een Lali\u0107]] (a Croatian [[sociologist]]) which attacked Bandi\u0107 by pointing out his misdeeds and errors and questioning Bandi\u0107's loyalty to the SDP's principles. The letter was sparked partially by the [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] of anti-corruption Zagreb road-authorities director Igor Ra\u0111enovi\u0107, which had not been properly investigated. Another reason was a concert held on [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]] by [[Marko Perkovi\u0107 Thompson]], a singer known to attract an [[Usta\u0161e|usta\u0161a]] audience. Bandi\u0107 supported the concert instead of condemning it, inaccordance with SDP anti-nationalistic principles. Although the letter attacked the SDP as a whole, Bandi\u0107 was considered a key participant in all events described. Bandi\u0107 responded to the letter indirectly by encouraging the police to do their job, while failing to appropriately defend his position.<ref name=lalic_letter>{{cite journal\n| last = Cigoj\n| first = Mark\n|author2=Galovi\u0107, Alen\n| title = Pismo koje potresa SDP\n| journal = [[Globus (weekly)|Globus]]\n| issue = 918\n| pages =18\u201322\n| url = http://www.globus.com.hr\n| date = 2008-07-11\n| accessdate = 2008-07-12\n}}</ref><ref name=\"lali\u0107_ve\u010dernji\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |title=Javne osobe pisale Milanovi\u0107u da zaustavi Bandi\u0107a \n |last=Popovi\u0107 \n |first=Jasmina \n |date=2008-07-09 \n |accessdate=2008-08-02 \n |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] \n |language=Croatian \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731053802/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |archivedate=2008-07-31 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> Zoran Milanovi\u0107 responded instead, accusing Lali\u0107 of trying to buy himself a return to the Croatian political scene. Bandi\u0107 thus received the SDP's support, ensuring his candidacy in the upcoming 2009 mayoral election.<ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_fights_back\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47300/ |title=Pismo koje je u\u010dvrstilo Bandi\u0107a |author1=Bajru\u0161i, Robert |trans-title=A letter that strengthened Bandi\u0107 |author2=Gaura, Orhidea |date=2008-07-14 |accessdate=2008-08-02 |issue=661 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oon0FPx?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47300/pismo-koje-je-ucvrstilo-bandica}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox /> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov /> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing /> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-kum-izgradio-najskuplji-wc-u-hrvatskoj-20090318|title=Bandi\u0107ev kum izgradio najskuplji WC u Hrvatskoj|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|accessdate=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Fourth term (2009\u20132013)===\n{{see also|2009 Zagreb local elections}}\nUntil 2009, the mayor of Zagreb was elected by the city assembly ([[city council]]). In [[2009 Zagreb local elections|elections held in the spring of 2009]], the mayor was directly elected for the first time. Bandi\u0107 was forced into a second round not by HDZ candidate ([[Jasen Mesi\u0107]]) but by outsider [[Josip Kregar]] (dean of the Faculty of Law at the [[University of Zagreb]]), who ran on an independent platform. Bandi\u0107 won the second round, with 62 percent of the vote to Kregar's 37 percent. In October 2009, Bandi\u0107 visited the site of a World War II [[Yugoslav Partisans|partisan]] massacre on the island of [[Daksa (Dubrovnik)|Daksa]] with the [[Croatian Bishops' Conference]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Dubrovnik/tabid/75/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/75337/Default.aspx | title=Daksa kod Dubrovnika: biskupi molili za \u017ertve komunisti\u010dkog terora - do\u0161ao i Milan Bandi\u0107 | work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]] | date=October 21, 2009 | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> On 29 October 2009 Bandi\u0107's proposed exceptional budget, with a proposal to hold a referendum on the building of a new football stadium, was rejected. Among those voting against the budget was his own party, the SDP.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=51872&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=38&cHash=8a5414470f | title=I SDP protiv Bandi\u0107a | date=October 29, 2009 | work=hrt.hr | publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302221451/http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48 | archivedate=March 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential campaign===\n[[File:Milan bandi\u0107 poster.JPG|thumb|240px|Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard during second round of 2009\u20132010 presidential [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|elections]]|alt=Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard in parking lot, with blue and red letters on white background]]\nOn 5 November 2009 Bandi\u0107 announced his presidential candidacy in the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|2009\u20132010 presidential election]] after media speculation. Bandi\u0107's move resulted in his automatic expulsion from the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] and the loss of his positions as party president and leader of the Zagreb branch. He was replaced as leader of the Zagreb SDP by [[Davor Bernardi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=75175&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=34&cHash=098abf8794\n| title = HRT: Bernardi\u0107 na \u010delu zagreba\u010dkog SDP-a\n| year = 2010\n| accessdate = 2010-06-29\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the 27 December 2009 first round of the election Bandi\u0107 received 14.83 percent of the vote, placing him in second place after SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] (with 32.7 percent). On 10 January he lost the second round with 39.74 percent of the vote.\nIn Zagreb Bandi\u0107 lost both rounds of the election, receiving support in only a handful of city neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite web | work = Zagrebancija.com | url = http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | language = Croatian | title = Detaljna analiza kraha - Kako je Milan Bandi\u0107 izgubio povjerenje Zagreba | date = December 30, 2009 | accessdate = January 16, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100120181034/http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | archivedate = January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Ve\u010dernji list]] | url = http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/josipovic-potukao-bandica-gotovo-svim-zagrebackim-cetvrtima-clanak-77273 | language = Croatian | title = Donja Dubrava i Brezovica jedine Bandi\u0107eve \u010detvrti - Josipovi\u0107 potukao Bandi\u0107a u gotovo svim zagreba\u010dkim \u010detvrtima | date = January 10, 2010 | accessdate = January 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary election of 2011===\nOn 8 October 2011 Bandi\u0107 announced that he will compete in [[2011 Croatian parliamentary election|Croatian parliamentary election of 2011]] with independent list named \"Stijena\" ({{lang-en|Rock}}).<ref name=VL>[http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/bandic-izbore-ide-neovisnom-listom-koju-je-nazvao-stijena-clanak-334146 Bandi\u0107 na izbore ide s neovisnom listom koju je nazvao Stijena]. [[Ve\u010dernji list]], 2011-10-08. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref>\n\n===Fifth term (2013\u20132017)===\n{{See also|2013 Zagreb local elections}}\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Sixth term (2017\u2013present)===\n{{See also|2017 Zagreb local elections}}\n\n==Mayoral achievements==\n[[File:Milan Bandi\u0107 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bandi\u0107 at the [[Snow Queen Trophy]], January 2009|alt=Bandi\u0107 smiling and looking to his right, wearing blue-and-white skiing jersey over brown long-sleeved shirt]]\n[[File:Zagrebacka Avenija, Zagreb.JPG|thumb|right|Renovated [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]|alt=Aerial view of eight-lane highway]]\nOne of Bandi\u0107's best-known projects is the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]], whose eastern stretch beginning at Svilkovi\u0107i Street (later Savska Opatovina Rotary) was later renamed to [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]].<ref name=komunalni_lj-zg>{{cite journal\n |url=http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |title=Zastupnici skratili Ljubljansku \n |last=Kos Bu\u010dar \n |first=Dajana \n |language=Croatian \n |date=2006-10-11 \n |accessdate=2008-07-24 \n |journal=Zagreba\u010dki komunalni vjesnik \n |issue=338 \n |format=PDF, 108 KB \n |page=4 \n |issn=1845-4968 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529140837/http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |archivedate=2011-05-29 \n}}</ref> He is also credited with the Zagreb model apartment building ({{lang-hr|Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje}}), also locally known as ''Bandi\u0107evi stanovi'' (\"Bandi\u0107's apartments\").<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\" /> [[Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107]], another investor in the Zagreb apartment market, accused Bandi\u0107 of trying to undermine the statewide POS housing projects. POS ({{lang-hr|POticana Stanogradnja}}, \"subsidized apartments\") is cheap housing instituted by Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107 during the coalition of SDP, Bandi\u0107's party, and several other parties (such as \u010ca\u010di\u0107's HNS, which ruled the Croatian government from 2000 to 2003).<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| title = Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n| date = 2004-05-18\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = \u0160pansko.net\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629150931/http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| archive-date = 2011-06-29\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=hrt_zms>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |title       = Milan Bandi\u0107 najavio zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n |date        = 2002-02-22\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-03\n |work        = [[Croatian Radiotelevision]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091952/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-04\n}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 has heavily criticized the state of [[Transport in Zagreb|Zagreb's transportation system]] which he encountered at the beginning of his mayoral career.<ref name=jeza>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |title       = Bandi\u0107: Hvata me jeza zbog Remetine\u010dkog rotora\n |date        = 2008-04-10\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-29\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080412093330/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |archivedate = 2008-04-12\n}}</ref> With the guidance of Zagreb traffic engineers Bandi\u0107 has approved ambitious transportation projects in Zagreb, such as the Ljubljanska/Zagreba\u010dka Avenue widening, [[Homeland Bridge]] construction, renovation of the [[green wave]] system in the city center with the addition of [[bicycle path]]s and multi-level underground [[parking garages]] at [[Tu\u0161kanac]], [[Kvaternik Square]] and other locations. An important project begun during Bandi\u0107's term in office is the Zagreb [[light rail|metro]], which is planned to become the main suburban transportation mode to the city.<ref name=metro>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |format      = PDF\n |title       = Design concept and financing of the light rail Zagreb project\n |date        = 2006-09-22\n |last1       = Koli\u0107\n |first1      = Davorin\n |last2       = Marenjak\n |first2      = Sa\u0161a\n |last3       = Skendrovi\u0107\n |first3      = Vladimir\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-26\n |work        = Neuron Consulting Engineers\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711211147/http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |archivedate = 2007-07-11\n}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has arranged the construction of the [[Arena Zagreb]], a [[team handball|handball]] arena located in [[Lani\u0161te, Croatia|Lani\u0161te]], which was constructed to prepare the city for the [[2009 World Men's Handball Championship]].<ref name=arena_sanader>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=344911\n| title = Bandi\u0107 i Sanader dogovorili izgradnju dvorane Arena Zagreb, Ingra i TriGr\u00e1nit dobili posao\n| date = 2007-04-24\n| accessdate = 2008-08-07\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=\"arena_\u0161pricer\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34754/ |title=Bandi\u0107: \"Hladan sam k'o \u0161pricer\" |trans-title=Bandi\u0107: I'm as cool as can be |date=2007-05-25 |last=Zrinjski |first=Marijana |accessdate=2008-08-07 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=602 |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oiDfnqv?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34754/bandic-hladan-sam-ko-spricer |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nOn July 10, 2009, Bandi\u0107 was made an honorary citizen of [[Srebrenica]], Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914132454/http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2011 |title=Povelja op\u0161tine: Milan Bandi\u0107 po\u010dasni gra\u0111anin Srebrenice |author=A. B. |date=10 July 2009 |publisher=BiH Vijesti |accessdate=16 November 2011 |language=bs}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2018, [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] honored Bandi\u0107 with an [[Order of Friendship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Putin odlikovao Milana Bandi\u0107a Ordenom prijateljstva |url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/putin-odlikovao-milana-bandica-ordenom-prijateljstva-1264868 |website=vecernji.hr |accessdate=29 November 2018|language=hr}}</ref>\n\n==Health problems==\n\nOn 3 July 2003 after a session of the Zagreb City Council Bandi\u0107 requested medical assistance, stating that he had begun to feel ill during the session. The media reported that he had suffered a minor [[stroke]]; the official explanation was that exhaustion and overwork had caused a [[blood vessel]] in his [[endocranium]] to [[spasm]]. He was hospitalized for a few weeks, then went to [[Krapinske Toplice]] to recover, and returned to his duties in September.<ref name=\"ostojic bandic\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.vecernji.hr/lokalni-izbori/bitka-za-zagreb-kako-je-ostojic-bandicu-spasio-zivot-491484\n| title = Bitka za Zagreb: Kako je Ostoji\u0107 Bandi\u0107u spasio \u017eivot\n| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]\n| date = 28 December 2012\n| language = Croatian\n| accessdate = 3 March 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n{{Criticism section|date=October 2014}}\n\n==={{anchor|Land exchange case}}Land-exchange case===\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\n===''Cvjetni prolaz'' case===\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox>{{cite web |url=http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm \n |title=Eparhijski arhijerej |accessdate=2008-09-27 |work=Serbian orthodox church |language=Serbian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531230841/http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm |archivedate=2008-05-31 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov>{{cite web |url = http://www.glasistre.hr/?5bb51035b592e5bf7ec3a43bb6bb7e44,TS,1885,,11666,15206,150393, | title = Ne vjeruj Bandi\u0107u ni kad te triput ljubi | accessdate = 2008-02-17 | date = 2007-01-13 | work = Glas Istre | last = Vesi\u0107 | first = Vanja |language = Croatian}}</ref> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-psovkama-protiv-protivnika-projekta.html | title = Bandi\u0107 psovkama protiv protivnika projekta | accessdate = 2008-05-15 | date = 2007-01-27 | work = Dnevnik.hr | language = Croatian}}</ref> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\n=== ''Golden Toilets'' case ===\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\" /> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|accessdate=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===2014 arrest===\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged use of cocaine===\nAccording to some Croatian media, Bandi\u0107 is long time cocaine addict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dnevno.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/nas-je-gradonacelnik-zesci-ovisnik-o-kokainu-918248/ |title=Na\u0161 je gradona\u010delnik \u017ee\u0161\u0107i ovisnik o kokainu! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://100posto.jutarnji.hr/news/cak-se-ni-i-hdz-ovci-vise-se-skrivaju-s-travom-a-europarlamentarka-tvrdi-da-nam-je-sabor-pun-kokaina-bacilo-me-na-paranoju-u-strah-i-bilo-je-to-prvi-i-zadnji-put-da-sam/ |title=Kad se zabijeli Markov trg! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n===Minor controversies===\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz>{{cite web | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=277097 | title = Zuroff: Neka Bandi\u0107 sebi i suradnicima plati put u Auschwitz | date = 2005-08-02 | accessdate = 2008-09-28 | work = Vijesti.net | language = Croatian}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist>{{cite web |url = http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |title= Bandi\u0107 javno prijetio novinaru |accessdate= 2007-09-11 |date= 2006-01-17 |work= Bolji \u017eivot |language= Croatian |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020755/http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |archivedate = 2007-09-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May 2007 Bandi\u0107 fell asleep shortly before noon during a session of the Zagreb City Assembly; TV cameras captured the moment.<ref name=city_assembly_sleep>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-zaspao-na-sjednici-skupstine.html | title = Bandi\u0107 zaspao na sjednici Skup\u0161tine | accessdate = 2008-06-15 | date = 2007-06-01 | work = [[Dnevnik Nove TV]] | language = Croatian}}</ref> This was apparently not the first time he suffered from sleep problems; he fell asleep on 16 June 2006 at the [[Croatian National Theatre in Zagreb|Croatian National Theater]], where he presented an award to Marija Musta\u0107, secretary of the [[Croatian Association of the Blind]].\n\nIn May 2008 Bandi\u0107 left his car illegally parked at the center of [[\u0160ubi\u0107eva Street]], creating a road hazard and causing traffic problems; he held a public presentation of a camera system designed to issue [[traffic ticket|tickets]] to red-light runners, improperly-parked cars and the like. He then shopped in the [[Dolac Market|Dolac]] open-air market while his driver waited in the car, obstructing traffic. When questioned about this incident, Bandi\u0107 blamed it on his driver.<ref name=subiceva_road_obstruction>{{cite web |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |title=Bandi\u0107 najavio prometno redarstvo koje bi, kad bi ga bilo, ju\u010der najprije ulovilo njega |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2008-05-16 |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] |last=\u0160poljar |first=Marko |author2=Li\u0161anin, Mi\u0161o |language=Croatian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517135056/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |archivedate=2008-05-17 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n* [[List of mayors of Zagreb]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Josip Kregar]]\n(governor appointed by Croatian government)|\n years=2000\u20132002|\n after=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]|\n years=2005\u2013present |\n after=Incumbent\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandic, Milan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Political Sciences, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Grude]]\n[[Category:League of Communists of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milan_Bandi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Thoothukudi massacre", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Thoothukudi police firing|2=Talk:Thoothukudi massacre#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       =Thoothukudi Massacare\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| map         = {{Location map|Tamil Nadu|lat=8.48|long=78.04|caption=}}\n| map_caption = Location of Thoothukudi in Tamil Nadu\n| location    = [[Thoothukudi]], Tamil Nadu, [[India]]\n| target      = Protestors against [[Sterlite Copper]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|8.784117|78.099142|display=inline,title}}\n| date        = 22 May 2018\n| time        = \n| timezone    = UTC+5:30\n| type        = [[Shooting]]<!-- Don't change without valid reference -->\n| fatalities  = 13<!-- Don't change without valid reference --><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 15 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| injuries    = 102<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 13 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| perps       = [[Tamil Nadu Police]] & Paramilitary forces\n| weapons     = [[L1A1 SLR]] [[battle rifle]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/news/tamilnadu/125778-this-is-the-type-of-rifle-used-in-tuticorin.html |title=\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd 11 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b89\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8 \u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0b87\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0bcd}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/massacre-thoothukudi-intelligence-failure-or-deliberate-assault-81865 |title=The police firing in Thoothukudi: Intelligence failure or deliberate assault?}}</ref>\n| numparts    =\n}}\n\n[[File:Sterlitejpg.jpg|thumb|Protesters in large numbers take out a march against the Sterlite copper plant on May 22, 2018.]]The '''Thoothukudi Massacre''' (also known as the '''Thoothukudi police firing''' or '''Sterlite protest firing''') took place on 22 May 2018 in [[Thoothukudi]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India, when [[Tamil Nadu Police]] officers fired into a protest of 20,000 people, killing 13 protesters and injuring dozens of others.<ref name=\"financialexpress\" /> The protest was against the [[Sterlite Copper]] factory, which was accused of causing environmental pollution.<ref name=\"financialexpress\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/sterlite-protest-in-tuticorin-9-killed-in-tamil-nadu-top-developments-history-reasons-behind-violence/1177652/|title=Reasons behind Killings|last=|first=|date=|work=The Financial Express|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSterlite Copper has been facing resistance from the local fishermen\u2019s groups in the area ever since the plant was given permission to be established by the J Jayalaitha AIADMK in 1993.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sudhakar|first=P.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/for-sterlite-its-crisis-situation-once-again/article4564893.ece|title=For Sterlite, it's crisis situation once again|date=2013-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Sporadic protests have occurred in [[Thoothukudi]] since 1999, directed against the Sterlite Copper smelting works, the factory owned by [[Vedanta Limited]], a subsidiary of [[Vedanta Resources]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/variety/sterlite-protests-sulphur-dioxide-vedanta-tamil-nadu/story/1/23101.html|title=Why hundreds of Tamils won't quit protests against Vedanta's Sterlite|website=www.dailyo.in|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> Protesters opposed the soil, water and air contamination caused by the factory.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/sterlite-s-pollution-problem-113041801267_1.html|title=Sterlite's pollution problem|date=2013-04-18|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Pollution studies ===\nAn epidemiological study carried out by [[Tirunelveli Medical College]] in 2006\u201307 found an increased prevalence of respiratory diseases and ear, nose and throat (ENT) morbidity in the 5-km radius of Sterlite Industries. The study reported the prevalence of respiratory diseases in the area at 13.9% which was far higher than the state average. The prevalence of asthmatic bronchitis is 2.8%, which more than two-times the state average of 1.29%. Myalgia (general body pain) is another extensively reported symptom and women were often found to have menstrual disorders, like [[Menorrhagia|menorrhagiae]] and dysmenorrhagiae in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite - here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|last=Jayaraman|first=Nityanand|date=April 1, 2018|website=thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Their report blamed it on the air pollution caused by the industry's thermal power plants and automobiles in the area.<ref>{{cite book | last = Elango  | first = S. | title = Health status and Epidemiological study around 5&nbsp;km radius of Sterlite Industries (India) Limited, Thoothukudi | publisher = Tirunelveli Medical College | date = Oct 2008 | location = Tirunelveli | pages = 106 | language = English | url = https://poromboke.files.wordpress.com/2018/03/health-report-sterlite_edited.pdf}}</ref> The [[groundwater]] iron content in the area of the plant has been found to be 17\u201320 times the allowable limit, causing additional health problems for the population already experiencing higher than average incidence of respiratory diseases. During the time of this Study at 2007, Sterlite was operating about about 18 to 42 percentage, compared to its 4 Lakh Tonnes per Annum in the year 2017-2018.<ref name=\"newsminute\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|date=2018-04-01|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/jul/29/sterlite-keen-to-expand-operation-in-thoothukudi-1850064.html|title=Sterlite keen to expand operation in Thoothukudi|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\nThe 1998 report by [[National Environmental Engineering Research Institute]] (NEERI), the levels of selenium, arsenic and lead in treated effluent were higher than specified standards. The team also found dead birds after they consumed the water mixed with the effluent and also reported that the industry's process of cooling the effluents can cause health hazards to the staff and residents in the local region. In another instance, the NEERI reported water samples from dugwells and borewells around the spot were found to be non-[[Drinking water|drinkable]] due to its high chemical content. During 1998, the industry was operating at 10% capacity, compared to that of 2018.  <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-data-how-smelter-likely-cause-water-pollution-79055|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's proof: The data on how the smelter is likely cause for water pollution|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/environment/neeri-made-way-for-sterlite-to-pollute-tuticorin-60647|title=NEERI made way for Sterlite to pollute Tuticorin|last=|first=|date=|website=downtoearth.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2005 environmental audit by NEERI, the samples from a village 2-km northwest of the factory had levels of cadmium, copper, lead, chromium, and arsenic 2 to 9 times higher than allowed levels. Soil Samples were also analyzed in areas surrounding the plant during the study and [[Arsenic poisoning|arsenic]] levels ranged from 133 mg/kg to 287 mg/kg, where soils containing more than 50 mg/kg of arsenic are supposed to treated as a 'hazardous wastes' under the Indian Law.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn October 2010, Sampling tests by an NGO, Community Environmental Monitoring, found salinity level in an open well to be of 7854 mg/litre while levels exceeding 2000 mg/litre can badly damage the crops. Another water sample from a bore-well had [[sulfate]] levels 10 times higher than the average. A soil sample from the same spot contained 335 g/kg of iron and a ingestion of just 3.5 grams by a child can be a serious case of [[Iron poisoning|Iron Poisoning]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA Scientific study in 2017, found most of the ground water samples in the area are highly contaminated with heavy metals like arsenic, lead, boron etc. which were higher than the [[World Health Organization]]'s prescribed limit.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Selvam|first=S.|last2=Antony Ravindran|first2=A.|last3=Venkatramanan|first3=S.|last4=Singaraja|first4=C.|date=2017-05-01|title=Assessment of heavy metal and bacterial pollution in coastal aquifers from SIPCOT industrial zones, Gulf of Mannar, South Coast of Tamil Nadu, India|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|journal=Applied Water Science|language=en|volume=7|issue=2|pages=897\u2013913|doi=10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|issn=2190-5495}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board (TNPCB) observed that the unit has been releasing poisonous gas in the air. TNPCB identified that the sulphur dioxide levels went off the scale on the night of March 23, 2013. It showed a reading of 2939.55-mg/cubic meter against the decreed limit of 1250 mg/cubic meter.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2018/columnists/sterlite-protests-reach-a-climax.html|title=Sterlite protests reach a climax|last=Pioneer|first=The|website=The Pioneer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2018, the TNPCB accused the Sterlite Copper of causing groundwater pollution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/governance/sterlite-typifies-all-that-s-wrong-with-environmental-governance-in-india-60877|title=Sterlite typifies all that's wrong with environmental governance in India|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Gas leaks ===\nOn July 7th 1997, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board told the company to shut down after a sulphur dioxide gas leak which hospitalized more than 90 people.<ref>{{Cite news|last=BSCAL|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/sterlite-told-to-shut-plant-following-gas-leak-197070701041_1.html|title=Sterlite Told To Shut Plant Following Gas Leak|date=1997-07-07|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Sterlite Copper factory also made headlines in 2013 after a suspected sulphur dioxide gas leak from one of its smelter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sterlite-plant-idINDEE93005C20130401|title=Sterlite ordered to shut large copper smelter over 'gas leak'|date=2013-04-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref> The plant was blamed for health issues observed in the area related to gas leakage and residents near-by complained of coughing, [[wheezing]], eye iritation, and [[Miscarriage|miscarriages]] following the leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1287476/sterlite-coppers-20-years-in-thoothukudi-have-been-marked-by-deaths-miscarriages-and-endless-protests/|title=Protests, miscarriages, deaths: Sterlite Copper's 20 years in Thoothukudi|last=Thomas|first=Sushma U. N, Maria|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Following the alleged gas leak in March 2013, the then chief minister, the late [[J. Jayalalithaa]], ordered its closure. The company appealed to the [[National Green Tribunal Act|National Green Tribunal]], which overturned the government order. The state moved the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] against it, where the petition was still pending. The plant closed on March 27 of 2018, with the company citing a 15-day maintenance process.<ref name=\"financialexpress\" /> The Supreme Court ordered the company to pay a 100-crore fine for polluting the water, air and soil around the plant and the factory was temporarily shutdown by the pollution regulator.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sc-slaps-rs-100-cr-penalty-on-sterlite-for-pollution/article4572805.ece|title=SC slaps Rs. 100 cr. penalty on Sterlite for pollution|last=Venkatesan|first=J.|date=2013-04-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> About 150 people were arrested in protests against the plant.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn June 2019, the Tamil Nadu government reported that there were 84 incidents of gas leaks at Sterlite Copper in the year 2013 alone, to the [[Madras High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/84-gas-leaks-at-sterlite-in-2013-alone-tn-tells-madras-hc/articleshow/69881981.cms|title=84 gas leaks at Sterlite in 2013 alone, Tamil Nadu tells Madras HC {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Jun 21|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=11:52}}</ref>\n\n== Protests ==\nA wave of protests began on March 24, 2018 after the Sterlite Copper announced its plans to expand the plant, people around Kumarettiyapuram village protested for more than 100 days. Later the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board rejected the application by the company for clearance. The protesters claimed that the company went on to expand despite the rejection by the government.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Radhakrishnan|first=Sruthi|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/the-hindu-explains-sterlite-protests/article23969542.ece|title=The Hindu explains: Sterlite protests|date=2018-05-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vikatan.com/social-affairs/environment/120896-after-kumarettiyapuram-pandarampatti-village-people-joins-sterlite-protest-in-thoothukudi|title=\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b9f\u0bcd \u0b86\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b8e\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bae\u0bcd!|last=|first=|date=|website=vikatan.com|language=ta|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/27/anti-sterlite-in-thoothukudi-heart-of-darkness-1819970.html|title=Anti-Sterlite in Thoothukudi: Heart of darkness|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The protests were joined by traders of Thoothukudi city central trade association on the same day following calls for a [[bandh]] by environmental activist M Krishnamoorthi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/200318/thoothukudi-foreign-hand-behind-anti-sterlite-stir.html|title=Thoothukudi: 'Foreign hand' behind anti-Sterlite stir|date=2018-03-20|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThe protesters wanted the company's smelting unit in Thoothukudi shut down as it was causing environmental damage to the area. The company has been accused of being negligent regarding environmental management, causing harm to the health of the locals in and around Thoothukudi.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe District Administration called up 23 people belonging to the trader associations and anti-sterlite activists from the protesters including the environmental activist Fatima Babu on 20th May for a peace meeting. The members agreed to shift the venue after pressure from the government, from the Collector's Office to another place and to change the course of the protest to only get validation. Fatima was soon expelled by the protesting group after she agreed with the government's conditions.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/tuticorin-protests-sterlite-industries-illegally-obtained-environmental-clearance-activist-fatima-babu-tells-madras-high-court-4480681.html|title=Tuticorin protests: Sterlite Industries 'illegally obtained' environmental clearance, activist Fatima Babu tells Madras High Court|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nTwo groups of people protested separately on 22nd May. One of the was protesting a attention-seeking protest at SAV ground  and the other was marching towards the Collector's office. Soon both the groups joined together and marched toward the Collector's office. Police resorted to [[lathi charge]] and fired tear gas shells at the crowd after disagreeing with the protesters who wanted to stage a sit-in. There were about 2000 police personnel and a crowd of over 20,000 protesters. The district administration neglected intelligence reports of mass mobilization of over 18,000 people in the district.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAn employee of the Sterlite Copper claimed the involvement of groups like Makkal Athikaram and Foil Vedanta in the protests.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/880329/view-from-the-other-side-sterlite-workers-attacked-by-thoothukudi-protestors-recall-the-terror|title=View from the other side: Sterlite workers attacked by Thoothukudi protestors recall the terror|last=Govindarajan|first=Vinita|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Firing==\n\nOn May 22, 2018, thousands of people began to march to the district collector's office to submit a petition when the \"[[section 144]]\" was imposed. Section 144 makes a gathering of more than four people unlawful but an unofficial release said 20,000 people took out a procession towards the district-collector's office and the copper plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/05/27/sterlite-protest-section-144-lifted-in-thoothukudi.html|title=Sterlite protest: Section 144 lifted in Thoothukudi|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Protestors were successful in entering the premises of the collectorate. The police started shooting against the protesters, \"without any formal warning\" after tear gas and lathi charge proved ineffective.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/anti-sterlite-protests-tuticorin-villagers-accuse-left-outfit-of-inciting-violence-5247129/|title=Anti-Sterlite protests: Tuticorin villagers accuse Left outfit of inciting violence|date=2018-07-06|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nThe police started shooting at the protesters and were also accused of shooting without any formal warning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Police were also reported of intentionally shooting at the heads of the protesters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/police-targeted-protesters-shot-head-victims-families-671547.html|title=Police targeted the protesters; shot at head|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> 13 protesters were killed including a 17-year old school student, and dozens were injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/she-wanted-be-lawyer-her-dreams-lie-box-thoothukudi-teen-victim-s-kin-81854|title=She wanted to be a lawyer, her dreams lie in a box|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"fivedays\" /><ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/as-tuticorin-weeps-for-13-felled-in-police-firing-a-quite-rage-persists/articleshow/64334132.cms</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-police-fired-from-assault-rifles-on-anti-sterlite-protesters-heard-saying-at-least-one-should-die-2110643.html|title=Tamil Nadu Police fired from assault rifles on anti-Sterlite protesters, heard saying at least one should die{{!}} Zee News India|website=zeenews.india.com|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>\n\n[[First information report|FIR]]<nowiki/>s filed in local police stations, claimed that the order to shoot was issued by officers in the rank of deputy Tehsildars and people pointed out that only Collectors have the authority to issue shooting orders.<ref name=\"TH20180529-1\">{{cite news | last = Pon Vasanth | first = B. A | title = Three officers in the rank of deputy tahsildar issued firing orders in Thoothukudi, say FIRs | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Madurai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 29 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/3-deputy-tahsildars-issued-firing-orders-say-firs/article24017934.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu government ordered a shutdown of Internet in the entire districts of Tuticorin, Tirunelveli and Kanyakumari for five days after the firing.<ref name=\"fivedays\">{{cite web |title=Sterlite protest: Tamil Nadu orders internet suspension for five days in three southern districts |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/23/sterlite-protest-tamil-nadu-orders-internet-suspension-for-five-days-in-three-southern-districts-1818574.html |website=New Indian Express |accessdate=9 July 2018 |date=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n==Reactions==\n\n* [[Thirumurugan Gandhi]], the coordinator of [[May 17 Movement]], took the issue to the 38th session of the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]], Geneva in July 2018. On 9 August 2018, Thirumurugan Gandhi was detained by immigration authorities at Bangalore Airport on his return to India and charged under Section 124 A (sedition), 153 A (1) and 153 (b) of IPC for speaking about the Thoothukudi firings at the UNHRC. Court, later, refused to remand him under judicial custody as it found the charges are baseless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/court-refuses-detain-activist-thirumurugan-gandhi-86351|title=Court refuses to detain activist Thirumurugan Gandhi|date=2018-08-10|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/aug/10/thirumurugan-gandhi-held-in-bengaluru-for-un-speech-on-police-firing-in-thoothukudi-1855732.html|title=Thirumurugan Gandhi held in Bengaluru for UN speech on police firing in Thoothukudi|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n* [[Indian National Congress]] party president [[Rahul Gandhi]] described it as \"[[state-sponsored terrorism]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/india/anti-sterlite-protest-gunning-down-9-people-by-police-in-tamil-nadu-is-state-sponsored-terrorism-says-rahul-gandhi-2110523.html?src=fb|title=Anti-Sterlite protest: Gunning down 9 people by police in Tamil Nadu is state-sponsored terrorism, says Rahul Gandhi|date=2018-05-22|work=Zee News|access-date=2018-05-22|language=en}}</ref> \n*[[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] condemned the firing, and his political party held a rally in Tirunelveli condemning the shooting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.oneindia.com/news/tamilnadu/seeman-condemns-the-gun-firing-at-thoothukudi-protest/articlecontent-pf308746-320470.html|title=Naam Thamizhar Katchi leader Seeman condemns gun firing at Thoothukudi|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref>\n* [[Kamal Haasan]] was one of the first political leaders to arrive to Tuticorin to see the injured in the hospital, after the shootings.\n* [[Vaiko]] and [[M.K.Stalin]] demanded investigations into the shootings.<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/india/mass-murder-of-innocent-people-dmks-stalin-questions-order-to-fire-at-anti-sterlite-protesters-5187874/</ref>\n* [[National Human Rights Commission of India]] demanded investigation into the killings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/05/indian-police-accused-killing-11-protesters-180523134721427.html |title=Indian police accused of killing at least 11 protesters}}</ref> It asked its Director General (Investigation) to send a team headed by an [[Superintendent of Police|SP]] to visit the spot and conduct an inquiry.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\" />\n* Tamils and [[Tamil diaspora]] across the world including [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Europe]], [[Malaysia]], [[Sri Lanka]] and [[Australia]] held protests against the killing.\n* In support of the protests The UK's Opposition, Labour Party, has called for Vedanta to be delisted from the London Stock Exchange. [[John McDonnell]], the UK's Shadow Chancellor, said removing Vedanta Resources from the London financial markets would prevent reputational damage from the \"rogue\" company which has been operating \"illegal\" mining concerns for years. \"After the firing on the protestors this week, regulators must now take action. Vedanta must be immediately delisted from the London Stock Exchange to remove its cloak of respectability, restore confidence in the governance of the Stock Exchange, and prevent further reputational damage to London's financial markets from this rogue corporation,\" McDonnell said in a statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uk-opposition-wants-vedanta-delisted-from-london-stock-exchange/articleshow/64331300.cms |title=UK Opposition wants Vedanta delisted on London Stock Exchange}}</ref>\n* Actor [[Rajinikanth]] said \"The entire problem started after anti-social elements attacked police and burned down collector's office, as a result, peaceful protestors were killed. If you undertake protest for each and everything, Tamil Nadu will be turned into a cemetery\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44313804|title=Rajinikanth: Anger after actor justifies deadly police firing|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/rajinikanth-blames-anti-social-elements-for-sterlite-protest201805302030500001/ |title=Rajinikanth blames anti-social elements for Sterlite protest}}</ref> His reaction to the firing was criticized on the social media.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-superstar-rajinikanth-apologises-for-losing-cool-at-media-interaction-2621031 |title=Superstar Rajinikanth apologises for losing cool at media interaction |access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-s-speech-earns-him-negative-image-on-social-media-news-tamil-sf5jD6fcigihb.html|title=Rajinikanth's speech earns him negative image on social media?|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> Following his controversial statements regarding the Thoothukudi police firing, the Tamil activist groups in [[Norway]] and [[Switzerland]] banned the release of Rajinikanth's film [[Kaala (2018 film)|''Kaala'']] in Norway and Switzerland by the scheduled world wide release date as of 7 June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tamil.news18.com/news/entertainment/after-norway-kaala-ban-in-swiss-too-24491.html|title=\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u2013 News18 Tamil|website=News18 Tamil|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.samayam.com/tamil-cinema/movie-news/rajinikanth-kaala-movie-banned-in-switzerland-and-norway/articleshow/64428551.cms|title=\u0bb0\u0b9c\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b92\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7, \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8 - Samayam Tamil|date=2018-06-02|work=[[Samayam Tamil]]|access-date=2018-06-03|language=ta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/foreign-nations-ban-rajinis-kaala-tamil-news-214931|title=Foreign nations ban Rajini's 'Kaala'? - Tamil Movie News \u2013 IndiaGlitz.com|work=IndiaGlitz.com|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> The Tamil diaspora groups in Norway and Switzerland announced that they would not release the films of actors in the future who deliberately hurt the feelings and attitudes of Tamil people following the comments from Rajinikanth on Tamils.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tamilnews.com/2018/06/01/switzerland-ban-super-star-movie-following-norway/|title=\u0ba8\u0bcb\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd '\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe' \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8??|last=S|first=Ashwiniya|date=2018-06-01|work=TAMIL NEWS|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the ban was later lifted and the film was released within a week, a day before the scheduled worldwide release in Switzerland and Norway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|title=Wochenprogramm|date=2018-06-11|work=Top Kino|access-date=2018-06-19|language=de-CH|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619085834/http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|title=Kaala (Tamil)|date=2018-06-01|work=Filmweb|access-date=2018-06-19|language=no-NO|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619090401/https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref>The actor was also summoned to appear before the one man commission probing the incident on 25th February. However, the actor cited professional engagements and disturbance caused to the public if a star of his stature arrives at the court to decline appearing before the commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/thoothukudi-sterlite-copper-plant-probe-rajinikanth-gets-exemption-from-appearance-808094.html|title=Thoothukudi Sterlite Copper plant probe: Rajinikanth gets exemption from appearance|date=2020-02-25|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nA video released by the environmental activist S. Mugilan, a few days before he went missing from a train while traveling from Chennai to Madurai, said that the \"shooting was well planned\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/environmental-activist-missing-thoothukudi-massacre-police|title=Activist Goes Missing Hours After Incriminating Top Cops in Thoothukudi Massacre|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=TuNo|title=Arsonists - Sterlite - The Hidden Truth - \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0baf\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd? \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b9f\u0bcd - \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0b89\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0bae\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd|date=2019-02-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SlukGKrzYLc|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn 28 May 2018, the Sterlite factory was sealed after an order given by the Tamil Nadu Environmental pollution and Forests Department.<ref name=\"TH20180528-1\">{{cite news | last = Rohit | first = T. K. | title = Sterlite Copper to be permanently closed, says Tamil Nadu government | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 28 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sterlite-copper-to-be-permanently-closed-says-tamil-nadu-government/article24014605.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> The next day, Tamil Nadu's State Industries Promotion Corporation (SIPCOT) announced that it would take back 342.22 acres of land that it had given for expansion of the facility.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\">{{cite news | title = T.N. to take back land allotted to Sterlite | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai / New Delhi | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tn-to-take-back-land-allotted-to-sterlite/article24029865.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> Many political leaders including [[M.K.Stalin]], [[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] and [[Anbumani Ramadoss]] criticized the sealing order, saying that it would not stand up to legal scrutiny since the government had given no reason for shutting down the factory.<ref name=\"TH20180530-2\">{{cite news | title = G.O. won't stand up to legal scrutiny: Stalin | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-wont-stand-up-to-legal-scrutiny-stalin/article24027956.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TH20180530-3\">{{cite news | title = G.O. to close Sterlite plant inadequate | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-to-close-sterlite-plant-inadequate/article24030059.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn October 28, 2018, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the sulphur-dioxide levels in the air had reduced significantly after the Sterlite plant's closure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/so2-levels-have-reduced-significantly-after-closure-of-sterlite-plant-tnpcb/article25353938.ece|title=SO2 levels have reduced significantly after closure of Sterlite plant: TNPCB|last=Simhan|first=TE Raja|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2019, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the [[Ambient air quality criteria|ambient air quality]] had improved dramatically after the closure of the plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/tuticorin-air-quality-aqi-sterlite-copper-smelting-pollution-sipcot-tnpcb|title=Tuticorin Air Quality Improves Noticeably After Sterlite Closure: TNPCB Data|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Manjolai Labourers massacre]]\n* [[2018 Tamil Nadu protests for Kaveri water sharing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pollution in India]]\n[[Category:Police brutality in India]]\n[[Category:2018 in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 2018 crimes in Asia|Thoothukudi_firing]]\n[[Category:Thoothukudi]]\n[[Category:Protests in India]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Thoothukudi police firing|2=Talk:Thoothukudi massacre#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       =Thoothukudi Massacare\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| map         = {{Location map|Tamil Nadu|lat=8.48|long=78.04|caption=}}\n| map_caption = Location of Thoothukudi in Tamil Nadu\n| location    = [[Thoothukudi]], Tamil Nadu, [[India]]\n| target      = Protestors against [[Sterlite Copper]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|8.784117|78.099142|display=inline,title}}\n| date        = 22 May 2018\n| time        = \n| timezone    = UTC+5:30\n| type        = [[Shooting]]<!-- Don't change without valid reference -->\n| fatalities  = 13<!-- Don't change without valid reference --><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 15 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| injuries    = 102<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 13 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| perps       = [[Tamil Nadu Police]] & Paramilitary forces\n| weapons     = [[L1A1 SLR]] [[battle rifle]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/news/tamilnadu/125778-this-is-the-type-of-rifle-used-in-tuticorin.html |title=\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd 11 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b89\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8 \u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0b87\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0bcd}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/massacre-thoothukudi-intelligence-failure-or-deliberate-assault-81865 |title=The police firing in Thoothukudi: Intelligence failure or deliberate assault?}}</ref>\n| numparts    =\n}}\n\n[[File:Sterlitejpg.jpg|thumb|Protesters in large numbers take out a march against the Sterlite copper plant on May 22, 2018.]]The '''Thoothukudi Massacre''' (also known as the '''Thoothukudi police firing''' or '''Sterlite protest firing''') took place on 22 May 2018 in [[Thoothukudi]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India, when [[Tamil Nadu Police]] officers fired into a protest of 20,000 people, killing 13 protesters and injuring dozens of others.<ref name=\"financialexpress\" /> The protest was against the [[Sterlite Copper]] factory, which was accused of causing environmental pollution.<ref name=\"financialexpress\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/sterlite-protest-in-tuticorin-9-killed-in-tamil-nadu-top-developments-history-reasons-behind-violence/1177652/|title=Reasons behind Killings|last=|first=|date=|work=The Financial Express|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSterlite Copper has been facing resistance from the local fishermen\u2019s groups in the area ever since the plant was given permission to be established by the J Jayalaitha AIADMK in 1993.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sudhakar|first=P.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/for-sterlite-its-crisis-situation-once-again/article4564893.ece|title=For Sterlite, it's crisis situation once again|date=2013-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Sporadic protests have occurred in [[Thoothukudi]] since 1999, directed against the Sterlite Copper smelting works, the factory owned by [[Vedanta Limited]], a subsidiary of [[Vedanta Resources]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/variety/sterlite-protests-sulphur-dioxide-vedanta-tamil-nadu/story/1/23101.html|title=Why hundreds of Tamils won't quit protests against Vedanta's Sterlite|website=www.dailyo.in|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> Protesters opposed the soil, water and air contamination caused by the factory.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/sterlite-s-pollution-problem-113041801267_1.html|title=Sterlite's pollution problem|date=2013-04-18|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Pollution studies ===\nAn epidemiological study carried out by [[Tirunelveli Medical College]] in 2006\u201307 found an increased prevalence of respiratory diseases and ear, nose and throat (ENT) morbidity in the 5-km radius of Sterlite Industries. The study reported the prevalence of respiratory diseases in the area at 13.9% which was far higher than the state average. The prevalence of asthmatic bronchitis is 2.8%, which more than two-times the state average of 1.29%. Myalgia (general body pain) is another extensively reported symptom and women were often found to have menstrual disorders, like [[Menorrhagia|menorrhagiae]] and dysmenorrhagiae in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite - here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|last=Jayaraman|first=Nityanand|date=April 1, 2018|website=thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Their report blamed it on the air pollution caused by the industry's thermal power plants and automobiles in the area.<ref>{{cite book | last = Elango  | first = S. | title = Health status and Epidemiological study around 5&nbsp;km radius of Sterlite Industries (India) Limited, Thoothukudi | publisher = Tirunelveli Medical College | date = Oct 2008 | location = Tirunelveli | pages = 106 | language = English | url = https://poromboke.files.wordpress.com/2018/03/health-report-sterlite_edited.pdf}}</ref> The [[groundwater]] iron content in the area of the plant has been found to be 17\u201320 times the allowable limit, causing additional health problems for the population already experiencing higher than average incidence of respiratory diseases. During the time of this Study at 2007, Sterlite was operating about about 18 to 42 percentage, compared to its 4 Lakh Tonnes per Annum in the year 2017-2018.<ref name=\"newsminute\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|date=2018-04-01|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/jul/29/sterlite-keen-to-expand-operation-in-thoothukudi-1850064.html|title=Sterlite keen to expand operation in Thoothukudi|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\nThe 1998 report by [[National Environmental Engineering Research Institute]] (NEERI), the levels of selenium, arsenic and lead in treated effluent were higher than specified standards. The team also found dead birds after they consumed the water mixed with the effluent and also reported that the industry's process of cooling the effluents can cause health hazards to the staff and residents in the local region. In another instance, the NEERI reported water samples from dugwells and borewells around the spot were found to be non-[[Drinking water|drinkable]] due to its high chemical content. During 1998, the industry was operating at 10% capacity, compared to that of 2018.  <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-data-how-smelter-likely-cause-water-pollution-79055|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's proof: The data on how the smelter is likely cause for water pollution|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/environment/neeri-made-way-for-sterlite-to-pollute-tuticorin-60647|title=NEERI made way for Sterlite to pollute Tuticorin|last=|first=|date=|website=downtoearth.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2005 environmental audit by NEERI, the samples from a village 2-km northwest of the factory had levels of cadmium, copper, lead, chromium, and arsenic 2 to 9 times higher than allowed levels. Soil Samples were also analyzed in areas surrounding the plant during the study and [[Arsenic poisoning|arsenic]] levels ranged from 133 mg/kg to 287 mg/kg, where soils containing more than 50 mg/kg of arsenic are supposed to treated as a 'hazardous wastes' under the Indian Law.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn October 2010, Sampling tests by an NGO, Community Environmental Monitoring, found salinity level in an open well to be of 7854 mg/litre while levels exceeding 2000 mg/litre can badly damage the crops. Another water sample from a bore-well had [[sulfate]] levels 10 times higher than the average. A soil sample from the same spot contained 335 g/kg of iron and a ingestion of just 3.5 grams by a child can be a serious case of [[Iron poisoning|Iron Poisoning]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA Scientific study in 2017, found most of the ground water samples in the area are highly contaminated with heavy metals like arsenic, lead, boron etc. which were higher than the [[World Health Organization]]'s prescribed limit.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Selvam|first=S.|last2=Antony Ravindran|first2=A.|last3=Venkatramanan|first3=S.|last4=Singaraja|first4=C.|date=2017-05-01|title=Assessment of heavy metal and bacterial pollution in coastal aquifers from SIPCOT industrial zones, Gulf of Mannar, South Coast of Tamil Nadu, India|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|journal=Applied Water Science|language=en|volume=7|issue=2|pages=897\u2013913|doi=10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|issn=2190-5495}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board (TNPCB) observed that the unit has been releasing poisonous gas in the air. TNPCB identified that the sulphur dioxide levels went off the scale on the night of March 23, 2013. It showed a reading of 2939.55-mg/cubic meter against the decreed limit of 1250 mg/cubic meter.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2018/columnists/sterlite-protests-reach-a-climax.html|title=Sterlite protests reach a climax|last=Pioneer|first=The|website=The Pioneer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2018, the TNPCB accused the Sterlite Copper of causing groundwater pollution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/governance/sterlite-typifies-all-that-s-wrong-with-environmental-governance-in-india-60877|title=Sterlite typifies all that's wrong with environmental governance in India|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Gas leaks ===\nOn July 7th 1997, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board told the company to shut down after a sulphur dioxide gas leak which hospitalized more than 90 people.<ref>{{Cite news|last=BSCAL|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/sterlite-told-to-shut-plant-following-gas-leak-197070701041_1.html|title=Sterlite Told To Shut Plant Following Gas Leak|date=1997-07-07|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Sterlite Copper factory also made headlines in 2013 after a suspected sulphur dioxide gas leak from one of its smelter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sterlite-plant-idINDEE93005C20130401|title=Sterlite ordered to shut large copper smelter over 'gas leak'|date=2013-04-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref> The plant was blamed for health issues observed in the area related to gas leakage and residents near-by complained of coughing, [[wheezing]], eye iritation, and [[Miscarriage|miscarriages]] following the leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1287476/sterlite-coppers-20-years-in-thoothukudi-have-been-marked-by-deaths-miscarriages-and-endless-protests/|title=Protests, miscarriages, deaths: Sterlite Copper's 20 years in Thoothukudi|last=Thomas|first=Sushma U. N, Maria|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Following the alleged gas leak in March 2013, the then chief minister, the late [[J. Jayalalithaa]], ordered its closure. The company appealed to the [[National Green Tribunal Act|National Green Tribunal]], which overturned the government order. The state moved the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] against it, where the petition was still pending. The plant closed on March 27 of 2018, with the company citing a 15-day maintenance process.<ref name=\"financialexpress\" /> The Supreme Court ordered the company to pay a 100-crore fine for polluting the water, air and soil around the plant and the factory was temporarily shutdown by the pollution regulator.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sc-slaps-rs-100-cr-penalty-on-sterlite-for-pollution/article4572805.ece|title=SC slaps Rs. 100 cr. penalty on Sterlite for pollution|last=Venkatesan|first=J.|date=2013-04-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> About 150 people were arrested in protests against the plant.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn June 2019, the Tamil Nadu government reported that there were 84 incidents of gas leaks at Sterlite Copper in the year 2013 alone, to the [[Madras High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/84-gas-leaks-at-sterlite-in-2013-alone-tn-tells-madras-hc/articleshow/69881981.cms|title=84 gas leaks at Sterlite in 2013 alone, Tamil Nadu tells Madras HC {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Jun 21|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=11:52}}</ref>\n\n== Protests ==\nA wave of protests began on March 24, 2018 after the Sterlite Copper announced its plans to expand the plant, people around Kumarettiyapuram village protested for more than 100 days. Later the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board rejected the application by the company for clearance. The protesters claimed that the company went on to expand despite the rejection by the government.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Radhakrishnan|first=Sruthi|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/the-hindu-explains-sterlite-protests/article23969542.ece|title=The Hindu explains: Sterlite protests|date=2018-05-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vikatan.com/social-affairs/environment/120896-after-kumarettiyapuram-pandarampatti-village-people-joins-sterlite-protest-in-thoothukudi|title=\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b9f\u0bcd \u0b86\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b8e\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bae\u0bcd!|last=|first=|date=|website=vikatan.com|language=ta|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/27/anti-sterlite-in-thoothukudi-heart-of-darkness-1819970.html|title=Anti-Sterlite in Thoothukudi: Heart of darkness|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The protests were joined by traders of Thoothukudi city central trade association on the same day following calls for a [[bandh]] by environmental activist M Krishnamoorthi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/200318/thoothukudi-foreign-hand-behind-anti-sterlite-stir.html|title=Thoothukudi: 'Foreign hand' behind anti-Sterlite stir|date=2018-03-20|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThe protesters wanted the company's smelting unit in Thoothukudi shut down as it was causing environmental damage to the area. The company has been accused of being negligent regarding environmental management, causing harm to the health of the locals in and around Thoothukudi.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe District Administration called up 23 people belonging to the trader associations and anti-sterlite activists from the protesters including the environmental activist Fatima Babu on 20th May for a peace meeting. The members agreed to shift the venue after pressure from the government, from the Collector's Office to another place and to change the course of the protest to only get validation. Fatima was soon expelled by the protesting group after she agreed with the government's conditions.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/tuticorin-protests-sterlite-industries-illegally-obtained-environmental-clearance-activist-fatima-babu-tells-madras-high-court-4480681.html|title=Tuticorin protests: Sterlite Industries 'illegally obtained' environmental clearance, activist Fatima Babu tells Madras High Court|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nTwo groups of people protested separately on 22nd May. One of the was protesting a attention-seeking protest at SAV ground  and the other was marching towards the Collector's office. Soon both the groups joined together and marched toward the Collector's office. Police resorted to [[lathi charge]] and fired tear gas shells at the crowd after disagreeing with the protesters who wanted to stage a sit-in. There were about 2000 police personnel and a crowd of over 20,000 protesters. The district administration neglected intelligence reports of mass mobilization of over 18,000 people in the district.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAn employee of the the Sterlite Copper claimed the involvement of groups like Makkal Athikaram and Foil Vedanta in the protests.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/880329/view-from-the-other-side-sterlite-workers-attacked-by-thoothukudi-protestors-recall-the-terror|title=View from the other side: Sterlite workers attacked by Thoothukudi protestors recall the terror|last=Govindarajan|first=Vinita|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Firing==\n\nOn May 22, 2018, thousands of people began to march to the district collector's office to submit a petition when the \"[[section 144]]\" was imposed. Section 144 makes a gathering of more than four people unlawful but an unofficial release said 20,000 people took out a procession towards the district-collector's office and the copper plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/05/27/sterlite-protest-section-144-lifted-in-thoothukudi.html|title=Sterlite protest: Section 144 lifted in Thoothukudi|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Protestors were successful in entering the premises of the collectorate. The police started shooting against the protesters, \"without any formal warning\" after tear gas and lathi charge proved ineffective.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/anti-sterlite-protests-tuticorin-villagers-accuse-left-outfit-of-inciting-violence-5247129/|title=Anti-Sterlite protests: Tuticorin villagers accuse Left outfit of inciting violence|date=2018-07-06|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nThe police started shooting at the protesters and were also accused of shooting without any formal warning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Police were also reported of intentionally shooting at the heads of the protesters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/police-targeted-protesters-shot-head-victims-families-671547.html|title=Police targeted the protesters; shot at head|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> 13 protesters were killed including a 17-year old school student, and dozens were injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/she-wanted-be-lawyer-her-dreams-lie-box-thoothukudi-teen-victim-s-kin-81854|title=She wanted to be a lawyer, her dreams lie in a box|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"fivedays\" /><ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/as-tuticorin-weeps-for-13-felled-in-police-firing-a-quite-rage-persists/articleshow/64334132.cms</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-police-fired-from-assault-rifles-on-anti-sterlite-protesters-heard-saying-at-least-one-should-die-2110643.html|title=Tamil Nadu Police fired from assault rifles on anti-Sterlite protesters, heard saying at least one should die{{!}} Zee News India|website=zeenews.india.com|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>\n\n[[First information report|FIR]]<nowiki/>s filed in local police stations, claimed that the order to shoot was issued by officers in the rank of deputy Tehsildars and people pointed out that only Collectors have the authority to issue shooting orders.<ref name=\"TH20180529-1\">{{cite news | last = Pon Vasanth | first = B. A | title = Three officers in the rank of deputy tahsildar issued firing orders in Thoothukudi, say FIRs | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Madurai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 29 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/3-deputy-tahsildars-issued-firing-orders-say-firs/article24017934.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu government ordered a shutdown of Internet in the entire districts of Tuticorin, Tirunelveli and Kanyakumari for five days after the firing.<ref name=\"fivedays\">{{cite web |title=Sterlite protest: Tamil Nadu orders internet suspension for five days in three southern districts |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/23/sterlite-protest-tamil-nadu-orders-internet-suspension-for-five-days-in-three-southern-districts-1818574.html |website=New Indian Express |accessdate=9 July 2018 |date=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n==Reactions==\n\n* [[Thirumurugan Gandhi]], the coordinator of [[May 17 Movement]], took the issue to the 38th session of the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]], Geneva in July 2018. On 9 August 2018, Thirumurugan Gandhi was detained by immigration authorities at Bangalore Airport on his return to India and charged under Section 124 A (sedition), 153 A (1) and 153 (b) of IPC for speaking about the Thoothukudi firings at the UNHRC. Court, later, refused to remand him under judicial custody as it found the charges are baseless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/court-refuses-detain-activist-thirumurugan-gandhi-86351|title=Court refuses to detain activist Thirumurugan Gandhi|date=2018-08-10|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/aug/10/thirumurugan-gandhi-held-in-bengaluru-for-un-speech-on-police-firing-in-thoothukudi-1855732.html|title=Thirumurugan Gandhi held in Bengaluru for UN speech on police firing in Thoothukudi|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n* [[Indian National Congress]] party president [[Rahul Gandhi]] described it as \"[[state-sponsored terrorism]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/india/anti-sterlite-protest-gunning-down-9-people-by-police-in-tamil-nadu-is-state-sponsored-terrorism-says-rahul-gandhi-2110523.html?src=fb|title=Anti-Sterlite protest: Gunning down 9 people by police in Tamil Nadu is state-sponsored terrorism, says Rahul Gandhi|date=2018-05-22|work=Zee News|access-date=2018-05-22|language=en}}</ref> \n*[[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] condemned the firing, and his political party held a rally in Tirunelveli condemning the shooting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.oneindia.com/news/tamilnadu/seeman-condemns-the-gun-firing-at-thoothukudi-protest/articlecontent-pf308746-320470.html|title=Naam Thamizhar Katchi leader Seeman condemns gun firing at Thoothukudi|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref>\n* [[Kamal Haasan]] was one of the first political leaders to arrive to Tuticorin to see the injured in the hospital, after the shootings.\n* [[Vaiko]] and [[M.K.Stalin]] demanded investigations into the shootings.<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/india/mass-murder-of-innocent-people-dmks-stalin-questions-order-to-fire-at-anti-sterlite-protesters-5187874/</ref>\n* [[National Human Rights Commission of India]] demanded investigation into the killings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/05/indian-police-accused-killing-11-protesters-180523134721427.html |title=Indian police accused of killing at least 11 protesters}}</ref> It asked its Director General (Investigation) to send a team headed by an [[Superintendent of Police|SP]] to visit the spot and conduct an inquiry.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\" />\n* Tamils and [[Tamil diaspora]] across the world including [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Europe]], [[Malaysia]], [[Sri Lanka]] and [[Australia]] held protests against the killing.\n* In support of the protests The UK's Opposition, Labour Party, has called for Vedanta to be delisted from the London Stock Exchange. [[John McDonnell]], the UK's Shadow Chancellor, said removing Vedanta Resources from the London financial markets would prevent reputational damage from the \"rogue\" company which has been operating \"illegal\" mining concerns for years. \"After the firing on the protestors this week, regulators must now take action. Vedanta must be immediately delisted from the London Stock Exchange to remove its cloak of respectability, restore confidence in the governance of the Stock Exchange, and prevent further reputational damage to London's financial markets from this rogue corporation,\" McDonnell said in a statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uk-opposition-wants-vedanta-delisted-from-london-stock-exchange/articleshow/64331300.cms |title=UK Opposition wants Vedanta delisted on London Stock Exchange}}</ref>\n* Actor [[Rajinikanth]] said \"The entire problem started after anti-social elements attacked police and burned down collector's office, as a result, peaceful protestors were killed. If you undertake protest for each and everything, Tamil Nadu will be turned into a cemetery\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44313804|title=Rajinikanth: Anger after actor justifies deadly police firing|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/rajinikanth-blames-anti-social-elements-for-sterlite-protest201805302030500001/ |title=Rajinikanth blames anti-social elements for Sterlite protest}}</ref> His reaction to the firing was criticized on the social media.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-superstar-rajinikanth-apologises-for-losing-cool-at-media-interaction-2621031 |title=Superstar Rajinikanth apologises for losing cool at media interaction |access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-s-speech-earns-him-negative-image-on-social-media-news-tamil-sf5jD6fcigihb.html|title=Rajinikanth's speech earns him negative image on social media?|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> Following his controversial statements regarding the Thoothukudi police firing, the Tamil activist groups in [[Norway]] and [[Switzerland]] banned the release of Rajinikanth's film [[Kaala (2018 film)|''Kaala'']] in Norway and Switzerland by the scheduled world wide release date as of 7 June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tamil.news18.com/news/entertainment/after-norway-kaala-ban-in-swiss-too-24491.html|title=\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u2013 News18 Tamil|website=News18 Tamil|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.samayam.com/tamil-cinema/movie-news/rajinikanth-kaala-movie-banned-in-switzerland-and-norway/articleshow/64428551.cms|title=\u0bb0\u0b9c\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b92\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7, \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8 - Samayam Tamil|date=2018-06-02|work=[[Samayam Tamil]]|access-date=2018-06-03|language=ta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/foreign-nations-ban-rajinis-kaala-tamil-news-214931|title=Foreign nations ban Rajini's 'Kaala'? - Tamil Movie News \u2013 IndiaGlitz.com|work=IndiaGlitz.com|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> The Tamil diaspora groups in Norway and Switzerland announced that they would not release the films of actors in the future who deliberately hurt the feelings and attitudes of Tamil people following the comments from Rajinikanth on Tamils.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tamilnews.com/2018/06/01/switzerland-ban-super-star-movie-following-norway/|title=\u0ba8\u0bcb\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd '\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe' \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8??|last=S|first=Ashwiniya|date=2018-06-01|work=TAMIL NEWS|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the ban was later lifted and the film was released within a week, a day before the scheduled worldwide release in Switzerland and Norway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|title=Wochenprogramm|date=2018-06-11|work=Top Kino|access-date=2018-06-19|language=de-CH|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619085834/http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|title=Kaala (Tamil)|date=2018-06-01|work=Filmweb|access-date=2018-06-19|language=no-NO|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619090401/https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref>The actor was also summoned to appear before the one man commission probing the incident on 25th February. However, the actor cited professional engagements and disturbance caused to the public if a star of his stature arrives at the court to decline appearing before the commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/thoothukudi-sterlite-copper-plant-probe-rajinikanth-gets-exemption-from-appearance-808094.html|title=Thoothukudi Sterlite Copper plant probe: Rajinikanth gets exemption from appearance|date=2020-02-25|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nA video released by the environmental activist S. Mugilan, a few days before he went missing from a train while traveling from Chennai to Madurai, said that the \"shooting was well planned\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/environmental-activist-missing-thoothukudi-massacre-police|title=Activist Goes Missing Hours After Incriminating Top Cops in Thoothukudi Massacre|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=TuNo|title=Arsonists - Sterlite - The Hidden Truth - \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0baf\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd? \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b9f\u0bcd - \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0b89\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0bae\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd|date=2019-02-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SlukGKrzYLc|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn 28 May 2018, the Sterlite factory was sealed after an order given by the Tamil Nadu Environmental pollution and Forests Department.<ref name=\"TH20180528-1\">{{cite news | last = Rohit | first = T. K. | title = Sterlite Copper to be permanently closed, says Tamil Nadu government | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 28 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sterlite-copper-to-be-permanently-closed-says-tamil-nadu-government/article24014605.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> The next day, Tamil Nadu's State Industries Promotion Corporation (SIPCOT) announced that it would take back 342.22 acres of land that it had given for expansion of the facility.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\">{{cite news | title = T.N. to take back land allotted to Sterlite | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai / New Delhi | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tn-to-take-back-land-allotted-to-sterlite/article24029865.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> Many political leaders including [[M.K.Stalin]], [[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] and [[Anbumani Ramadoss]] criticized the sealing order, saying that it would not stand up to legal scrutiny since the government had given no reason for shutting down the factory.<ref name=\"TH20180530-2\">{{cite news | title = G.O. won't stand up to legal scrutiny: Stalin | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-wont-stand-up-to-legal-scrutiny-stalin/article24027956.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TH20180530-3\">{{cite news | title = G.O. to close Sterlite plant inadequate | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-to-close-sterlite-plant-inadequate/article24030059.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn October 28, 2018, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the sulphur-dioxide levels in the air had reduced significantly after the Sterlite plant's closure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/so2-levels-have-reduced-significantly-after-closure-of-sterlite-plant-tnpcb/article25353938.ece|title=SO2 levels have reduced significantly after closure of Sterlite plant: TNPCB|last=Simhan|first=TE Raja|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2019, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the [[Ambient air quality criteria|ambient air quality]] had improved dramatically after the closure of the plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/tuticorin-air-quality-aqi-sterlite-copper-smelting-pollution-sipcot-tnpcb|title=Tuticorin Air Quality Improves Noticeably After Sterlite Closure: TNPCB Data|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Manjolai Labourers massacre]]\n* [[2018 Tamil Nadu protests for Kaveri water sharing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pollution in India]]\n[[Category:Police brutality in India]]\n[[Category:2018 in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 2018 crimes in Asia|Thoothukudi_firing]]\n[[Category:Thoothukudi]]\n[[Category:Protests in India]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thoothukudi_massacre"}
{"title_page": "Helsinki bid for the 2006 Winter Olympics", "text_new": "{{Olympic bid|2006|Winter|\n| logo         = Helsinki2006bid.png\n| logo-size    = 200px\n|  winner = Turin\n|  runner-up = Sion\n|  shortlisted1 = Helsinki\n|  shortlisted2 = Klagenfurt\n|  shortlisted3 = Poprad-Tatry\n|  shortlisted4 = Zakopane\n| Paralympics  = yes\n| fullname     = [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| chair        = \n| committee    = [[Finnish Olympic Committee]] (FIN)\n| history      = [[1952 Summer Olympics]]\n| result       = Not shortlisted\n}}\n{{2006 Winter Olympics}}\n\n'''Helsinki 2006''' was a joint bid for the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] presented by the city of Helsinki and [[Finnish Olympic Committee]]. Some of the proposed venues were located in [[Lillehammer]], [[Norway]].\n\nFinland does not possess sufficiently high mountains in its territory to host the alpine skiing competitions and thus proposed some events pursuant to Rule 38.2 of the [[Olympic Charter]]. Whilst the individual venues were considered to be excellent, the 1000-km distance between Helsinki and Lillehammer, and the fact that a large portion of the Games will be held in Norway, may have led to organisational and operational burdens.<ref>http://library.la84.org/OlympicInformationCenter/OlympicReview/1999/OREXXVI27/OREXXVI27u.pdf</ref>\n\n==Venues==\nThe proposed venues were spread between two countries:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/209611/files/2006_OG_-_Report_of_the_Evaluation_Commission.pdf |title=Report of the IOC Evaluation Commission for the XX Olympic Winter Games in 2006 |publisher=International Olympic Committee |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}, p.18</ref>\n\n===[[Finland]]===\n* [[Helsinki]] - ceremonies, main olympic village, ice hockey (two venues: [[Hartwall Arena]] and [[Barona Areena]]), speed skating ([[Myllypuro]]), figure skating and short track ([[Helsinki Ice Hall]]), curling ([[Pirkkola]] Arena)\n* [[Lahti]] - biathlon, ski-jumping, Nordic combined, cross-country skiing, freestyle skiing (Messil\u00e4)\n\n===[[Norway]]===\n* [[Lillehammer]] - [[Lillehammer Olympic Bobsleigh and Luge Track]] for bobsleigh, luge and skeleton\n* [[Hafjell]] - alpine skiing (men's and women's slalom, giant slalom and combined slalom), snowboard\n* [[Kvitfjell]] - alpine skiing (men's and women's downhill, combined downhill and super-G)\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n===Helsinki 2006 Candidature Files===\n* [http://issuu.com/thatsnotmypuppy/docs/helsinki2006volume1/0 Volume 1]\n* [http://issuu.com/thatsnotmypuppy/docs/helsinki2006volume2/0 Volume 2]\n* [http://issuu.com/thatsnotmypuppy/docs/helsinki2006volume3/0 Volume 3]\n\n[[Category:2006 Winter Olympics bids]]\n[[Category:Sport in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Finland at the Olympics|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Olympic bid|2006|Winter|\n| logo         = Helsinki2006bid.png\n| logo-size    = 200px\n|  winner = Turin\n|  runner-up = Sion\n|  shortlisted1 = Helsinki\n|  shortlisted2 = Klagenfurt\n|  shortlisted3 = Poprad-Tatry\n|  shortlisted4 = Zakopane\n| Paralympics  = yes\n| fullname     = [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| chair        = \n| committee    = [[Finnish Olympic Committee]] (FIN)\n| history      = [[1952 Summer Olympics]]\n| result       = Not shortlisted\n}}\n{{2006 Winter Olympics}}\n\n'''Helsinki 2006''' was a joint bid for the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] presented by the city of Helsinki and [[Finnish Olympic Committee]]. Some of the proposed venues were located in [[Lillehammer]], [[Norway]].\n\nFinland does not possess sufficiently high mountains in its territory to host the alpine skiing competitions and thus proposed some events pursuant to Rule 38.2 of the [[Olympic Charter]]. Whilst the individual venues were considered to be excellent, the 1000-km distance between Helsinki and Lillehammer, and the fact that a large portion of the Games will be held in Norway, may have led to organisational and operational burdens.<ref>http://library.la84.org/OlympicInformationCenter/OlympicReview/1999/OREXXVI27/OREXXVI27u.pdf</ref>\n\n==Venues==\nThe proposed venues were spread between two countries:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/209611/files/2006_OG_-_Report_of_the_Evaluation_Commission.pdf |title=Report of the IOC Evaluation Commission for the XX Olympic Winter Games in 2006 |publisher=International Olympic Committee |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}, p.18</ref>\n\n===[[Finland]]===\n* [[Helsinki]] - ceremonies, main olympic village, ice hockey (two venues: [[Hartwall Arena]] and [[Barona Areena]]), speed skating ([[Myllypuro]]), figure skating and short track ([[Helsinki Ice Hall]]), curling ([[Pirkkola]] Arena)\n* [[Lahti]] - biathlon, ski-jumping, Nordic combined, cross-country skiing, freestyle skiing (Messil\u00e4)\n\n===[[Norway]]===\n* [[Lillehammer]] - [[Lillehammer Olympic Bobsleigh and Luge Track]] for bobsleigh, luge and skeleton\n* [[Hafjell]] - alpine skiing (men\u2019s and women\u2019s slalom, giant slalom and combined slalom), snowboard\n* [[Kvitfjell]] - alpine skiing (men\u2019s and women\u2019s downhill, combined downhill and super-G)\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n\n===Helsinki 2006 Candidature Files===\n* [http://issuu.com/thatsnotmypuppy/docs/helsinki2006volume1/0 Volume 1]\n* [http://issuu.com/thatsnotmypuppy/docs/helsinki2006volume2/0 Volume 2]\n* [http://issuu.com/thatsnotmypuppy/docs/helsinki2006volume3/0 Volume 3]\n\n[[Category:2006 Winter Olympics bids]]\n[[Category:Sport in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Finland at the Olympics|*]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helsinki_bid_for_the_2006_Winter_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "National Assembly (South Korea)", "text_new": "{{short description|Legislature of South Korea}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox legislature\n| name               = National Assembly of the<br />Republic of Korea\n| native_name        = {{noitalic|{{nobold|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \uad6d\ud68c<br />\u5927\u97d3\u6c11\u570b\u570b\u6703}}}}\n| transcription_name = ''Daehanminguk Gukhoe''\n| legislature        = [[List of members of the National Assembly (South Korea), 2016\u20132020|20th National Assembly]]\n| coa_pic            = Emblem of the National Assembly of Korea.svg\n| coa_res            =\n| logo_pic           = Communication logo of the National Assembly of Korea.svg\n| house_type         = [[Unicameral]]\n| leader1_type       = [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Korea|Speaker]]\n| leader1            = {{Color box|{{Independent politician/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Moon Hee-sang]]\n| party1             = [[Independent politician|Independent]]<ref>The Speaker is required to not have membership of any political party during his or her tenure as Speaker, by law. Formerly a member of the [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]].</ref>\n| election1          = 13 July 2018\n| leader2_type       = Deputy Speaker\n| leader2            = {{Color box|{{United Future Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Lee Ju-young\n| party2 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 = [[United Future Party|United Future]]\n| election2          = 13 July 2018\n| leader3_type       = Deputy Speaker \n| leader3            = {{Color box|{{Party for People's Livelihoods/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Joo Seung-yong\n| party3             = [[Party for People's Livelihoods|PPL]]\n| election3          = 13 July 2018\n| members            = 300\n| structure1         = South Korea_National Assembly_2020.svg\n| structure1_res     = 270px\n| political_groups1  = \n''' Government '''\n:{{Color box|{{Democratic Party of Korea/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]] (180){{efn|The Democratic Party of Korea contests only constituencies, while the Together Citizen's Party contests only lists. They are essentially the same party, but they split to bypass the proportional compensation seats.}}\n::{{Color box|{{Democratic Party of Korea/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]] (163)\n::{{Color box|{{Democratic Party of Korea/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Together Citizens' Party|Together Citizens']] (17)\n\n''' Opposition '''\n:{{Color box|{{United Future Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[United Future Party|United Future]] (103){{efn|The United Future party contests only constituencies, while the Future Korea party contests only lists. They are essentially the same party, but they split to bypass the proportional compensation seats.}}\n::{{Color box|{{United Future Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[United Future Party|United Future]] (84)\n::{{Color box|{{United Future Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Future Korea Party|Future Korea]] (19)\n:{{Color box|{{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice]] (6)\n:{{Color box|{{People Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[People Party (South Korea)|People]] (3)\n:{{Color box|{{Open Democrats/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Open Democratic Party]] (3)\n:{{Color box|#CCCCCC|border=darkgray}} [[Independent politician|Independents]] (5)\n\n\n| committees1        =\n| voting_system1     = [[Parallel voting]] and [[Mixed-member proportional representation|Mixed Member Proportional]]<br />\n* [[First-past-the-post voting|First-past-the-post]] (253 seats)\n* [[Party-list proportional representation]] (17 seats)\n* [[Mixed-member proportional representation|Proportional compensation]] (30 seats) \n| last_election1     = [[2020 South Korean legislative election|15 April 2020]]\n| next_election1     = [[2024 South Korean legislative election|17 April 2024]]\n| session_room       = National_Assembly_Building_of_the_Republic_of_Korea.png{{!}}border\n| session_res        = 270px\n| term_length        = 4 years\n| meeting_place      = [[Korea National Assembly Building|National Assembly Building]]<br />[[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]<br /><small>{{coord|37|31|55.21|N|126|54|50.66|E|source:kowiki_region:KR|display=inline}}</small>\n| website            = [http://korea.assembly.go.kr/ korea.assembly.go.kr]\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul = {{linktext|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d|\uad6d\ud68c}}\n| hanja  = {{linktext|\u5927\u97d3\u6c11\u570b|\u570b\u6703}}\n| rr = Daehanminguk gukhoe\n| mr = Taehanmin'guk kukhoe\n}}\n[[File:Main conference room of South korean national assembly building.JPG|280px|thumb|right|Main conference room of South Korean national assembly building.]]\n[[File:20140808\ub2e4\ubb38\ud654\uac00\uc871\uacfc \ud568\uaed8119\uc11c\uc6b8\ud22c\uc5b498.jpg|thumb|280px|right|South Korean national assembly Main conference room, 2014]]\nThe '''National Assembly of the Republic of Korea''', often shortened to the '''National Assembly''' in domestic English-language media, is the 300-member<ref>Article 21, Clause 1 of the Election Law</ref> [[unicameral]] national [[legislature]] of [[South Korea]]. [[Legislative elections in South Korea|Elections to the National Assembly]] are held every four years. The latest [[2020 South Korean legislative election|legislative elections]] were held on 15 April 2020. Single-member constituencies comprise 253 of the assembly's seats, while the remaining 47 are allocated by [[proportional representation]], 30 of which are used to compensate for the Single-member constituencies. Members serve four-year terms.\n\nThe unicameral assembly consists of at least 200 members according to the [[Constitution of South Korea|South Korean constitution]]. In 1990 the assembly had 299 seats, 224 of which were directly elected from single-member districts in the [[1988 South Korean legislative election|general elections of April 1988]]. Under applicable laws, the remaining seventy-five representatives were elected from party lists. By law, candidates for election to the assembly must be at least thirty years of age. As part of a political compromise in 1987, an earlier requirement that candidates have at least five years' continuous residency in the country was dropped to allow [[Kim Dae-Jung]], who had spent several years in exile in [[Japan]] and the [[United States]] during the 1980s, to return to political life. The National Assembly's term is four years. In a change from the more authoritarian [[Fourth Republic of South Korea|Fourth Republic]] and [[Fifth Republic of South Korea|Fifth Republic]] (1972\u201380 and 1980\u201387, respectively), under the [[History of South Korea#Sixth Republic 1987\u2013present|Sixth Republic]], the assembly cannot be dissolved by the president.\n\n==Current composition==\n[[File:Graph of South Korean Political Parties (2005-2018).png|thumb|right|This graph traces the recent origins of all six main political parties currently in the Republic of Korea. All of which have either split from or merged with other parties in the last four years. They have emerged from four main ideological camps, from Left to Right: Progressive (socialist), liberal, centrist, and conservative.]]\n\n{{See also|2016 South Korean legislative election|List of members of the National Assembly (South Korea), 2016\u20132020}}\n{{Parties in the South Korean Assembly}}\n\n==Structure and appointment==\n\n===Speaker===\nThe constitution stipulates that the assembly is presided over by a [[List of Speakers of the National Assembly of South Korea|Speaker]] and two Deputy Speakers,<ref>Article 48 of the Constitution of the Republic of Korea.</ref> who are responsible for expediting the legislative process. The Speaker and Deputy Speakers are elected in a secret ballot by the members of the Assembly, and their term in office is restricted to two years.<ref name=\"Park Recht\">{{cite book |last=Park |first=Young-Do |title=Einf\u00fchrung in das koreanische Recht |language=German |trans-title=Introduction to Korean Law |publisher=Springer |year=2010 |page=25 |chapter=Kapitel 2: Verfassungsrecht |isbn=9783642116032}}</ref> The Speaker is independent of party affiliation, and the Speaker and Deputy Speakers may not simultaneously be government ministers.<ref name=\"Park Recht\" />\n\n===Negotiation groups===\nParties that hold at least 20 seats in the assembly form floor negotiation groups ({{lang-ko|\uad50\uc12d\ub2e8\uccb4}}, [[Hanja]]: \u4ea4\u6d89\u5718\u9ad4, [[Revised Romanization|RR]]: {{transl|kor|gyoseop danche}}), which are entitled to a variety of rights that are denied to smaller parties. These include a greater amount of state funding and participation in the leaders' summits that determine the assembly's legislative agenda.<ref>Youngmi Kim (2011). ''The Politics of Coalition in South Korea''. Taylor & Francis, p. 65.</ref>\n\n===Legislative process===\nTo introduce a bill, a legislator must present the initiative to the Speaker with the signatures of at least ten other members of the assembly. The bill must then be edited by a committee to ensure that the bill contains correct and systematic language. It can then be approved or rejected by the Assembly.<ref>Park 2010, p. 27.</ref>\n\n=== Committees===\nThere are 17 standing committees which examine bills and petitions falling under their respective jurisdictions, and perform other duties as prescribed by relevant laws.\n\n* House Steering Committee\n* Legislation and Judiciary Committee\n* National Policy Committee\n* Strategy and Finance Committee\n* Science, ICT, Future Planning, Broadcasting and Communications Committee\n* Education Committee\n* Culture, Sports and Tourism Committee\n* Foreign Affairs and Unification Committee\n* National Defense Committee\n* Security and Public Administration Committee\n* Agriculture, Food, Rural Affairs, Oceans and Fisheries Committee\n* Trade, Industry and Energy Committee\n* Health and Welfare Committee\n* Environment and Labor Committee\n* Land, Infrastructure and Transport Committee\n* Intelligence Committee\n* Gender Equality and Family Committee\n\n===Election===\n{{see also|Legislative elections in South Korea}}\nSince the promulgation of the March 1988 electoral law, the assembly has been elected every four years through a [[parallel voting|Supplementary Member]] system, meaning that some of the members are elected from constituencies according to the system of [[first past the post]], while others are elected at a national level through [[proportional representation]].<ref>[[Aurel S. Croissant]], \"Electoral Politics of South Korea\", in Croissant ''et al.'' (2002) ''Electoral Politics in Southeast and East Asia.'' Friedrich Ebert Foundation, p. 257.</ref> As of 2016, 253 members represent constituencies, while 47 were elected from PR lists. In contrast to elections to the Assembly, presidential elections occur once every five years, and this has led to frequent situations of [[minority government]] and legislative deadlock.<ref>Croissant, p. 257.</ref>\n\n==Reform proposals==\nA proposal to lower the number of seats required to form a negotiation group to 15 was passed on 24 July 2000, but was overturned by the [[Constitutional Court of Korea|Constitutional Court]] later that month.<ref>Y. Kim, p. 68.</ref> In order to meet the quorum, the [[United Liberal Democrats]], who then held 17 seats, arranged to \"rent\" three legislators from the [[Millennium Democratic Party]]. The legislators returned to the MDP after the collapse of the ULD&ndash;MDP coalition in September 2001.<ref>Y. Kim, pp. 68&ndash;9.</ref>\n\n==Legislative violence==\nFrom 2004 to 2009, the assembly gained notoriety as a frequent site for [[legislative violence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2009/09/16/the-worlds-most-unruly-parliaments/|title=The World's Most Unruly Parliaments|publisher=}}</ref> The Assembly first came to the world's attention during a violent dispute on impeachment proceedings for then President [[Roh Moo-hyun]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3504026.stm|title=South Korean president impeached|date=12 March 2004|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_pictures/3504136.stm|title=In pictures: Impeachment battle|date=12 March 2004|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> when open physical combat took place in the assembly. Since then, it has been interrupted by periodic conflagrations, piquing the world's curiosity once again in 2009 when members battled each other with sledgehammers and fire extinguishers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/worldnews/article-1097434/Democracy-South-Korean-style-MPs-blasted-extinguishers-trying-break-Parliament-hoses-sledgehammers.html|title=Democracy, South Korean-style: MPs blasted with fire extinguishers after trying to break into Parliament with hoses and sledgehammers|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-korea-fight28-2009jan28-story.html|title=South Korea lawmakers: Reaching across the aisle with a sledgehammer|first=By John M.|last=Glionna|website=latimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/southkorea/3832972/South-Korean-politicians-use-fire-extinguishers-against-opposition.html|title=South Korean politicians use fire extinguishers against opposition|date=18 December 2008|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/opinon/2009/06/202_40545.html|title=Hall of Violence|date=2 March 2009|publisher=}}</ref> Images of the melee were broadcast around the world.\n\n==History==\n[[File:NC of SK.jpg|thumb|left|South Korean National Assembly in the 1980s]]\n{{Politics of South Korea}}\n\n===First Republic===\n{{See also|First Republic of South Korea}}\nElections for the assembly were held under UN supervision<ref>[http://korea50.army.mil/history/factsheets/overview.shtml Setting the Stage<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070716130844/http://korea50.army.mil/history/factsheets/overview.shtml |date=16 July 2007 }}</ref> on 10 May 1948. The [[First Republic of South Korea]] was established on 17 July 1948<ref>[http://www.oefre.unibe.ch/law/icl/ks__indx.html ICL \u2013 South Korea Index<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061213041106/http://www.oefre.unibe.ch/law/icl/ks__indx.html |date=13 December 2006 }}</ref> when the constitution of the First Republic was established by the Assembly. The Assembly also had the job of electing the [[President of South Korea|President]], and elected anti-communist [[Syngman Rhee]] as President on 10 May 1948.\n\nUnder the first constitution, the National Assembly was unicameral. Under the second and third constitutions, the National Assembly became bicameral and consisted of the [[House of Commons (South Korea)|House of Commons]] and the [[Senate (South Korea)|Senate]], but actually unicameral with the House of Commons because the House of Commons could not pass a bill to establish the Senate.\n\n{{legend2|{{Conservative (South Korea)/meta/color}}|Conservative|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|{{Liberal (South Korea)/meta/color}}|Liberal|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|{{Progressive (South Korea)/meta/color}}|Progressive|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n{{legend2|lightgreen|majority|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|lightyellow|plurality only|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|lightpink|largest minority|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:96%; text-align:center;\"\n! National<br />Assembly\n! colspan=\"2\"| Majority<br />Party\n! Majority<br />Leader\n! Seats\n! Speaker\n! Seats\n! Minority<br />Leaders\n! colspan=\"2\"| Minority<br />Parties