{"title_page": "2019 Arkansas River floods", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox flood\n| name       = 2019 Arkansas River floods\n| image      = Arkansas River flooding May 27 2019 MODIS labeled.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| alt        = <!--(short description of image per [[WP:ALT]])-->\n| caption    = [[MODIS]] satellite image showing flooding along the Arkansas River on May&nbsp;27\n| duration   = {{start date|2019|05|18}}\u2013{{end date|2019|06|14}}\n| damages    = $3&nbsp;billion (2019 [[United States dollar|USD]]){{#tag:ref|All damage totals in 2019&nbsp;[[United States dollars]] unless otherwise noted.|group=note}}\n| fatalities = 5&nbsp;total\n| affected   = Eastern [[Oklahoma]], western [[Arkansas]], southeastern [[Kansas]], southwestern [[Missouri]]\n}}\nBetween May and June&nbsp;2019, an extended sequence of heavy rainfall events over the [[South Central United States]] caused historic flooding along the [[Arkansas River]] and its tributaries. Major and record river flooding occurred primarily in northeastern [[Oklahoma]], and the elevated flows continued downstream into [[Arkansas]] where the caused additional inundation. Antecedent soil moisture levels and water levels in lakes and streams were already high from previous rains, priming the region for significant runoff and flooding. The prolonged combination of high atmospheric moisture and a sustained weather pattern extending across the [[continental United States]] led to frequent high-yield rainfall over the Arkansas River watershed. The overarching weather pattern allowed moisture levels to quickly rebound after each sequential rainfall episode. With soils already saturated, the excess precipitation became [[surface runoff]] and flowed into the already elevated lakes and streams. Most rainfall occurred in connection with a series of [[Tornado outbreak sequence of May 2019|repeated thunderstorms]] between May&nbsp;19\u201321, which was then followed by additional rains that kept streams within [[flood stage]].\n\nFlooding in the Arkansas River basin caused an estimated $3&nbsp;billion in damage and killed five people. The initial episode of torrential rainfall prompted the issuance of two [[flash flood warning|flash flood emergencies]] for several counties in eastern Oklahoma on May&nbsp;20, with numerous water rescues occurring during the event. Several reservoirs in eastern Oklahoma filled over capacity and reached record levels, requiring large releases of water to alleviate the dangerously high storage of water. Repeated rains continued to keep the reservoirs filled, necessitating further releases of water. The prolonged release of reservoir water combined with surface runoff to cause near-record to record flooding along the Arkansas River. Parts of the [[Tulsa metropolitan area]] and entire towns near swollen rivers were inundated. In some locations the Arkansas River backed upstream into its tributaries, causing major flooding. The bulge of elevated water levels that began in Oklahoma flowed downstream into Arkansas by May&nbsp;23, breaching three levees along the Arkansas River and inundating numerous buildings. In [[Van Buren, Arkansas|Van Buren]], the flood was assessed by the [[United States Geological Survey]] as a [[return period|1 in 200 year flood event]].{{#tag:ref|The return period refers to the probability of a given flood peak occurring over a period of time. A 100-year event, by definition, has a 1% chance happening in a specific year, although it is possible for such events to happen more than once over 100&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />|group=note}} Federal [[Stafford Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Act|major disaster declarations]] and statewide [[state of emergency|states of emergencies]] were declared for Oklahoma and Arkansas.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n[[File:Arkansas river basin map.png|thumb|left|300px|Map of the Arkansas River basin]]\nAcross the [[continental United States]], 12&nbsp;months preceding May&nbsp;2019 were the wettest in 124&nbsp;years of recordkeeping,<ref name=\"EOFlooding\">{{cite web |title=Flooding Along the Arkansas River |url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/145108/flooding-along-the-arkansas-river |website=[[NASA Earth Observatory|Earth Observatory]] |publisher=[[NASA Goddard Space Flight Center]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |date=May 30, 2019}}</ref> in line with a [[Physical impacts of climate change|longer-term trend of increasing precipitation and heavy rainfall events]] due to [[climate change]].<ref name=\"EOSoggySoils\">{{cite web |title=Record-Setting Precipitation Leaves U.S. Soils Soggy |url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/145101/record-setting-precipitation-leaves-us-soils-soggy |website=Earth Observatory |publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> [[Soil moisture]] and water levels in lakes and streams across the [[Great Plains#Southern Great Plains|Southern Plains]] were high heading into May. During the latter half of May&nbsp;2019, an active weather pattern became established over the United States, characterized by the juxtaposition of pronounced [[trough (meteorology)|trough]] over the western half of the country and [[subtropical ridge|ridging]] over the southern and southeastern United States.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> This configuration was favorable for frequent rainfalls over the Southern Plains,<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> placing the [[jet stream]] in a position to draw the warm and moist [[air mass]] atop the [[Gulf of Mexico]] northward.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}} Atmospheric moisture was also atypically high during this period, with [[precipitable water]] content persisting between {{cvt|1.5|\u2013|2|in|mm}}, thereby increasing the precipitation potential of each individual shower and thunderstorm.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\">{{cite report|last1=Piltz |first1=Steven F. |last2=McGavcock|first2=Nicole|title=Monthly Report of River and Flood Conditions |url=https://www.weather.gov/media/tsa/e5/e5may19.pdf |publisher=National Weather Service Tulsa, OK |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma |format=PDF |date=May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SE831194\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Tulsa County, OK |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=831194 |website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref> The first rains associated with the flood occurred on May&nbsp;18, when a [[squall line]] moved across eastern Oklahoma and western Arkansas. Additional showers immediately preceding and succeeding the squall enhanced rainfall totals.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} \n\nBetween May&nbsp;20\u201321, another storm system moved from the [[Rocky Mountains]] into Oklahoma. A [[warm front]] associated with the complex moved across the state during the daytime on May&nbsp;20, followed by a [[cold front]] that swept eastwards across the state between the evening of May&nbsp;20 into the following morning. This produced several episodes of [[severe thunderstorm]]s enhanced by the confluence of the moist, warm, and [[atmospheric instability|unstable]] airmass ahead of the storm system.<ref name=\"SE824437\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Osage County, OK |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=824437|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref> Initially isolated thunderstorms over eastern Oklahoma coalesced into a line, with new storm cells [[training (meteorology)|training]] repeatedly tracking over the same locations as the line slowly moved east. The complex combined with another cluster of storms over central Oklahoma and tracked northeast, causing further rainfall before dissipating. Another squall line was generated by the storm system as the associated [[cold-core low|upper-level low]] moved into Kansas, sweeping through eastern Oklahoma and northwestern Arkansas on the morning of May&nbsp;21 with its heaviest rains overlapping the same areas affected by the earlier storms.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} Most of the rainfall associated with the flood event occurred during a 36-hour period between May&nbsp;19\u201321 in a region spanning from northeastern Oklahoma to northwestern Arkansas.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\">{{cite report|last1=Lewis |first1=Jason M. |last2=Trevisan |first2=Adam R. |title=Peak Streamflow and Stages at Selected Streamgages on the Arkansas River in Oklahoma and Arkansas, May to June 2019 |url=https://pubs.usgs.gov/of/2019/1129/ofr20191129.pdf |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Reston, Virginia |format=PDF |doi=10.3133/ofr20191129|ISSN=2331-1258|id=U.S. Geological Survey Open-File Report 2019\u20131129 |date=2019}}</ref>{{rp|1}}  Lesser rainfall events followed the primary rainfall event, keeping rivers in flood stage into June&nbsp;2019.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}} On May&nbsp;22, the approach of an upper-level trough allowed moisture levels to quickly rebound in the wake of the previous day's storms. Several thunderstorms rapidly organized along [[Interstate 44]] in Oklahoma during the late afternoon and moved towards the east-northeast. A [[advection|surge of warm air]] and strengthening [[Low level jet|low-level winds]] during the nighttime hours instigated additional storm formation over the same areas.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}}\n\nTwo rounds of showers and thunderstorms affected eastern Oklahoma and the [[Ozarks]] between May&nbsp;24\u201325, reaping a moist atmosphere characterized by precipitable water levels at least two [[standard deviation]]s above normal over north-central Oklahoma and south-central Kansas. Widespread {{cvt|1.5|\u2013|4|in|mm}} rainfalls occurred across the upper Arkansas River basin.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|30}} The dominant trough over the western United States persisted, maintaining a southwesterly wind across the Southern Plains along which storms would travel. In the pre-dawn hours of May&nbsp;26, a [[bow echo]] tracked across Oklahoma into Kansas, primarily affecting areas north of [[Interstate 40]] and the [[Tulsa metropolitan area]] with severe weather and {{cvt|1|\u2013|3|in|mm}} of rainfall. Two more periods of rainfall occurred on May&nbsp;26, producing {{cvt|0.5|\u2013|3|in|mm}} of rainfall along the Kansas\u2013Oklahoma border.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|31}} More rain fell ahead of a slow-moving cold front between May&nbsp;28\u201330 over Oklahoma and Arkansas, with localized totals of {{cvt|2|\u2013|4|in|mm}}; this event was concentrated further southeast of the earlier rains, primarily affecting southeastern and east-central Oklahoma and northwestern Arkansas.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|34}}\n\n==Impact and aftermath==\n{{see also|Tornado outbreak sequence of May 2019}}\n[[File:Flooding at Muskogee confluence May 31 2019.png|thumb|300px|alt=Aerial view of flooding|Flooding at the confluence of the Arkansas, Neosho, and Verdigris rivers in Muskogee, Oklahoma]]\nThe [[National Centers for Environmental Information]] (NCEI) estimated that flooding in the Arkansas River basin caused $3&nbsp;billion in damage, with a 95% [[confidence interval]] between $1.8\u2013$5.3&nbsp;billion. Five people were killed by the floods.<ref name=\"BillionDollarEvents\">{{cite web |title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events/US/2019 |website=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters |publisher=NOAA National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina |date=2020}}</ref> Between May&nbsp;18\u201330, {{cvt|6|\u2013|16|in|mm}} of rain fell along and northwest of a line from [[Okmulgee, Oklahoma]] to near [[Bentonville, Arkansas]], with {{cvt|3|\u2013|5|in|mm}} of rain occurring at points southeast of this region.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> The rains also extended into southern [[Kansas]] and southwestern [[Missouri]].<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|35}} Rainfall totals of {{cvt|10|\u2013|16|in|mm}} were widespread across southern [[Kansas]] and northern Oklahoma.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> Some areas of Oklahoma received {{cvt|22|in|mm}} of rainfall in total, representing the highest accumulated rainfall during the flood event.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} [[Talala, Oklahoma]], recorded more than twice its average May rainfall in a single week.<ref name=\"SoundingFloodSirens\">{{cite news |last1=Cappucci |first1=Matthew |title=A week of relentless rain is terrorizing Oklahoma, swallowing homes and sounding flood sirens |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2019/05/24/week-relentless-rain-is-terrorizing-oklahoma-swallowing-homes-sounding-flood-sirens/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |publisher=The Washington Post |date=May 24, 2019 |location=Washington, D.C.}} {{subscription required}}</ref> While most of the contributing rains fell between May&nbsp;19\u201321, river flood crests occurred between May&nbsp;26\u2013June&nbsp;4.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} Within the warning region of the [[National Weather Service Tulsa, Oklahoma|National Weather Service office in Tulsa, Oklahoma]], at least one river was at flood stage between the evening of May&nbsp;20 and the morning of June&nbsp;13.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|20}} Kansas and [[Missouri]] ultimately had their wettest Mays on record, with Oklahoma experiencing its second-highest May totals and Arkansas recording its ninth-highest.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}}\n\n===Oklahoma===\nSix [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] reservoirs in northeastern Oklahoma set records for water volume during the floods: [[Birch Lake (Oklahoma)|Birch Lake]], [[Lake Hudson (Oklahoma)|Lake Hudson]], [[Kaw Lake]], [[Keystone Lake]], [[Oologah Lake]], and [[Skiatook Lake]]. The [[National Weather Service]] cataloged 31&nbsp;river flood events at 22&nbsp;river forecast points in eastern Oklahoma. Two of these instances were at [[Flood stage#Record Flood Stage|record flood stage]], including the Arkansas River near [[Ponca City, Oklahoma|Ponca City]]; 25 of the 31&nbsp;flood events were classified as [[Flood stage#major flood stage|major floods]]. Several river gauges recorded flooding conditions lasting for more than a week; the longest flood was documented along the Arkansas River near [[Muskogee, Oklahoma|Muskogee]], which remained above [[flood stage]] for 22&nbsp;days and 5&nbsp;hours.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> Numerous [[List of state highways in Oklahoma|state]] and [[United States Numbered Highway System|U.S. highways]] were closed by the [[Oklahoma Department of Transportation]] at various points due to flooding.<ref name=\"UpdateOK72\">{{cite news |title=Update: Oklahoma 72 from East 201st South near Coweta is open; road closures remain elsewhere |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/state-and-regional/today-s-list-of-highway-closures-and-city-of-tulsa/article_6e980686-89ea-5cca-87b1-71079f7a0299.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |agency=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Over a thousand homes were affected by flooding associated with the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"MultiyearProcess\">{{cite news |last1=Grimwood|first1=Harrison|title='A multiyear process for recovery': Flooding continues as Corps increases Keystone Dam output  |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/local/a-multiyear-process-for-recovery-flooding-continues-as-corps-increases/article_b0e22907-37c1-545e-b04a-b25fc3f30c56.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |agency=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Throughout the state, 4&nbsp;people were killed and 87&nbsp;others were injured.<ref name=\"NeighborhoodsLeveeTest\">{{cite news |title=Oklahoma neighborhoods prepare to evacuate as flooding tests levees |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-oklahoma-flooding-20190525-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=May 25, 2019 |location=Los Angeles, California}}</ref><ref name=\"SE831194\" /><ref name=\"SE830730\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Lincoln County, OK|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=830730|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref><ref name=\"SE830720\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Payne County, OK|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=830720|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the primary flood event, water levels along the Arkansas River at Muskogee had remained just below flood stage. The first round of rainfall on May&nbsp;18 produced widespread totals of {{cvt|0.5|\u2013|1|in|mm}} across eastern Oklahoma and western Arkansas, raising the Arkansas River into flood stage.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} With the threat of flood and a [[tornado outbreak]] looming, many events scheduled for the evening of May&nbsp;20 were cancelled or rescheduled.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} That evening, heavy and persistent rainfall from a slow-moving line of thunderstorms caused widespread [[flash flooding]] primarily along a line from [[Bristow, Oklahoma|Bristow]] to [[Miami, Oklahoma|Miami]] and areas northwest, submerging roadways and leading to several evacuations and water rescues. At 11:14&nbsp;p.m. CDT on May&nbsp;20, National Weather Service Tulsa issued a [[Flash flood warning|flash flood emergency]] for southern [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage]], [[Pawnee County, Oklahoma|Pawnee]], northwestern [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma]], and [[Washington County, Oklahoma|Washington]] counties. Another flash flood emergency was issued 30&nbsp;minutes later for western [[Mayes County, Oklahoma|Mayes]], southeastern Osage, [[Rogers County, Oklahoma|Rogers]], northern [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner]], and Tulsa counties.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} \n\nBy 7&nbsp;a.m. CDT on May&nbsp;21 between {{cvt|4|\u2013|8|in|mm}} had fallen across north-central and northeastern Oklahoma. A station in [[Pawnee, Oklahoma|Pawnee]] recorded the highest 24-hour total with {{cvt|9.52|in|mm}}.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} More than {{cvt|6|in|mm}} of rain fell in a 24-hour period of May&nbsp;21 over parts of [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] and [[Stillwater, Oklahoma|Stillwater]].<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}} Atop saturated soils, the rainfall became [[surface runoff]] which flowed into streams and the United States Army Corps of Engineers's [[reservoir|flood control pools]]. Flooding affected the watersheds of the upper Arkansas, [[Neosho River|Neosho]], and [[Verdigris River|Verdigris]] rivers, which all reach a [[confluence]] in Muskogee.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} The submarine [[USS Batfish (SS-310)]] at the [[Muskogee War Memorial Park]] briefly took on water due to the swollen Arkansas River.<ref name=\"USSBatfish\">{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Efforts Underway To Protect USS Batfish In Muskogee Flooding |url=https://www.newson6.com/story/40525838/uss-batfish-floats-again-in-muskogee-flooding |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=NewsOn6.com |publisher=Griffin Communications |date=May 24, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Flash flooding and broader areal flooding caused [[Bird Creek]] to inundate areas around [[Skiatook, Oklahoma|Skiatook]]. Near [[Avant, Oklahoma|Avant]], the creek rose {{cvt|30.5|ft|m}} in 12&nbsp;hours, cresting at {{cvt|36.52|ft|m}} on the morning of May&nbsp;21. Water releases were necessary to relieve dangerously high lake levels in the absence of surcharge capacity, worsening flooding downstream of [[Pensacola Dam]] and [[Lake Hudson (Oklahoma)#Robert S. Kerr Dam structure|Kerr Dam]].<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} Residents were forced to evacuate [[Webbers Falls, Oklahoma|Webbers Falls]] on May&nbsp;22 as the flooded river began to overtake homes.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\">{{cite web |title=NWS Little Rock, AR - Historic Flooding in 2019 (Arkansas River/Tropical Storm Barry) |url=https://www.weather.gov/lzk/flood2019.htm |website=Historic Events in Arkansas |publisher=National Weather Service Little Rock, AR |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Little Rock, Arkansas}}</ref> A voluntary evacuation was declared for residents of [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]] living within the 100-year floodplain near the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"BrokenArrowEvacuations\">{{cite news |title=City Of Broken Arrow Urges Voluntary Evacuations In 100-Year Flood Plain |url=https://www.newson6.com/story/40516132/broken-arrow-residents-near-arkansas-river-urged-to-take-flooding-precautions |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=NewsOn6.com |agency= |publisher=Griffin Communications |date=May 23, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Flash flooding following {{cvt|6|in|mm}} of rain in [[El Reno, Oklahoma|El Reno]] led to six water rescues.<ref name=\"OklahomaFloodingPeopleTrapped\">{{cite news |last1=Villareal |first1=Mireya |title=Oklahoma flooding leaves people trapped by rising waters |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oklahoma-flooding-leaves-people-trapped-by-rising-waters-2019-05-21/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=CBS News |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |date=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Arkansas River flood at Webbers Falls, May 31 2019.png|thumb|left|Flooding in Webbers Falls, Oklahoma]]\nThe water levels in Kaw, Keystone, and Oologah lakes began to exceed their flood control limits after the May&nbsp;22\u201323 rainfall. Kaw Lake's depth reached 112.16% of its flood pool capacity on May&nbsp;24, causing the associated surcharge pool to completely fill; similar circumstances were present at Keystone and Ooologah lakes, prompting releases of the excess water downstream.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} Releases at the [[Keystone Lake#Dam construction details|Keystone Dam]] into the Arkansas River reached flow rates more than double the flow rates at [[Niagara Falls]].<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /> The Keystone Dam water release was its second largest on record and contributed to the Arkansas River reaching major flood stage in Tulsa during the afternoon of May&nbsp;23.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} Tulsa city officials recommended that people living west of [[Downtown Tulsa]] evacuate in acknowledgement of the old age of the levees protecting the city from the swollen Arkansas River. The town of [[Braggs, Oklahoma|Braggs]], approximately {{cvt|55|mi|km}} northeast of Tulsa, lost power and was fully enveloped by floodwaters.<ref name=\"NeighborhoodsLeveeTest\" /> Widespread flooding occurred across numerous streams as the May&nbsp;22\u201323 rains further exacerbated the elevated river stages from the earlier extreme rainfall event. The entire stretch of the Arkansas River within the warning region of National Weather Service Tulsa\u2014spanning {{cvt|396|mi|km}}\u2013experienced a major flood. All barge traffic along the [[McClellan\u2013Kerr Arkansas River Navigation System]] was suspended on May&nbsp;22. Two unoccupied barges tethered together broke free from their moorings at the [[Port of Muskogee]] that evening, haphazardly floating downstream. They were briefly obstructed by rocks before continuing downstream as the river rose, eventually colliding with the [[lock (water navigation)|lock]] and dam system at [[Webbers Falls Lake]] and capsizing at around noon on May&nbsp;23.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} All residents in [[Moffett, Oklahoma|Moffett]] along the Arkansas River were ordered to evacuate on May&nbsp;24.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\">{{cite news |last1=Bryan |first1=Max |title=Arkansas River flood No. 1 story of 2019 |url=https://www.swtimes.com/news/20191231/arkansas-river-flood-no-1-story-of-2019 |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Times Record |publisher=Gannett Co., Inc |date=December 31, 2019 |location=Fort Smith, Arkansas}}</ref> The Neosho River crested at {{cvt|25.5|ft|m}} in Miami on May&nbsp;24. Southern parts of the city were submerged, with some roads under {{cvt|4|ft|m}} underwater. Thirty water rescues took place in Miami during the floods.<ref name=\"MiamiSurvivalMode\">{{cite news |last1=Stogsdill |first1=Sheila |title=Miami police crack down on road barricade violations while residents go into 'survival mode' amid unrelenting flooding |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/miami-police-crack-down-on-road-barricade-violations-while-residents/article_8d41f1f7-6321-5626-81bb-05ad56b3031d.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |publisher=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 25, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref>\n\nBy May&nbsp;25, the excess surface runoff flowing into the Arkansas River caused the river to begin piling water upstream into its tributaries. The [[Poteau River]] flooded in this manner near [[Panama, Oklahoma|Panama]] and rises were documented upstream to [[Lake Wister]]. Lake Hudson reached a record height on May&nbsp;24 despite concurrent water releases at Kerr Dam. [[Fort Gibson Dam|Fort Gibson Lake]] crested a day later while excess water was being released via Fort Gibson Dam.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|30}} Widespread runoff from the May&nbsp;26 caused Keystone Lake to rise further, reaching a record elevation of {{cvt|757.19|ft|m}} two days later. A second water release from the dam took place on May&nbsp;29, causing a {{cvt|23.41|ft|m|adj=on}}-crest on the Arkansas River in Tulsa; this was the river's second highest crest in the city on record.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} A neighborhood on the western side of [[Sand Springs, Oklahoma|Sand Springs]] were flooded by both water releases from Keystone Lake.<ref name=\"SandSpringWestEvacuate\">{{cite news |last1=Canfield |first1=Kevin |title=Angry residents west of Sand Springs say they didn't have enough warning to evacuate |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/local/angry-residents-west-of-sand-springs-say-they-didn-t/article_aa3b9d02-484f-5b07-b51c-6653e780ae1d.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |publisher=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 28, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Homes in southern Tulsa and [[Bixby, Oklahoma|Bixby]] were also inundated. Two people drowned in Tulsa on May&nbsp;26 to the floodwaters along the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> Other locations along the Arkansas River downstream also set records or near-records for river heights. In addition to Keystone, six other lakes crested between May&nbsp;25\u201327, with three setting new pools of record. Releases from Oologah Lake caused major flooding along the Verdigris River near [[Claremore, Oklahoma|Claremore]].<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|31}} Saturated soils and high river levels quickened the development of flash flooding, leading to the issuance of a flash flood emergency for northwestern [[Muskogee County, Oklahoma|Muskogee]], central [[Okfuskee County, Oklahoma|Okfuskee]], and [[Okmulgee County, Oklahoma|Okmulgee]] counties on May&nbsp;29 following another round of heavy rainfall. Although some lakes and streams had begun to recede, the new rains caused water levels to rise once more along the Arkansas River and Poteau River. Birch Lake exceeded its flood control pool for a second time while [[Lake Eufaula (Oklahoma)|Lake Eufaula]] did so for its first time, requiring another water release into the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|35}}\n\n[[Governor of Oklahoma]] [[Kevin Stitt]] declared a [[state of emergency]] for all 77&nbsp;counties on May&nbsp;24, augmenting an earlier state of emergency that had been in place for 52&nbsp;counties since the beginning of the month. [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]] approved a [[Stafford Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Act|Major Disaster Declaration]] for Oklahoma on June&nbsp;1 with an incident period from May&nbsp;7\u2013June&nbsp;9.<ref name=\"NWS TSA ClimateHydrology\">{{cite web |title=May 2019 Climate and Hydrology Summary |url=https://www.weather.gov/tsa/climo_summary_may2019 |publisher=National Weather Service Tulsa, OK |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> [[United States National Guard]] helicopters dropped {{cvt|4000|lb|kg}} sandbags to reinforce strained levees.<ref name=\"CommunitiesScramble\">{{cite news |title=Arkansas River communities scramble to hold historic flooding at bay |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/arkansas-river-flooding-fort-smith-floods-threatening-thousands-tulsa-oklahoma/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=CBS News |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The City of Tulsa began allowing flood-stricken evacuees back to their homes on June&nbsp;1, following over a week of displacement.<ref name=\"ReturningHomeInSomeAreas\">{{cite news |title='It has been quite a week and a half': Residents returning home in some areas |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/local/it-has-been-quite-a-week-and-a-half-residents/article_59dfa6bc-f7d7-58ed-8546-9bda2ae99830.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |publisher=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=June 1, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref>\n\n===Arkansas===\n[[File:Arkansas River Flooding at North Little Rock May 2019.jpg|thumb|alt=A river overflowing its banks|Flooding in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]]]]\nThe swollen streams in northeastern Oklahoma led to record flows in Arkansas throughout the [[Arkansas River Valley]] as the elevated bulge of water moved downstream, combining both surface runoff and large releases of water from upstream dams.<ref name=\"SE848643\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Sebastian County, AR |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=848643|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref> On May&nbsp;22, officials from the Army Corps of Engineers warned of potentially record-breaking flood levels and flow rates in Arkansas, and urged people in floodplains and other flood-prone areas to relocate livestock and other belongings.<ref name=\"OfficialsWarnPotentiallyHistoric\">{{cite news |last1=Rddad |first1=Youssef |title=Officials warn of potentially historic flooding as Arkansas River swells |url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2019/may/22/officials-warn-potential-and-major-flooding-arkans/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette |publisher=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette, Inc. |date=May 22, 2019 |location=Little Rock, Arkansas}}</ref> The floods reached [[Fort Smith, Arkansas|Fort Smith]] along the Arkansas\u2013Oklahoma border on May&nbsp;23.<ref name=\"GovernorSenatorsExpectFEMA\">{{cite news |last1=Bryan |first1=Max |title=Governor, senators expect FEMA assistance for Fort Smith area |url=https://www.swtimes.com/news/20190531/governor-senators-expect-fema-assistance-for-fort-smith-area |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Times Record |publisher=Gannett Co., Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Fort Smith, Arkansas}}</ref> \n\nSix of seven streamgages along the Arkansas River surveyed by the [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) in Arkansas recorded their highest streamflows on record. The flooding was considered a [[return period|1 in 200 year event]] near [[Van Buren, Arkansas]], where the river reached a peak streamflow of {{cvt|570000|ft3/s|m3/s}}.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|7}} The river at Van Buren reached {{cvt|40.79|in|m}}, topping the previous record of {{cvt|38.1|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" /> Water from the Arkansas River backed upstream into [[Lee Creek (Arkansas)|Lee Creek]], causing major flooding.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} At [[Dardanelle, Arkansas|Dardanelle]], the flooding reached magnitudes with return periods exceeding 200&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|7}} At least three levees were breached along the Arkansas River between Fort Smith and [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], with another five sustaining substantial damage.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} The breach of a {{cvt|40|ft|m|adj=on}}-section of levee near Dardanelle in [[Yell County, Arkansas|Yell County]] prompted evacuations, threatening 300\u2013400&nbsp;homes and 5,700&nbsp;people.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /><ref name=\"LeveeNorthLittleRock\">{{cite news |title=Levee in North Little Rock not breached despite earlier report, official says |url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2019/may/31/levee-yell-county-fails-overnight-flash-flood-warn/?breaking |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette |publisher=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette, Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Little Rock, Texas}}</ref> While the homes were ultimately not affected, the flooding significantly impacted adjacent farmland. [[Arkansas Highway 155]] sustained major damage. Other highways were also flooded, including [[Arkansas Highway 22]], where one person died on May&nbsp;28 after circumnavigating a flood barricade. Highway&nbsp;22 remained closed until June&nbsp;4, three days after the Arkansas River initially crested.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /> Parks, homes, and businesses in Fort Smith were overtaken by the river, leaving parts of the city accessible only by boat.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" /><ref name=\"CommunitiesScramble\" /> In total, 500&nbsp;homes in Fort Smith were affected.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" />\n\nEvacuations occurred in [[Faulkner County, Arkansas|Faulkner County]] due to the rise of [[Lake Conway]] and the potential breach of the Lollie Levee. The lake flooded shoreline homes while the Lollie Levee maintained integrity.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /> Mandatory evacuations were also ordered in parts of [[Jefferson County, Arkansas|Jefferson County]].<ref name=\"LeveeNorthLittleRock\" />  On May&nbsp;28, a partition of levee {{cvt|80|ft|m}} wide and {{cvt|12|ft|m}} high in [[Crawford County, Arkansas|Crawford County]] slumped against the rising Arkansas River, threatening 250&nbsp;people in 152&nbsp;residences; the levee remained intact as the river crested on June&nbsp;1.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" /> [[Governor of Arkansas]] [[Asa Hutchinson]] declared a state of emergency for the entire state on May&nbsp;21.<ref name=\"NWS TSA ClimateHydrology\" /> Hutchinson estimated that flooding caused the state economy to lose $23&nbsp;million per day. On May&nbsp;29, $350,000 in state financial assistance was committed towards flood mitigation.<ref name=\"GovernorSenatorsExpectFEMA\" /> President Donald Trump approved a Major Disaster Declaration for Kansas on June&nbsp;8 with an incident period from May&nbsp;21\u2013June&nbsp;14.<ref name=\"NWS TSA ClimateHydrology\" /> The [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] disbursed $9&nbsp;million in recovery fund grants to twelve Arkansas counties in December&nbsp;2019.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" />\n\n{{clear}}\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Weather}}\n*[[Tornado outbreak sequence of May 2019]]&nbsp;\u2013 occurred in conjunction with the flooding\n*Concurrent floods in the United States:\n**[[Mississippi River floods of 2019]]\n**[[2019 Midwestern U.S. floods]]\n*[[2010 Arkansas floods]]&nbsp;\u2013 deadly flash flood along the [[Little Missouri River (Arkansas)|Little Missouri]] and [[Caddo River|Caddo]] rivers\n*[[Climate change in Arkansas]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Floods in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 natural disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 floods]]\n[[Category:2019 in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Arkansas River]]\n[[Category:2019 in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Oklahoma]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox flood\n| name       = 2019 Arkansas River floods\n| image      = Arkansas River flooding May 27 2019 MODIS labeled.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| alt        = <!--(short description of image per [[WP:ALT]])-->\n| caption    = [[MODIS]] satellite image showing flooding along the Arkansas River on May&nbsp;27\n| duration   = {{start date|2019|05|18}}\u2013{{end date|2019|06|14}}\n| damages    = $3&nbsp;billion (2019 [[United States dollar|USD]]){{#tag:ref|All damage totals in 2019&nbsp;[[United States dollars]] unless otherwise noted.|group=note}}\n| fatalities = 5&nbsp;total\n| affected   = Eastern [[Oklahoma]], western [[Arkansas]], southeastern [[Kansas]], southwestern [[Missouri]]\n}}\nBetween May and June&nbsp;2019, an extended sequence of heavy rainfall events over the [[South Central United States]] caused historic flooding along the [[Arkansas River]] and its tributaries. Major and record river flooding occurred primarily in northeastern [[Oklahoma]], and the elevated flows continued downstream into [[Arkansas]] where the caused additional inundation. Antecedent soil moisture levels and water levels in lakes and streams were already high from previous rains, priming the region for significant runoff and flooding. The prolonged combination of high atmospheric moisture and a sustained weather pattern extending across the [[continental United States]] led to frequent high-yield rainfall over the Arkansas River watershed. The overarching weather pattern allowed moisture levels to quickly rebound after each sequential rainfall episode. With soils already saturated, the excess precipitation became [[surface runoff]] and flowed into the already elevated lakes and streams. Most rainfall occurred in connection with a series of [[Tornado outbreak sequence of May 2019|repeated thunderstorms]] between May&nbsp;19\u201321, which was then followed by additional rains that kept streams within [[flood stage]].\n\nFlooding in the Arkansas River basin caused an estimated $3&nbsp;billion in damage and killed five people. The initial episode of torrential rainfall prompted the issuance of two [[flash flood warning|flash flood emergencies]] for several counties in eastern Oklahoma on May&nbsp;20, with numerous water rescues occurring during the event. Several reservoirs in eastern Oklahoma filled over capacity and reached record levels, requiring large releases of water to alleviate the dangerously high storage of water. Repeated rains continued to keep the reservoirs filled, necessitating further releases of water. The prolonged release of reservoir water combined with surface runoff to cause near-record to record flooding along the Arkansas River. Parts of the [[Tulsa metropolitan area]] and entire towns near swollen rivers were inundated. In some locations the Arkansas River backed upstream into its tributaries, causing major flooding. The bulge of elevated water levels that began in Oklahoma flowed downstream into Arkansas by May&nbsp;23, breaching three levees along the Arkansas River and inundating numerous buildings. In [[Van Buren, Arkansas|Van Buren]], the flood was assessed by the [[United States Geological Survey]] as a [[return period|1 in 200 year flood event]].{{#tag:ref|The return period refers to the probability of a given flood peak occurring over a period of time. A 100-year event, by definition, has a 1% chance happening in a specific year, although it is possible for such events to happen more than once over 100&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />|group=note}} Federal [[Stafford Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Act|major disaster declarations]] and statewide [[state of emergency|states of emergencies]] were declared for Oklahoma and Arkansas.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n[[File:Arkansas river basin map.png|thumb|left|300px|Map of the Arkansas River basin]]\nAcross the [[continental United States]], 12&nbsp;months preceding May&nbsp;2019 were the wettest in 124&nbsp;years of recordkeeping,<ref name=\"EOFlooding\">{{cite web |title=Flooding Along the Arkansas River |url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/145108/flooding-along-the-arkansas-river |website=[[NASA Earth Observatory|Earth Observatory]] |publisher=[[NASA Goddard Space Flight Center]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |date=May 30, 2019}}</ref> in line with a [[Physical impacts of climate change|longer-term trend of increasing precipitation and heavy rainfall events]] due to [[climate change]].<ref name=\"EOSoggySoils\">{{cite web |title=Record-Setting Precipitation Leaves U.S. Soils Soggy |url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/145101/record-setting-precipitation-leaves-us-soils-soggy |website=Earth Observatory |publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> [[Soil moisture]] and water levels in lakes and streams across the [[Great Plains#Southern Great Plains|Southern Plains]] were high heading into May. During the latter half of May&nbsp;2019, an active weather pattern became established over the United States, characterized by the juxtaposition of pronounced [[trough (meteorology)|trough]] over the western half of the country and [[subtropical ridge|ridging]] over the southern and southeastern United States.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> This configuration was favorable for frequent rainfalls over the Southern Plains,<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> placing the [[jet stream]] in a position to draw the warm and moist [[air mass]] atop the [[Gulf of Mexico]] northward.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}} Atmospheric moisture was also atypically high during this period, with [[precipitable water]] content persisting between {{cvt|1.5|\u2013|2|in|mm}}, thereby increasing the precipitation potential of each individual shower and thunderstorm.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\">{{cite report|last1=Piltz |first1=Steven F. |last2=McGavcock|first2=Nicole|title=Monthly Report of River and Flood Conditions |url=https://www.weather.gov/media/tsa/e5/e5may19.pdf |publisher=National Weather Service Tulsa, OK |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma |format=PDF |date=May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SE831194\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Tulsa County, OK |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=831194 |website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref> The first rains associated with the flood occurred on May&nbsp;18, when a [[squall line]] moved across eastern Oklahoma and western Arkansas. Additional showers immediately preceding and succeeding the squall enhanced rainfall totals.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} \n\nBetween May&nbsp;20\u201321, another storm system moved from the [[Rocky Mountains]] into Oklahoma. A [[warm front]] associated with the complex moved across the state during the daytime on May&nbsp;20, followed by a [[cold front]] that swept eastwards across the state between the evening of May&nbsp;20 into the following morning. This produced several episodes of [[severe thunderstorm]]s enhanced by the confluence of the moist, warm, and [[atmospheric instability|unstable]] airmass ahead of the storm system.<ref name=\"SE824437\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Osage County, OK |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=824437|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref> Initially isolated thunderstorms over eastern Oklahoma coalesced into a line, with new storm cells [[training (meteorology)|training]] repeatedly tracking over the same locations as the line slowly moved east. The complex combined with another cluster of storms over central Oklahoma and tracked northeast, causing further rainfall before dissipating. Another squall line was generated by the storm system as the associated [[cold-core low|upper-level low]] moved into Kansas, sweeping through eastern Oklahoma and northwestern Arkansas on the morning of May&nbsp;21 with its heaviest rains overlapping the same areas affected by the earlier storms.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} Most of the rainfall associated with the flood event occurred during a 36-hour period between May&nbsp;19\u201321 in a region spanning from northeastern Oklahoma to northwestern Arkansas.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\">{{cite report|last1=Lewis |first1=Jason M. |last2=Trevisan |first2=Adam R. |title=Peak Streamflow and Stages at Selected Streamgages on the Arkansas River in Oklahoma and Arkansas, May to June 2019 |url=https://pubs.usgs.gov/of/2019/1129/ofr20191129.pdf |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Reston, Virginia |format=PDF |doi=10.3133/ofr20191129|ISSN=2331-1258|id=U.S. Geological Survey Open-File Report 2019\u20131129 |date=2019}}</ref>{{rp|1}}  Lesser rainfall events followed the primary rainfall event, keeping rivers in flood stage into June&nbsp;2019.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}} On May&nbsp;22, the approach of an upper-level trough allowed moisture levels to quickly rebound in the wake of the previous day's storms. Several thunderstorms rapidly organized along [[Interstate 44]] in Oklahoma during the late afternoon and moved towards the east-northeast. A [[advection|surge of warm air]] and strengthening [[Low level jet|low-level winds]] during the nighttime hours instigated additional storm formation over the same areas.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}}\n\nTwo rounds of showers and thunderstorms affected eastern Oklahoma and the [[Ozarks]] between May&nbsp;24\u201325, reaping a moist atmosphere characterized by precipitable water levels at least two [[standard deviation]]s above normal over north-central Oklahoma and south-central Kansas. Widespread {{cvt|1.5|\u2013|4|in|mm}} rainfalls occurred across the upper Arkansas River basin.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|30}} The dominant trough over the western United States persisted, maintaining a southwesterly wind across the Southern Plains along which storms would travel. In the pre-dawn hours of May&nbsp;26, a [[bow echo]] tracked across Oklahoma into Kansas, primarily affecting areas north of [[Interstate 40]] and the [[Tulsa metropolitan area]] with severe weather and {{cvt|1|\u2013|3|in|mm}} of rainfall. Two more periods of rainfall occurred on May&nbsp;26, producing {{cvt|0.5|\u2013|3|in|mm}} of rainfall along the Kansas\u2013Oklahoma border.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|31}} More rain fell ahead of a slow-moving cold front between May&nbsp;28\u201330 over Oklahoma and Arkansas, with localized totals of {{cvt|2|\u2013|4|in|mm}}; this event was concentrated further southeast of the earlier rains, primarily affecting southeastern and east-central Oklahoma and northwestern Arkansas.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|34}}\n\n==Impact and aftermath==\n{{see also|Tornado outbreak sequence of May 2019}}\n[[File:Flooding at Muskogee confluence May 31 2019.png|thumb|300px|alt=Aerial view of flooding|Flooding at the confluence of the Arkansas, Neosho, and Verdigris rivers in Muskogee, Oklahoma]]\nThe [[National Centers for Environmental Information]] (NCEI) estimated that flooding in the Arkansas River basin caused $3&nbsp;billion in damage, with a 95% [[confidence interval]] between $1.8\u2013$5.3&nbsp;billion. Five people were killed by the floods.<ref name=\"BillionDollarEvents\">{{cite web |title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events/US/2019 |website=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters |publisher=NOAA National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina |date=2020}}</ref> Between May&nbsp;18\u201330, {{cvt|6|\u2013|16|in|mm}} of rain fell along and northwest of a line from [[Okmulgee, Oklahoma]] to near [[Bentonville, Arkansas]], with {{cvt|3|\u2013|5|in|mm}} of rain occurring at points southeast of this region.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> The rains also extended into southern [[Kansas]] and southwestern [[Missouri]].<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|35}} Rainfall totals of {{cvt|10|\u2013|16|in|mm}} were widespread across southern [[Kansas]] and northern Oklahoma.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> Some areas of Oklahoma received {{cvt|22|in|mm}} of rainfall in total, representing the highest accumulated rainfall during the flood event.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} [[Talala, Oklahoma]], recorded more than twice its average May rainfall in a single week.<ref name=\"SoundingFloodSirens\">{{cite news |last1=Cappucci |first1=Matthew |title=A week of relentless rain is terrorizing Oklahoma, swallowing homes and sounding flood sirens |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2019/05/24/week-relentless-rain-is-terrorizing-oklahoma-swallowing-homes-sounding-flood-sirens/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |publisher=The Washington Post |date=May 24, 2019 |location=Washington, D.C.}} {{subscription required}}</ref> While most of the contributing rains fell between May&nbsp;19\u201321, river flood crests occurred between May&nbsp;26\u2013June&nbsp;4.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} Within the warning region of the [[National Weather Service Tulsa, Oklahoma|National Weather Service office in Tulsa, Oklahoma]], at least one river was at flood stage between the evening of May&nbsp;20 and the morning of June&nbsp;13.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|20}} Kansas and [[Missouri]] ultimately had their wettest Mays on record, with Oklahoma experiencing its second-highest May totals and Arkansas recording its ninth-highest.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}}\n\n===Oklahoma===\nSix [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] reservoirs in northeastern Oklahoma set records for water volume during the floods: [[Birch Lake (Oklahoma)|Birch Lake]], [[Lake Hudson]], [[Kaw Lake]], [[Keystone Lake]], [[Oologah Lake]], and [[Skiatook Lake]]. The [[National Weather Service]] cataloged 31&nbsp;river flood events at 22&nbsp;river forecast points in eastern Oklahoma. Two of these instances were at [[Flood stage#Record Flood Stage|record flood stage]], including the Arkansas River near [[Ponca City, Oklahoma|Ponca City]]; 25 of the 31&nbsp;flood events were classified as [[Flood stage#major flood stage|major floods]]. Several river gauges recorded flooding conditions lasting for more than a week; the longest flood was documented along the Arkansas River near [[Muskogee, Oklahoma|Muskogee]], which remained above [[flood stage]] for 22&nbsp;days and 5&nbsp;hours.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> Numerous [[List of state highways in Oklahoma|state]] and [[United States Numbered Highway System|U.S. highways]] were closed by the [[Oklahoma Department of Transportation]] at various points due to flooding.<ref name=\"UpdateOK72\">{{cite news |title=Update: Oklahoma 72 from East 201st South near Coweta is open; road closures remain elsewhere |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/state-and-regional/today-s-list-of-highway-closures-and-city-of-tulsa/article_6e980686-89ea-5cca-87b1-71079f7a0299.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |agency=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Over a thousand homes were affected by flooding associated with the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"MultiyearProcess\">{{cite news |last1=Grimwood|first1=Harrison|title='A multiyear process for recovery': Flooding continues as Corps increases Keystone Dam output  |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/local/a-multiyear-process-for-recovery-flooding-continues-as-corps-increases/article_b0e22907-37c1-545e-b04a-b25fc3f30c56.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |agency=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Throughout the state, 4&nbsp;people were killed and 87&nbsp;others were injured.<ref name=\"NeighborhoodsLeveeTest\">{{cite news |title=Oklahoma neighborhoods prepare to evacuate as flooding tests levees |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-oklahoma-flooding-20190525-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=May 25, 2019 |location=Los Angeles, California}}</ref><ref name=\"SE831194\" /><ref name=\"SE830730\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Lincoln County, OK|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=830730|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref><ref name=\"SE830720\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Payne County, OK|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=830720|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the primary flood event, water levels along the Arkansas River at Muskogee had remained just below flood stage. The first round of rainfall on May&nbsp;18 produced widespread totals of {{cvt|0.5|\u2013|1|in|mm}} across eastern Oklahoma and western Arkansas, raising the Arkansas River into flood stage.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} With the threat of flood and a [[tornado outbreak]] looming, many events scheduled for the evening of May&nbsp;20 were cancelled or rescheduled.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} That evening, heavy and persistent rainfall from a slow-moving line of thunderstorms caused widespread [[flash flooding]] primarily along a line from [[Bristow, Oklahoma|Bristow]] to [[Miami, Oklahoma|Miami]] and areas northwest, submerging roadways and leading to several evacuations and water rescues. At 11:14&nbsp;p.m. CDT on May&nbsp;20, National Weather Service Tulsa issued a [[Flash flood warning|flash flood emergency]] for southern [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage]], [[Pawnee County, Oklahoma|Pawnee]], northwestern [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma]], and [[Washington County, Oklahoma|Washington]] counties. Another flash flood emergency was issued 30&nbsp;minutes later for western [[Mayes County, Oklahoma|Mayes]], southeastern Osage, [[Rogers County, Oklahoma|Rogers]], northern [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner]], and Tulsa counties.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|23}} \n\nBy 7&nbsp;a.m. CDT on May&nbsp;21 between {{cvt|4|\u2013|8|in|mm}} had fallen across north-central and northeastern Oklahoma. A station in [[Pawnee, Oklahoma|Pawnee]] recorded the highest 24-hour total with {{cvt|9.52|in|mm}}.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} More than {{cvt|6|in|mm}} of rain fell in a 24-hour period of May&nbsp;21 over parts of [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] and [[Stillwater, Oklahoma|Stillwater]].<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|4}} Atop saturated soils, the rainfall became [[surface runoff]] which flowed into streams and the United States Army Corps of Engineers's [[reservoir|flood control pools]]. Flooding affected the watersheds of the upper Arkansas, [[Neosho River|Neosho]], and [[Verdigris River|Verdigris]] rivers, which all reach a [[confluence]] in Muskogee.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} The submarine [[USS Batfish (SS-310)]] at the [[Muskogee War Memorial Park]] briefly took on water due to the swollen Arkansas River.<ref name=\"USSBatfish\">{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Efforts Underway To Protect USS Batfish In Muskogee Flooding |url=https://www.newson6.com/story/40525838/uss-batfish-floats-again-in-muskogee-flooding |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=NewsOn6.com |publisher=Griffin Communications |date=May 24, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Flash flooding and broader areal flooding caused [[Bird Creek]] to inundate areas around [[Skiatook, Oklahoma|Skiatook]]. Near [[Avant, Oklahoma|Avant]], the creek rose {{cvt|30.5|ft|m}} in 12&nbsp;hours, cresting at {{cvt|36.52|ft|m}} on the morning of May&nbsp;21. Water releases were necessary to relieve dangerously high lake levels in the absence of surcharge capacity, worsening flooding downstream of [[Pensacola Dam]] and [[Lake Hudson (Oklahoma)#Robert S. Kerr Dam structure|Kerr Dam]].<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|24}} Residents were forced to evacuate [[Webbers Falls, Oklahoma|Webbers Falls]] on May&nbsp;22 as the flooded river began to overtake homes.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\">{{cite web |title=NWS Little Rock, AR - Historic Flooding in 2019 (Arkansas River/Tropical Storm Barry) |url=https://www.weather.gov/lzk/flood2019.htm |website=Historic Events in Arkansas |publisher=National Weather Service Little Rock, AR |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Little Rock, Arkansas}}</ref> A voluntary evacuation was declared for residents of [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]] living within the 100-year floodplain near the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"BrokenArrowEvacuations\">{{cite news |title=City Of Broken Arrow Urges Voluntary Evacuations In 100-Year Flood Plain |url=https://www.newson6.com/story/40516132/broken-arrow-residents-near-arkansas-river-urged-to-take-flooding-precautions |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=NewsOn6.com |agency= |publisher=Griffin Communications |date=May 23, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Flash flooding following {{cvt|6|in|mm}} of rain in [[El Reno, Oklahoma|El Reno]] led to six water rescues.<ref name=\"OklahomaFloodingPeopleTrapped\">{{cite news |last1=Villareal |first1=Mireya |title=Oklahoma flooding leaves people trapped by rising waters |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oklahoma-flooding-leaves-people-trapped-by-rising-waters-2019-05-21/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=CBS News |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |date=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Arkansas River flood at Webbers Falls, May 31 2019.png|thumb|left|Flooding in Webbers Falls, Oklahoma]]\nThe water levels in Kaw, Keystone, and Oologah lakes began to exceed their flood control limits after the May&nbsp;22\u201323 rainfall. Kaw Lake's depth reached 112.16% of its flood pool capacity on May&nbsp;24, causing the associated surcharge pool to completely fill; similar circumstances were present at Keystone and Ooologah lakes, prompting releases of the excess water downstream.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} Releases at the [[Keystone Lake#Dam construction details|Keystone Dam]] into the Arkansas River reached flow rates more than double the flow rates at [[Niagara Falls]].<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /> The Keystone Dam water release was its second largest on record and contributed to the Arkansas River reaching major flood stage in Tulsa during the afternoon of May&nbsp;23.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} Tulsa city officials recommended that people living west of [[Downtown Tulsa]] evacuate in acknowledgement of the old age of the levees protecting the city from the swollen Arkansas River. The town of [[Braggs, Oklahoma|Braggs]], approximately {{cvt|55|mi|km}} northeast of Tulsa, lost power and was fully enveloped by floodwaters.<ref name=\"NeighborhoodsLeveeTest\" /> Widespread flooding occurred across numerous streams as the May&nbsp;22\u201323 rains further exacerbated the elevated river stages from the earlier extreme rainfall event. The entire stretch of the Arkansas River within the warning region of National Weather Service Tulsa\u2014spanning {{cvt|396|mi|km}}\u2013experienced a major flood. All barge traffic along the [[McClellan\u2013Kerr Arkansas River Navigation System]] was suspended on May&nbsp;22. Two unoccupied barges tethered together broke free from their moorings at the [[Port of Muskogee]] that evening, haphazardly floating downstream. They were briefly obstructed by rocks before continuing downstream as the river rose, eventually colliding with the [[lock (water navigation)|lock]] and dam system at [[Webbers Falls Lake]] and capsizing at around noon on May&nbsp;23.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} All residents in [[Moffett, Oklahoma|Moffett]] along the Arkansas River were ordered to evacuate on May&nbsp;24.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\">{{cite news |last1=Bryan |first1=Max |title=Arkansas River flood No. 1 story of 2019 |url=https://www.swtimes.com/news/20191231/arkansas-river-flood-no-1-story-of-2019 |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Times Record |publisher=Gannett Co., Inc |date=December 31, 2019 |location=Fort Smith, Arkansas}}</ref> The Neosho River crested at {{cvt|25.5|ft|m}} in Miami on May&nbsp;24. Southern parts of the city were submerged, with some roads under {{cvt|4|ft|m}} underwater. Thirty water rescues took place in Miami during the floods.<ref name=\"MiamiSurvivalMode\">{{cite news |last1=Stogsdill |first1=Sheila |title=Miami police crack down on road barricade violations while residents go into 'survival mode' amid unrelenting flooding |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/miami-police-crack-down-on-road-barricade-violations-while-residents/article_8d41f1f7-6321-5626-81bb-05ad56b3031d.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |publisher=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 25, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref>\n\nBy May&nbsp;25, the excess surface runoff flowing into the Arkansas River caused the river to begin piling water upstream into its tributaries. The [[Poteau River]] flooded in this manner near [[Panama, Oklahoma|Panama]] and rises were documented upstream to [[Lake Wister]]. Lake Hudson reached a record height on May&nbsp;24 despite concurrent water releases at Kerr Dam. [[Fort Gibson Dam|Fort Gibson Lake]] crested a day later while excess water was being released via Fort Gibson Dam.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|30}} Widespread runoff from the May&nbsp;26 caused Keystone Lake to rise further, reaching a record elevation of {{cvt|757.19|ft|m}} two days later. A second water release from the dam took place on May&nbsp;29, causing a {{cvt|23.41|ft|m|adj=on}}-crest on the Arkansas River in Tulsa; this was the river's second highest crest in the city on record.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} A neighborhood on the western side of [[Sand Springs, Oklahoma|Sand Springs]] were flooded by both water releases from Keystone Lake.<ref name=\"SandSpringWestEvacuate\">{{cite news |last1=Canfield |first1=Kevin |title=Angry residents west of Sand Springs say they didn't have enough warning to evacuate |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/local/angry-residents-west-of-sand-springs-say-they-didn-t/article_aa3b9d02-484f-5b07-b51c-6653e780ae1d.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |publisher=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=May 28, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> Homes in southern Tulsa and [[Bixby, Oklahoma|Bixby]] were also inundated. Two people drowned in Tulsa on May&nbsp;26 to the floodwaters along the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"SE831194\" /> Other locations along the Arkansas River downstream also set records or near-records for river heights. In addition to Keystone, six other lakes crested between May&nbsp;25\u201327, with three setting new pools of record. Releases from Oologah Lake caused major flooding along the Verdigris River near [[Claremore, Oklahoma|Claremore]].<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|31}} Saturated soils and high river levels quickened the development of flash flooding, leading to the issuance of a flash flood emergency for northwestern [[Muskogee County, Oklahoma|Muskogee]], central [[Okfuskee County, Oklahoma|Okfuskee]], and [[Okmulgee County, Oklahoma|Okmulgee]] counties on May&nbsp;29 following another round of heavy rainfall. Although some lakes and streams had begun to recede, the new rains caused water levels to rise once more along the Arkansas River and Poteau River. Birch Lake exceeded its flood control pool for a second time while [[Lake Eufaula (Oklahoma)|Lake Eufaula]] did so for its first time, requiring another water release into the Arkansas River.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|35}}\n\n[[Governor of Oklahoma]] [[Kevin Stitt]] declared a [[state of emergency]] for all 77&nbsp;counties on May&nbsp;24, augmenting an earlier state of emergency that had been in place for 52&nbsp;counties since the beginning of the month. [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]] approved a [[Stafford Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Act|Major Disaster Declaration]] for Oklahoma on June&nbsp;1 with an incident period from May&nbsp;7\u2013June&nbsp;9.<ref name=\"NWS TSA ClimateHydrology\">{{cite web |title=May 2019 Climate and Hydrology Summary |url=https://www.weather.gov/tsa/climo_summary_may2019 |publisher=National Weather Service Tulsa, OK |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref> [[United States National Guard]] helicopters dropped {{cvt|4000|lb|kg}} sandbags to reinforce strained levees.<ref name=\"CommunitiesScramble\">{{cite news |title=Arkansas River communities scramble to hold historic flooding at bay |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/arkansas-river-flooding-fort-smith-floods-threatening-thousands-tulsa-oklahoma/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=CBS News |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The City of Tulsa began allowing flood-stricken evacuees back to their homes on June&nbsp;1, following over a week of displacement.<ref name=\"ReturningHomeInSomeAreas\">{{cite news |title='It has been quite a week and a half': Residents returning home in some areas |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/news/local/it-has-been-quite-a-week-and-a-half-residents/article_59dfa6bc-f7d7-58ed-8546-9bda2ae99830.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Tulsa World |publisher=BH Media Group, Inc. |date=June 1, 2019 |location=Tulsa, Oklahoma}}</ref>\n\n===Arkansas===\n[[File:Arkansas River Flooding at North Little Rock May 2019.jpg|thumb|alt=A river overflowing its banks|Flooding in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]]]]\nThe swollen streams in northeastern Oklahoma led to record flows in Arkansas throughout the [[Arkansas River Valley]] as the elevated bulge of water moved downstream, combining both surface runoff and large releases of water from upstream dams.<ref name=\"SE848643\">{{cite report|type=Storm Event|title=Storm Event Report for Flood in Sebastian County, AR |url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=848643|website=Storm Events Database |publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |location=Asheville, North Carolina}}</ref> On May&nbsp;22, officials from the Army Corps of Engineers warned of potentially record-breaking flood levels and flow rates in Arkansas, and urged people in floodplains and other flood-prone areas to relocate livestock and other belongings.<ref name=\"OfficialsWarnPotentiallyHistoric\">{{cite news |last1=Rddad |first1=Youssef |title=Officials warn of potentially historic flooding as Arkansas River swells |url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2019/may/22/officials-warn-potential-and-major-flooding-arkans/ |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette |publisher=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette, Inc. |date=May 22, 2019 |location=Little Rock, Arkansas}}</ref> The floods reached [[Fort Smith, Arkansas|Fort Smith]] along the Arkansas\u2013Oklahoma border on May&nbsp;23.<ref name=\"GovernorSenatorsExpectFEMA\">{{cite news |last1=Bryan |first1=Max |title=Governor, senators expect FEMA assistance for Fort Smith area |url=https://www.swtimes.com/news/20190531/governor-senators-expect-fema-assistance-for-fort-smith-area |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Times Record |publisher=Gannett Co., Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Fort Smith, Arkansas}}</ref> \n\nSix of seven streamgages along the Arkansas River surveyed by the [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) in Arkansas recorded their highest streamflows on record. The flooding was considered a [[return period|1 in 200 year event]] near [[Van Buren, Arkansas]], where the river reached a peak streamflow of {{cvt|570000|ft3/s|m3/s}}.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|7}} The river at Van Buren reached {{cvt|40.79|in|m}}, topping the previous record of {{cvt|38.1|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" /> Water from the Arkansas River backed upstream into [[Lee Creek (Arkansas)|Lee Creek]], causing major flooding.<ref name=\"TSAMonthlyReport\" />{{rp|25}} At [[Dardanelle, Arkansas|Dardanelle]], the flooding reached magnitudes with return periods exceeding 200&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|7}} At least three levees were breached along the Arkansas River between Fort Smith and [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], with another five sustaining substantial damage.<ref name=\"USGSStreamflowReport\" />{{rp|1}} The breach of a {{cvt|40|ft|m|adj=on}}-section of levee near Dardanelle in [[Yell County, Arkansas|Yell County]] prompted evacuations, threatening 300\u2013400&nbsp;homes and 5,700&nbsp;people.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /><ref name=\"LeveeNorthLittleRock\">{{cite news |title=Levee in North Little Rock not breached despite earlier report, official says |url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2019/may/31/levee-yell-county-fails-overnight-flash-flood-warn/?breaking |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette |publisher=Arkansas Democrat-Gazette, Inc. |date=May 31, 2019 |location=Little Rock, Texas}}</ref> While the homes were ultimately not affected, the flooding significantly impacted adjacent farmland. [[Arkansas Highway 155]] sustained major damage. Other highways were also flooded, including [[Arkansas Highway 22]], where one person died on May&nbsp;28 after circumnavigating a flood barricade. Highway&nbsp;22 remained closed until June&nbsp;4, three days after the Arkansas River initially crested.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /> Parks, homes, and businesses in Fort Smith were overtaken by the river, leaving parts of the city accessible only by boat.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" /><ref name=\"CommunitiesScramble\" /> In total, 500&nbsp;homes in Fort Smith were affected.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" />\n\nEvacuations occurred in [[Faulkner County, Arkansas|Faulkner County]] due to the rise of [[Lake Conway]] and the potential breach of the Lollie Levee. The lake flooded shoreline homes while the Lollie Levee maintained integrity.<ref name=\"NWS LZK\" /> Mandatory evacuations were also ordered in parts of [[Jefferson County, Arkansas|Jefferson County]].<ref name=\"LeveeNorthLittleRock\" />  On May&nbsp;28, a partition of levee {{cvt|80|ft|m}} wide and {{cvt|12|ft|m}} high in [[Crawford County, Arkansas|Crawford County]] slumped against the rising Arkansas River, threatening 250&nbsp;people in 152&nbsp;residences; the levee remained intact as the river crested on June&nbsp;1.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" /> [[Governor of Arkansas]] [[Asa Hutchinson]] declared a state of emergency for the entire state on May&nbsp;21.<ref name=\"NWS TSA ClimateHydrology\" /> Hutchinson estimated that flooding caused the state economy to lose $23&nbsp;million per day. On May&nbsp;29, $350,000 in state financial assistance was committed towards flood mitigation.<ref name=\"GovernorSenatorsExpectFEMA\" /> President Donald Trump approved a Major Disaster Declaration for Kansas on June&nbsp;8 with an incident period from May&nbsp;21\u2013June&nbsp;14.<ref name=\"NWS TSA ClimateHydrology\" /> The [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] disbursed $9&nbsp;million in recovery fund grants to twelve Arkansas counties in December&nbsp;2019.<ref name=\"ArkansasFlood1\" />\n\n{{clear}}\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Weather}}\n*[[Tornado outbreak sequence of May 2019]]&nbsp;\u2013 occurred in conjunction with the flooding\n*Concurrent floods in the United States:\n**[[Mississippi River floods of 2019]]\n**[[2019 Midwestern U.S. floods]]\n*[[2010 Arkansas floods]]&nbsp;\u2013 deadly flash flood along the [[Little Missouri River (Arkansas)|Little Missouri]] and [[Caddo River|Caddo]] rivers\n*[[Climate change in Arkansas]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Floods in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 natural disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 floods]]\n[[Category:2019 in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Arkansas River]]\n[[Category:2019 in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Oklahoma]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLake Hudson(link changed toLake Hudson (Oklahoma)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Arkansas_River_floods"}
